Description: Zhang Xiaogang is cherished for his surrealist and symbolic painting style. Often leaning towards a melancholic mood, he employs sepia tones and a figurative composition, inducing a sense of nostalgia. His work often seems to imply disquieting, dreamlike narratives.

Title: Zinaida Serebriakova
Description: Zinaida Serebriakova is recognized for her artwork combining elements of realism and impressionism. She uses painting to achieve vibrant colors and a naturalistic layout. The depicted subjects are typically serene, conveying a peaceful mood to the viewer.

Title: Maximalist
Description: Maximalist art style is characterized by the principle of 'more is more', with chaotic combinations of patterns, rich textures, and bright colors, creating visually overwhelming and energetic work. Often mixed-media, this complex, curated clutter captures styles across Baroque, Rococo, and Pop Art and likened to artists such as Damien Hirst, Yayoi Kusama, and Jeff Koons.

Title: Kurzgesagt
Description: Kurzgesagt, an animation studio, uses a distinct art style that combines simplicity and functionality of minimalism with a bright flat design in their digital animations. Abstract environments illustrated with a flat lighting technique complement the informative mood. The symmetric compositions bring clarity to complex ideas, with Phillip Dettmer being a significant contributor to this approach.

Title: Concept Sheet
Description: The 'Concept Sheet' art style typically involves illustrative 2D digital art often used in character design and storyboarding. It often highlights multiple poses and detailed features of the characters used for film, game, or comic developments. Notable artists working in this manner include Alan Aldridge, Bill Sienkiewicz, Don Maitz, Frank Frazetta, and H.R. Giger.

Title: Jeffery Catherine Jones
Description: Jeffrey Catherine Jones was an American artist and illustrator known for her distinctive style and significant contributions to the fields of fantasy and sciences fiction art. Jones's fantastical works were often characterized by earth tones which helped to evoke an air of mysticism. Her figurative compositions were integral to her comic and book cover creations. Some notable authors Jones collaborated with include Robert E. Howard and Michael Moorcock.

Title: Tatsunoko Production
Description: As a significant animation studio, Tatsunoko Production established a unique art style, prominently onscreen in their Anime and Manga productions, characterized by exaggerated physical features and dynamic action sequences. Notable artists include Ippei Kuri, Kenji Yoshida, and Suzuki Tatsuo.

Title: Alphonso Mucha
Description: Alphonso Mucha, a renowned artist, is recognized for his romantic, nature-inspired art in the style of Art Nouveau and Symbolism. His work, often featuring organic forms, decorative details, and a pastel color scheme, has influenced the likes of Gustav Klimt, René Lalique, Hector Guimard, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, and Louis Comfort Tiffany.

Title: FateZero
Description: The FateZero art style encapsulates anime and manga styles, characterized by detailed character designs and dynamic action scenes set within a vibrant, fantasy environment. The style involves high contrast lighting and digital animation. Artists like Gen Urobuchi, Takashi Takeuchi, Kazuki Nakashima, Muneyuki Kanbe, and Kazuchika Kise have composed similar works.

Title: Iwona Lifsches
Description: Iwona Lifsches, an artist predominantly working in the style of photo-realism and modernism, is known for her artwork that captures the essence of texture and space within a limited monochromatic palette. Her abstract mood contributions have parallels with artists like David Jon Kassan, Jeremy Geddes, Raphaella Spence, Tim Cantor, and Roberto Bernardi.

Title: JoJos Bizarre Adventure
Description: JoJo's Bizarre Adventure is a renowned manga and anime series known for its dynamic and exaggerated art style. The series has a vibrant color palette and makes use of dramatic angles to add intensity to the scenes. Its creator, Hirohiko Araki, has a distinctive art style that has been instrumental in the enduring popularity of the series.

Title: Vicente Romero Redondo
Description: Vicente Romero Redondo is a Spanish artist known for his Impressionistic and Realistic art styles. Most of his works are characterized by warm and clear colors, natural light, and gentle moods. His paintings are often set in serene environments depicting introspective portraits and figures.

Title: Walter Simonson
Description: Walter Simonson is an American comic book artist known for his dynamic and epic art style. Characterized by action-filled scenes set in typical superhero environments, his works are widely praised for their energy, vibrant colors and adventurous mood. His comic book art has a dramatic flair that perfectly complements the epic tales told in the pages of the comics he illustrates.

Title: Street Art
Description: Street Art typically refers to the visual art created in public locations, often unsanctioned, and executed outside of the traditional contexts of the art world. Artists who use the streets for their canvas often create art in order to respond to their social and political environment, with the intent of producing meaningful dialogue.

Title: Urban Art
Description: Urban Art or Street Art is rooted in city cultures and takes forms like murals, graffiti, and stencil works. The pieces may contain colorful images or figurines that evoke social or political commentary. The artworks are typically large-scale and intended for public viewing. Banksy, Shepard Fairey, and JR are famous artists known for their urban art.

Title: Three-dimensional
Description: Three-dimensional art is any artwork that has a height, width, and a depth. This kind of art pieces come in a variety of forms like sculptures, installations, and kinetic arts, which allow viewers to see different aspects of the artwork from different viewpoints.

Title: Painter
Description: A painter is an artist who practices the art of painting, using a brush or other tool to apply pigment to a surface. The focus of painting can be quite diverse, including narrative, figurative, symbolic or abstract representation, and may draw on many genres or styles.

Title: Cubism
Description: Cubism is an early-20th-century avant-garde art movement that revolutionized European painting and sculpture. In Cubist artwork, objects are broken up, analyzed, and re-assembled in an abstracted form instead of being depicted from one viewpoint.

Title: Political
Description: The political art style is often provocative, representing socio-political issues with high-contrast and complex compositions. It is usually seen in urban environments and uses different colors to attract attention. Renowned artists include Banksy, Ai Weiwei, and Frida Kahlo.

Title: Figurative
Description: Figurative art style is characterized by its realistic, balanced, and dramatic approach to representing the human form. Usually expressed through paintings in a studio with natural lighting, it employs realistic color schemes. Michelangelo, Leonardo Da Vinci, and Gustav Klimt are some of its prominent practitioners.

Title: Melancholic
Description: The melancholic art style captures deep emotional states like sadness using dark tones, low-key lighting, and isolated compositions. Often executed in oil, it's associated with Expressionism and Surrealism. Artists such as Pablo Picasso, Edward Hopper, and Vincent Van Gogh are famous for this style.

Title: Comic Artist
Description: Comic Art Style, associated with Cartooning and Manga, features artistic drawing in sequential panels. This style, often created by comic artists (or illustrators), depicts environments with stylistic lighting, a vibrant color palette, and a humorous mood. Stan Lee, Osamu Tezuka, and Herge are key artists in this genre.

Title: Graphic Novels
Description: Graphic Novel Art Style is characterized by its narrative composition, contrasting lighting, and colorful palette, in either fantasy or realistic settings. The medium typically involves drawing, often seen in Manga and Superhero Comics genres. Renowned graphic novel artists include Alan Moore, Neil Gaiman, and Frank Miller.

Title: Comic Art
Description: Comic Art primarily involves styles like Cartoon and sometimes Abstract, and the medium of choice is generally illustration. This art style's heart lies in sequential art – the arrangement of images to narrate a story – and because it caters to multiple genres, the environment, lighting, color, and mood can vary greatly. Pioneers like Stan Lee, Jack Kirby, and Steve Ditko have considerably influenced the Comic Art style.

Title: Satirical
Description: Satirical Art Style utilizes irony and humor to criticize or mock something. It frequently exaggerates features to emphasize its point and is often seen in illustrations. Notable artists include Picasso, Banksy, and George Grosz.

Title: Cartoonish
Description: Cartoonish Art Style is characterized by exaggerated proportions, bold colors, and fantasy-inspired settings. It is often associated with whimsical moods projected through animated media. Notable cartoon artists include Walt Disney, Charles Schulz, and Hayao Miyazaki.

Title: Digital Art
Description: Digital Art Style can cover a wide range of styles but usually involves artwork created using digital technology, like digital painting or 3D modeling. Color usage varies greatly, resulting in innovative designs with flawless finishes. Artists known for their digital art include David Hockney, Banksy, and Andy Warhol.

Title: Monospace
Description: Monospace Art Style pertains to visuals elements or typography where every letter occupies the same amount of space. Characterized by a uniform composition and typically rendered in monochrome, the style is neutral in mood. Renowned typographers such as Zuzana Licko, Erik Spiekermann, and Edward Johnston have used monospace fonts in their work.

Title: Cobra
Description: Cobra is an art style that originated in the 20th century, combining aspects of expressionism, primitivism, and abstract art. Involving vibrant colors and spontaneous compositions, it's known for its rebellious and noncomformist vision.

Title: Situationist
Description: Situationist refers to an art style associated with a subversive political and art movement, combining theories from Lettrism and Dadaism. It is typically provocative and confrontational, expressed in various media and urban spaces.

Title: Rebellious
Description: Rebellious art style is a reaction against established norms, epitomizing artists' desire for freedom of expression. It is characterized by disorderly compositions and agitated moods, featuring art styles like Abstract Expressionism, Street Art, and Graffiti.

Title: Illustrator
Description: An Illustrator uses visual art forms to communicate a story, message, or idea and generally work in digital media. Styles such as Digital Art, Concept Art, and Pop Art are typical, with artists like Norman Rockwell and Alex Ross embodying the illustrator style.

Title: Concept Art
Description: Concept Art represents an art style that's used in entertainment industries like film and video games to visualize concepts and ideas, often in sci-fi and fantasy genres. It's typically digital and features narrative compositions in imaginary environments.

Title: Digital Artist
Description: Digital Artists utilize digital technology as an essential part of their creative output. Their art style often encompasses various sub-genres such as New Media Art, Computer Art, and Virtual Art. Works can vary greatly in mood, composition, color scheme, and lighting, reflecting the array of tools and techniques available in digital mediums.

Title: Game
Description: Video game art encompasses visual art incorporated into video games. This art form can range drastically from Sprite Art to VG Realism depending on the technology used. The environment, color scheme, and mood are typically defined by the game's world and narrative. The composition is often programmatic, with objects and elements carefully arranged for player interaction.

Title: Historical
Description: Historical art refers to the chronological depiction of certain periods, people or events, often with an emphasis on realism. Frequently seen in styles such as Renaissance, Baroque or Impressionism, it uses mediums like oil painting. Naturalistic lighting and balanced composition are key components, often reflecting the mood and context of the depicted period.

Title: Adventurous
Description: Adventurous in the arts often signifies artwork that's daring or innovative. It involves pushing the boundaries and exploring unconventional forms. This can be seen in styles like Abstract Art and Modern Art, where artists experiment with form, color, and composition, leading to dynamic and inspiring artwork.

Title: Immersive
Description: Immersive art style signifies works designed to envelop the viewer and engage their senses, thus creating an inclusive environment. It is especially prominent in Conceptual Art, Installation Art, and Interactive Art. Such artworks are meant to be engaging and interactive, challenging the viewer's perception of art.

Title: Louise Nevelson
Description: Louise Nevelson was a prominent American sculptor known for her monochromatic assemblages. She worked prominently in the styles of Abstract Expressionism and Cubism. Her artworks incorporate found objects into large-scale installations, typically painted in a single color, thereby creating a sense of unity and rhythm.

Title: Modern Art
Description: Modern art refers to the styles and ideologies that emerged and developed between the late 19th and early 20th centuries. This period saw a revolutionary shift towards non-representational art, exemplified through styles like Cubism, Fauvism, Dada, and Surrealism. Artists like Picasso, Kandinsky, and Pollock were pioneers of this movement.

Title: Abstract Art
Description: Abstract art is an art style that doesn't aim to represent an accurate depiction of visual reality. Instead, it uses shapes, colors, forms, and gestural marks to achieve its effect. It can be both non-figurative and non-objective, serving as a means to evoke emotions that are provocative. Notable artists including Kandinsky, Mondrian, and Malevich.

Title: Manga
Description: The Manga art style is characteristic of Japanese comics, often rendered in black-and-white with high contrast and set in environments such as urban cityscapes. The artwork is known for its distinctive, exaggerated features. The style varies from Shoujo (geared towards young girls) to Shounen (geared towards young boys). The composition of Manga often uses panel configurations directing the reader’s eye flow.

Title: Futuristic
Description: Futuristic art style adopts a vision of advanced and often technologically-advanced settings. The common themes are often shown in a stripped-down, sleek, and shiny design rendered through digital painting. There is a heavy use of neon colors especially in the Cyberpunk style. Prominent artists in this style include Syd Mead and H.R. Giger.

Title: Panel
Description: Panel art style is prominent in comic books and sequential art where the storyline is depicted panel by panel. The artist uses dynamic panel layouts for narrative pacing. Inking is the primary medium applied to illustrate the plot and characters. Jack Kirby and Steve Ditko are some of the relevant artists associated with this style.

Title: David Malin
Description: David Malin is a renowned astrophotographer known for pioneering techniques to capture the beauty of outer space through the lens of a camera. His color palette is characterized by the diverse spectra of natural starlight. His photographic art style has set the paradigm for astronomical photography.

Title: Celestial
Description: The Celestial art style is an artistic interpretation of outer space and sky. Usually depicted through medium such as oil painting, the environments illustrated are of the cosmos or sky, with cool-toned color palettes, and a fantastical mood. Vincent Van Gogh and Caspar David Friedrich have created iconic representations of Celestial art.

Title: Sci-Fi
Description: The Sci-Fi art style reflects envisioned futures, outer space adventures, advanced technologies, and extra-terrestrial life. It's often marked by detailed technology-related elements. The environment is typically set in outer space or futuristic locations. The lighting tends to be artificial, creating a mysterious mood.

Title: Punk
Description: The Punk art style showcases a rebellious and raw aesthetic, often seen in street art and graffiti. The environment is usually urban, with a high-contrast lighting and vibrant colors often used. The compositions are often asymmetrical, adding to the edgy, non-conformist vibe of the punk genre.

Title: Various
Description: The Various art style represents a mix of different styles, mediums, and techniques. The concept is broad and versatile, capable of referring to thousands of different distinct art styles.

Title: Company
Description: A Company art style typically refers to a visual aesthetic that is consistent across a company's branding and products. This could include logos, marketing materials, and product design. The specific style can vary widely depending on the company and its target market.

Title: Design Studio
Description: A Design Studio art style refers to the collective aesthetic output of a Design Studio. This often involves a mix of different styles, depending on the projects and clients of the studio. The style usually aims to be dynamic, innovative and customer-pleasing.

Title: Experimental
Description: The Experimental art style heavily incorporates abstract composition, often using mixed media. Artists who have worked extensively in this style include Marcel Duchamp, Yoko Ono, and Joseph Beuys. This style invokes intrigue and is often associated with art movements such as Surrealism, Dada, and Fluxus.

Title: Geometric
Description: The Geometric art style is closely related to the Abstract, Minimalist, and Bauhaus movements and primarily utilizes structured composition in painting. Artists such as Wassily Kandinsky, Piet Mondrian, and Kazimir Malevich are known for their geometric works.

Title: Fantasy
Description: Fantasy art style is intertwined with vibrant colors and mystical moods, often set in fictional worlds. The style spans Pre-Raphaelite, Surrealism, and Art Nouveau. Noteworthy artists include Brian Froud, H.R. Giger, and Gustave Doré.

Title: Norman Bel Geddes
Description: Norman Bel Geddes, an influential Industrial Designer, worked with a distinctive style closely associated with Art Deco, Futurism, and Streamline Moderne. His design approach typically included functional composition set against urban landscapes.

Title: Post-War Era
Description: Post-War Era art style is defined by movements such as Pop Art, Abstract Expressionism, and Minimalism, primarily utilizing painting. It's known for its reflective mood, with influential artists including Jackson Pollock, Andy Warhol, and Roy Lichtenstein.

Title: Optimistic
Description: Optimistic art style is often defined by its bright, vibrant colors and balanced compositions that exude a joyful mood. This can be seen in the works of artists like Claude Monet and Vincent Van Gogh, who masterfully created a sense of optimism in their paintings.

Title: Dystopian
Description: Dystopian art style is characterized by its desolate urban landscapes, dark and desaturated color palette, and melancholic mood. The composition often tends to be chaotic, portraying a stark contrast to idealistic visions. Artists like Zdzisław Beksiński and Salvador Dali are known for their dystopian art.

Title: Intense
Description: Intense art style is defined by its strong contrasts, dramatic mood, and bold lines or forms, often creating deeply impactful impressions. This style is demonstrated through artworks like those of Edvard Munch and Pablo Picasso, renowned for their intense visual expressions.

Title: Dynamic
Description: Dynamic art style, displayed profoundly in Abstract Expressionism and Futurism, is characterized by a vibrant color palette and compositions indicating movement and energy. Jackson Pollock and Giacomo Balla’s artworks often showcase a varying light intensity to enhance the dynamism.

Title: Provocative
Description: Provocative art style, typical in Contemporary and Pop Art, is marked by compositions with unexpected or shocking elements that challenge conventional norms and provoke thought. Artists like Banksy and Andy Warhol have created artworks loaded with social commentary and inherent provocation.

Title: Stylized
Description: Stylized art style represents a departure from realistic portrayals and reflects artistically exaggerated interpretation of subjects. The style can be seen in various genres including Abstract and Minimalism. The medium primarily employed is painting. These works often feature Vibrant color schemes and abstract compositions that creates a feeling of fantasy.

Title: Tapestry Art
Description: Tapestry Art is a form of textile art, traditionally woven by hand on a loom. The medium primarily used is fabric. Tapestry art often portrays Historical moods with narrative compositions. Artists like Jean Lurçat and Michel Tourlière have made significant contributions to this art form.

Title: Narrative
Description: Narrative Art style is a tradition in visual storytelling that conveys a story or sequence of events. It can be found in various mediums, including literature. The emotions portrayed in the narrative form an Emotional mood. Notable artists include Jean Lurçat and Michel Tourlière.

Title: Mysterious
Description: Mysterious art style is typically associated with Surrealism, Abstract Expressionism, and Symbolism. It often features dream-like scenarios portrayed through painting, usually using cool, dark colors. The lighting conditions of such artworks are often low-light to enhance the sense of mystery. Moreover, it presents an unpredictable composition, inducing feelings of intrigue among its viewers.

Title: Emotional
Description: Emotional art style draws its roots from Expressionism, Romanticism, and Impressionism. Blickered through painting, it's seen with vivid colors and expressive strokes to portray the artist's emotions. The moods expressed can range greatly, from joy to sorrow. Artists renowned for this style include Edvard Munch, Vincent Van Gogh and Claude Monet.

Title: Photographer
Description: Photographer as an artistic concept relates to the art style of a photographer. This can include Documentary Photography, Fine Art Photography, and Street Photography. All of these fields employ the medium of photography to convey the artist's ideas or document the surroundings.

Title: Portraiture
Description: Portraiture art style is often linked with Realism, Cubism, and Renaissance Portraiture. Typically, portraits are painted in a studio with controlled lighting conditions. Portraits are usually centralized within the composition and utilize natural colors. Rembrandt, Pablo Picasso, and Leonardo da Vinci are a few artists well-known for their contribution to this style.

Title: Sculptor
Description: The term 'sculptor' refers to an individual artist who creates sculptures. The style of the sculptor can vary; ranging from Classical to Abstract to Neoclassical. Regardless of style, the medium in which the sculptor chooses to express their vision is predominantly three-dimensional sculptures.

Title: Harlem Renaissance
Description: Harlem Renaissance was a cultural movement mainly consisting of African-American artists, writers, and thinkers. The art style heavily borrowed from African art, Cubism, and Modernism, depicting urban life and African-American culture. It employed multicolor schemes and diverse moods in its paintings. Its figurative composition portrayed a unique perspective on African-American experiences. Notable artists include Jacob Lawrence and Aaron Douglas.

Title: Concept Artist
Description: The concept art style involves creating artwork for digital properties such as games or films. This art style focuses on visual conceptualization rather than the fine details. It often includes storyboarding and character design to visualize a concept. The medium used is primarily digital. McQuarrie, Sorayama, and Wen are some artists known for this style.

Title: Mechanical
Description: The mechanical art style often reflects an industrial environment, utilizing gears, machines, and raw materials in its sculptures. It consists of styles such as Steampunk and Cyberpunk, with the recurring theme of machinery and mechanization. Artists like Tinguely, Paolozzi, and Jansen have been known to explore this style.

Title: William Gibson
Description: William Gibson is best known for his Cyberpunk style in the world of science fiction and postmodern literature. His works often portray dystopian moods, which have inspired many artists such as Ridley, Cameron, and Miyazaki.

Title: Paolo Bacigalupi
Description: Paolo Bacigalupi's literary style leans towards Biopunk and Climate Fiction. His work often carries an apocalyptic mood illustrating grim visions of the future. His art style has influenced artists like VanderMeer, McCarthy, and Atwood.

Title: Science Fiction
Description: Science Fiction art style often portrays future technology, advanced civilizations, and alien worlds. It's usually set in a futuristic or space environment with glowing lighting and a dominant color scheme of blue, black, white, and grey. This style is known for its dynamic composition and evokes a feeling of intrigue. Notable artists in this field include H.R. Giger and Syd Mead.

Title: Grim
Description: Grim art style is a visual aesthetic that depicts dark, gloomy, or macabre subjects. This style is often present in Gothic, Dark, and Horror art and typically uses an imbalanced composition and a color palette that leans towards dark, black, and grey shades. Renowned artists like Hieronymus Bosch and Francisco Goya are commonly associated with this style.

Title: Aerial Perspective
Description: The Aerial Perspective art style is a technique of rendering distance or depth used in painting. As the distance between an object and a viewer increases, the contrast between the object and its background decreases, the color saturation reduces and shift towards blue. Notable artists using this style include Leonardo Da Vinci and Camille Pissarro.

Title: Architect
Description: Architect art often adopts a minimalist, Cubist, and Modernist style, implemented primarily through design sketching. The color scheme is often monochrome and utilizes basic geometric shapes for composition, with notable personalities like David Ellis, Frank Gehry, Zaha Hadid, Le Corbusier, and Renzo Piano significantly contributing to its development.

Title: Person
Description: Portrait art style captures individuals by emphasizing facial features with a focused composition. It can range from realism to abstract styles, with lighting and color schemes dependent on the person and mood being portrayed. Notable portrait artists include Rembrandt and Vincent van Gogh.

Title: Urban
Description: The urban art style is a contemporary trend often associated with graffiti and street art. It portrays cityscapes using bright colors and dynamic compositions. Renowned urban artists include Banksy and Keith Haring.

Title: Video Game
Description: Video game art style uses digital mediums to create visual aspects of video games. It covers styles like pixel art, isometric, and 3D modeling. The environment is usually virtual, creating an interactive composition with dynamic lighting. Notable contributors include Shigeru Miyamoto and Hideo Kojima.

Title: Video Game Art
Description: Video Game Art adopts numerous art styles - digital art, concept art, 3D modeling, pixel art, and Chiptune art. Typically realized through computer graphics, its environment resides in virtual reality, and presents a variable lighting scheme within a full spectrum of colors. Notable game artists include David Ellis, Hideo Kojima, Shigeru Miyamoto, Tetsuya Nomura, and John Romero.

Title: Aerial
Description: Aerial art is an abstract & impressionist style, often expressed through drone photography. The artists focus on the sky as an environment and primarily make use of natural lighting, often creating scenes with high contrast. Noteworthy artists in this style include David Ellis, Yann Arthus-Bertrand, Vincent Laforet, George Steinmetz, and Cameron Davidson.

Title: Victorian Era
Description: Victorian Era art is characterized by Romanticism, Pre-Raphaelite and Academic art styles. Executed mainly through painting, it is known for romantic settings & historical depictions, with soft, diffused lighting and rich, vibrant colors. It sets a sentimental mood with a detailed & meticulous composition. David Ellis, John Everett Millais, William Holman Hunt, and Dante Gabriel Rossetti are key contributors to this art style.

Title: Hans-Peter Feldmann
Description: Hans-Peter Feldmann is a well-known name in the modern art scene, recognized for his conceptual, appropriation, and contemporary art styles. Often working with photography, Feldmann's approach models the idea of art as a social commentary and encourages active engagement from the viewer.

Title: Chalk Art
Description: Chalk Art is an art style under the genres of Street Art, Graffiti, and Anamorphic Art. This medium involves the use of chalk on pavement, usually situated in outdoor settings under natural lighting. It is temporary and often large-scale, with notable artists being Tracy Lee Stum, Julian Beever, and Edgar Mueller.

Title: Informative Art
Description: Informative Art is a style that involves the conveyance of messages or information, often falling under the wider categories of Conceptual Art or Infographics. This intellectual style can utilize a range of mediums and is typically structured in composition, with artists such as Jenny Holzer, Barbara Kruger, and Joseph Kosuth notable figures.

Title: Text-based
Description: Text-based art is a style capitalizing on the visual arrangement of words. Falling under genres like Typography Art, Concrete Poetry, or Conceptual Art, it's recognized for its intellectual mood. The composition is heavily based on text with various possible mediums. Known artists in this domain include Lawrence Weiner, Ed Ruscha, and Jenny Holzer.

Title: Psychedelic Art
Description: Psychedelic Art is a style known for its visually striking, dreamlike qualities and use of vibrant lighting and vivid colors. Often associated with Visionary Art, Surrealism, and Abstract Art, it is designed to inspire a sense of transcendence. Notable artists of this style include Alex Grey, Peter Max, and Mati Klarwein.

Title: Paint
Description: The 'Paint' art style, largely defined by its medium- 'Paint', can be stretched across various styles ranging from Oil painting to Tempera painting. Artists like 'Vincent van Gogh' popularised this style to capture varied moods using multi-color palette, traditionally on a canvas. The composition of such paintings is usually structured with natural lighting.

Title: Surreal
Description: The 'Surreal' art style is known for dream-like, irrational visual landscapes and uncanny depictions of objects. Surrealism and Metaphysical painting fall under this style. Mysterious in mood, with a vivid color scheme, such artworks are typically paintings. Some renowned Surrealist artists include Salvador Dali and Rene Magritte.

Title: Cybernetic
Description: The 'Cybernetic' art style is grounded in the field of cybernetics or systems science. This futuristic style uses digital media as a medium, often revolving around themes of technology, AI, and networks. It's marked by complex composition, artificial lighting, and vivid neon colors. Relevant artists include Norman White and Stelarc.

Title: Supernatural
Description: The 'Supernatural' art style portrays mystical, ethereal, and often terrifying themes, related to unworldly forces or entities. This phantasmagoric environment is reflected in dark color schemes, dramatic lighting, and symbolic compositions. Artistic styles like Romanticism, Surrealism, and Gothic Art explore these themes, with notable artists like Edvard Munch and Francisco Goya.

Title: Comic Writer
Description: Comic Writer is an art style characterized by storytelling in panels with usually vibrant, multi-color drawings. The medium generally utilized is ink. Renowned artists of this style include Stan Lee, Alan Moore, and Neil Gaiman.

Title: Outsider Art
Description: Outsider Art is an art style primarily expressed by the untrained or self-taught artists who are not part of the traditional art scene. The composition is frequently free-form, and the mood highly expressive. Well-known artists include Henry Darger, Bill Traylor, and Martin Ramirez.

Title: Simplified
Description: Simplified Art Style is associated with artistic approaches that minimize detail to emphasize essential features. It is closely tied to styles such as minimalism and abstract art. The medium generally used is painting, and the compositions often lean towards a geometric or monochromatic color scheme.

Title: Video Artist
Description: The art style of a Video Artist uses digital media as a medium to manipulate moving images creating a sense of Virtual Environment. This art style is closely related to Video Art and Multimedia Art movements. Artists associated include Nam June Paik, Bill Viola, and Pipilotti Rist.

Title: Video Art
Description: Video Art is a contemporary form of art utilizing the medium of moving visuals or video. The environment is often virtual with controlled artificial lighting. It's often associated with Performance Art and Conceptual Art. Nam June Paik, Vito Acconci, and Marina Abramović are notable artists in this field.

Title: Introspective
Description: Introspective art style is often characterized by the expression of the artist's inner self or thoughts, using mostly a painting medium. It comprises of various art styles like abstract, surrealism, and expressionism. The environment is generally an interior, exhibiting a thoughtful mood with balanced composition and soft lighting. Muted color tones are commonly used to reflect deeper personal meanings.

Title: Naive Art
Description: Naive art style, also known as Primitivism, Folk or Outsider Art, typically involves painting. This style portrays a simplified and non-sophisticated perspective of rural scenes, characterized by vibrant colors, flat perspective and straightforward composition. The lighting reflects a natural environment and evokes a positive mood. Key artists include Henri Rousseau, Alfred Wallis and Grandma Moses.

Title: Raw
Description: Raw art style, also known as Brut Art, Outsider Art or Art Informel, mainly features sculptures. This style is characterized by unconventionally artistic works which are often intended to have a primitive, earthy appearance. The compositions are abstract and the mood is primitive. The lighting is generally harsh to emphasize rough textures. Works of Jean Dubuffet, Jean Fautrier, and Pierre Alechinsky represent this style.

Title: Maria Sibylla Merian
Description: Maria Sibylla Merian, a noted Scientific Illustrator, has an art style that is informative and dedicated to the detailed representation of nature. Her medium was predominantly drawing. The style exhibits multi-colors, with a neutral lighting condition reflecting a natural environment. Along with Merian, artists such as John James Audubon, Ernst Haeckel and Carl Alexander Clerck have also contributed significantly to this field.

Title: Scientific Illustration
Description: Scientific Illustration is an art style primarily used to illuminate scientific knowledge and discoveries. This style is characterized by its use of drawing as the medium with detailed composition. Noted for its informative mood, it often exhibits a realistic color scheme under neutral lighting, representing the natural environment. Notable artists from this style include Leonardo Da Vinci, Ernst Haeckel, and John James Audubon.

Title: Detailed
Description: The Detailed art style is characterized by meticulous attention to even the minute details, striving for a high degree of visual fidelity. This style often employs Realism, Photorealism, or Surrealism. The composition focuses on every detail, with naturalistic colors and the chiaroscuro lighting technique stemming from the Realist tradition.

Title: Conceptual Art
Description: The Conceptual art style prioritizes the idea or concept over the physical or visual elements. Known for its abstract composition and intellectual mood, it can be expressed through various mediums, such as installation art. Color schemes vary widely as they are secondary to the underlying concept. Artists such as Sol LeWitt and Marcel Duchamp are known for their conceptual art.

Title: Fantasy Landscapes
Description: The Fantasy Landscapes art style involves the creation of imaginative, expansive compositions set in mystical environments. Highly saturated colors and ethereal lighting contribute to the fantasy theme. This style, expressed through mediums like digital painting, shares similarities with Fantasy Art and Romanticism. Iconic artists include Roger Dean and John Howe.

Title: Cinematic
Description: The Cinematic art style is characterized by its filmic qualities, often featuring high-contrast lighting and dynamic compositions. With roots in Film Noir and German Expressionism, it often evokes a melodramatic mood, typically set in urban environments. The color scheme is usually monochromatic. Iconic filmmakers like Alfred Hitchcock have employed this style.

Title: Suspenseful
Description: Suspenseful art style plays heavily on tension and the unexpected. It's often seen in Abstract and Expressionism genres. Artists like Salvador Dali and Edvard Munch have notably used this style.

Title: Complex Narratives
Description: Complex Narratives art style involves deep, intricate storytelling often seen in Narrative Art and Conceptual Art. Artists like Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg are noteworthy in this space.

Title: War Zones
Description: War Zones art style portrays realistic and chaotic scenes often seen in Realism and Impressionism. Artists like Francisco Goya and Pablo Picasso have contributed to these representations.

Title: Conceptual Photography
Description: Conceptual Photography art style is an artistic genre that utilizes photography as a medium. This style abstractly symbolizes ideas and is often related to Modernism and Postmodernism. Cindy Sherman and Man Ray are known for this style.

Title: Contemporary Art
Description: Contemporary Art style is a genre that began in the mid-20th century and includes diverse compositions from Postmodernism to Minimalism. Notable artists include Marina Abramović, Banksy, and Ai Weiwei.

Title: Text-based Imagery
Description: The Text-based Imagery art style is a unique form of artistic expression which primarily involves typography, calligraphy, and letterpress printing. Its medium is primarily focused on printmaking. The composition of the art is characterized by Layered Imagery, creating a multifaceted perspective. Louis Prang is one artist associated with this style.

Title: Photorealism
Description: Photorealism is an art style that seeks to replicate a high-resolution camera lens' precision in painting. It covers a variety of art styles like still life, portrait, and landscape. The general mood conveyed is neutral, with naturalistic lighting and full-spectrum color. Photorealism's composition is a direct translation of reality. Artists like Richard Estes, Audrey Flack, and Robert Bechtle are associated with this style.

Title: Grid-based
Description: Grid-based art is a visual style characterized by the use of defined grids. It is associated with various art movements like Geometric Abstraction, Minimalism, Op Art, De Stijl, and Cubism. The medium might include drawing, with the artwork displaying a structured composition. Notable artists include Piet Mondrian, Josef Albers, Sol LeWitt, Bridget Riley, and Agnes Martin.

Title: Porcelain Art
Description: Porcelain art comes under the domain of ceramic art and sculpture. It commonly employs the medium of sculpture and takes place in a studio environment. The color scheme is often multicolor and its composition is focused on details. Renowned porcelain artists include Meissen, Royal Porcelain Factory, Sevres, Wedgwood, and Royal Copenhagen.

Title: Floral Motifs
Description: Art featuring Floral Motifs is often found in movements like Art Nouveau, Rococo, Still Life, Impressionism, and the Arts and Crafts Movement. The preferred medium is painting, with a backdrop of natural environments. These works can be multicolored and cheerful. The arrangement of elements is usually balanced. Artists like Claude Monet, Vincent Van Gogh, Rachel Ruysch, Edouard Manet, and Gustav Klimt have often used floral motifs in their work.

Title: Nature
Description: Nature art involves styles such as Landscape Painting, Realism, Impressionism, Transcendental Painting, and Wildlife Art. Mostly being paintings set in an outdoor environment, it depicts multicolored and serene scenes, with a wide composition emphasizing on the vastness of nature. Notable artists include John Constable, Claude Monet, Albrecht Durer, Ansel Adams, and Frank Weston Benson.

Title: Self-portraiture
Description: Self-portraiture showcases the artist's introspective interpretation of their identity. It often employs styles such as Realism, Expressionism, Surrealism, Pop Art, and Impressionism, frequently using a painting medium. These artworks are usually created in a studio with direct lighting and may possess a multicolor scheme. The composition is often centered, emphasizing the artist themselves. Renowned artists like Rembrandt, Vincent Van Gogh, Frida Kahlo, Pablo Picasso, and Andy Warhol have made significant contributions to this art style.

Title: Wide-angle Shots
Description: The Wide-angle shots art style predominantly surfaces in photography, primarily the cinematic, documentary and realist styles. The medium—photography, allows expansive composition of urban environments bathed in natural lighting. Vivid colors punctuate these dramatic frames, best captured by artists like Dennis Stock, Michael Yates, and Sam Abell.

Title: Film Photography
Description: The Film photography art style, circling styles like fine art, abstract, and modernist, uses the medium of photography to establish intimate compositions. Staging usually happens in a studio with controlled lighting, often producing nostalgic monochrome tones. Artists such as Ansel Adams, Richard Avedon, and Diane Arbus have been instrumental in the development of this style.

Title: Historical Fashion
Description: The Historical fashion art style, often seen originating from disciplines like realist, impressionist, and Baroque art, utilizes clothing as its medium. Pieces are marked by their detailed composition amid sophisticated moods, often set against a backdrop of richly decorated interiors under dramatic lighting. Esteemed artists in this genre include Charles Frederick Worth, Jeanne Paquin, and Madame Grès.

Title: 19th Century
Description: The 19th century art style, demonstrating forms of Romanticism, Realism, and Impressionism, is primarily characterized by its painting medium. The grandiose compositions maintain a solemn mood, set within natural environments illuminated by natural light. Pastel color schemes remain a recurring theme. Notable artists of this period are figures like Édouard Manet, Gustave Courbet, and Pierre-Auguste Renoir.

Title: Dressmaking Patterns
Description: Dressmaking patterns art style, energized within vintage, retro, and bohemian styles, manifests through the medium of textile design. Its compositions are structured yet carry a creative mood within fashion studios under soft lighting. Its color schemes are notably vibrant with artists such as Mary Quant, Betsey Johnson, and Vera Neumann being key contributors.

Title: Visual Novel
Description: The Visual Novel art style thrives on the digital platform, and brings narratives to life through character-driven compositions. It combines elements of Anime, Manga, and at times, even the playful Chibi style. Artists such as Kazuki Fumi and Yusuke Tsutsumi have notably contributed to this genre of art.

Title: Culture
Description: Culture art style is a broad term encompassing various art forms like Folk, Tribal, and Calligraphy. The medium often used in this form of art is painting. Renowned artists like Frida Kahlo, Pablo Picasso and Banksy have richly contributed to the Culture art style.

Title: Subculture
Description: Subculture art style often includes forms such as Graffiti, Pop Art, and Lowbrow. The art is prominently featured in an urban environment, typically with vibrantly colored compositions that provoke thought and stir up the status quo. Artists like Keith Haring and Jean-Michel Basquiat are considered pioneers in this style.

Title: Goth
Description: The Goth art style is characterized by its evocative mood, drawing on dark and often supernatural elements. It often uses low lighting and black colors, with a haunted ambience and mystical or Gothic elements in its composition, with paintings as one of the main mediums.

Title: Grunge
Description: Grunge art style, often associated with the punk and urban scenes, is defined by a sense of rebellion. Muted colors, layered graphic elements, and a rough, distressed aesthetic typify the style. Banksy and Shepard Fairey are among the most recognizable artists in this genre.

Title: Layered
Description: Layered art style involves the approach of overlapping multiple elements or mediums creatively. The colors can greatly vary, but the key feature is the sense of depth and complexity introduced by the layering. Recognizable artists include Robert Rauschenberg and Kurt Schwitters.

Title: Fayum Mummy Portraits
Description: Fayum Mummy Portraits refer to a specific type of funerary art in the Roman-Egyptian period. They are painted directly onto the mummified bodies with natural tones and showcase realistic lighting. The artists of these portraits remain unknown.

Title: Information Design
Description: The Information Design art style is primarily used for visualisation of data and information. It uses a combination of graphic design and data representation to present information in an easy-to-understand, insightful, and aesthetically pleasing manner. The composition is normally structured and organised, often using grids for arrangement. The color scheme is variable, depending on the information being presented.

Title: Grid
Description: The Grid art style is a structured and geometric style, emphasising order and simplicity. The medium is often painting, with monochromatic color schemes common. Art produced in this style is frequently seen in Minimalist and Abstract Art, with artists like Piet Mondrian and Agnes Martin popularising the style.

Title: Paper
Description: The Paper art style is a tactile and physical medium used in numerous sub-styles such as origami and papercutting. It is often characterised by its delicate, intricate compositions, with a variable color scheme. Notable artists in this style include Eric Carle and Peter Callesen.

Title: Comics
Description: The Comics art style is a visual narrative mode utilised in manga, graphic novels, and superhero comics. Using the medium of illustration, this style often employs a full-color scheme with varying environments and lighting conditions, determined by the narrative. The composition is sequential, showing a progression of events or actions. Prominent figures in this style include Stan Lee and Alan Moore.

Title: Sequential
Description: The Sequential art style tells a story via a series of images or scenes, typically seen in comics and storyboarding. Variable environments and lighting conditions, a full-color scheme, and narrative mood are signature characteristics of this style. The artists utilising this style, such as Will Eisner and Scott McCloud, are often associated with comics and visual storytelling.

Title: Pin-up Art
Description: Pin-up Art style is a type of art that portrays models in a provocative and suggestive positions. Mostly noted in paintings, it often features bright colors and a figure-centric composition that attracts attention primarily to the women featured in design. It is typically associated with vintage, glamour, and pop art styles.

Title: Children's Literature
Description: Children's Literature Art style refers to the visual representation seen in children's books. The drawings often belong to illustration, cartoon, or fantasy styles, with a character-centric composition and an adventurous mood. The art often features vibrant colors and is set in an imaginary environment.

Title: Disturbing
Description: Disturbing Art style often pertains to art that invokes feelings of unease or discomfort. This style often uses dark colors and chaos in its composition. Surrealism, Expressionism and Dark Art styles are notably associated with this concept, featuring art from artists like Francis Bacon and Salvador Dali.

Title: Distorted
Description: Distorted Art style includes art that appears twisted or transformed from its usual shape, often presenting a non-representative composition. It is closely related to Cubism, Surrealism, and Abstract Expressionism. Artists associated with this style include Pablo Picasso and Salvador Dali.

Title: Water
Description: Water Art style often portrays the aesthetic of water, its motion, and related environments. This genre notably features aquatic environments and a dynamic composition. The art style is usually linked to impressionism, realism, or romanticism with artists like Claude Monet and J.M.W Turner.

Title: Anxious
Description: The Anxious art style characteristically features elements of Expressionism, Abstract, and Surrealism. Expressing feelings of unease, this style predominantly uses dark tones and has an irregular composition. The medium often used for this art style is painting.

Title: Graphic Designer
Description: A Graphic Designer often uses the Graphic Design art style, which features Minimalism, Swiss style, and Pop Art. Implemented typically through a digital medium, this art style uses bold colors and has a clear and direct composition. Notable graphic designers include Paul Rand, Saul Bass, and Milton Glaser.

Title: Typographer
Description: A Typographer extensively uses the Typography art style, characterized by Modern, Decorative, and Vintage elements. The medium is usually print, and the composition is typographic. The color scheme varies depending on the project or piece. Renowned typographers include Eric Gill, Herb Lubalin, and Adrian Frutiger.

Title: Comic Book Artist
Description: Comic Book Artist art style is often recognized by its bright, multicolor palette and sequential composition. It borrows elements from both Comic Art and Pop Art styles. Working mainly with ink, artists like Stan Lee, Jack Kirby, and Steve Ditko are well-renowned in this field.

Title: Alternative Comics
Description: Alternative Comics art style is noted for its narrative, satirical mood delivered in sequential panels. It mostly finds its roots in Underground Comics and Independent Comics styles. The work is primarily executed using graphite and limited to black and white. Artists like Robert Crumb, Daniel Clowes, and Chris Ware are key contributors to this genre.

Title: Comic Book Art
Description: Comic Book Art style is distinguished by its vibrant, multicolor visuals that tend to depict everyday, urban environments. Rooted in Pop Art and Manga styles, this form of art employs ink as the medium. The composition usually adopts a sequential layout. Pioneers of this genre include Osamu Tezuka, Jack Kirby, and Joe Shuster.

Title: Pop Art
Description: Pop Art style burst onto the scene as a response to Abstract Expressionism and Cubism. It often features energetic, simplified compositions with a multicolor palette. The style uses acrylic as the medium of choice and reflects urban life. Celebrated artists like Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein, and Keith Haring have played a significant role.

Title: Landscape Photography
Description: Landscape Photography art style is characterized by the expansive composition of outdoor environments. Relying on natural colors and light, it shares affiliations with Nature Photography and Travel Photography genres. Digital is the preferred medium. Ansel Adams, Peter Lik, and David Muench are some of the distinguished artists in this field.

Title: Installation Art
Description: Installation art is an artistic genre of three-dimensional works designed to transform a perception of a space. Often site-specific, it may have a temporary or permanent nature. It can incorporate any media to establish immersive, large-scale interactive environments.

Title: Fantastic Realism
Description: Fantastic Realism is an art style that combines meticulous detail and vibrant colors with dreamlike, symbolic, or fantastical themes. It blends the technical accuracy of the old masters with surreal and mythical themes.

Title: Film
Description: The film as an art style presents a dynamic combination of visual imagery and sound. Its aesthetics vary considerably and depend on the genre, director's creative vision, and techniques used. It's known for storytelling and inducing emotional responses.

Title: Fantasy Art
Description: Fantasy art encapsulates a genre of visual art generally characterized by its fantastical themes and mythological influences. It is often vibrant and mystical, filled with storytelling imagery from imaginary worlds, creatures, and landscapes.

Title: Design
Description: Design art style is visually communicated information using graphic arts. This can be applied in many fields such as graphic, industrial, interior, fashion, and digital design. The medium typically used is digital with a focus on layout in the composition of the design.

Title: Photojournalism
Description: Photojournalism is a style of art that involves capturing real-world events in a truthful and objective manner. This is typically done through mediums like documentary or street photography. Photojournalism often demands natural lighting and a realistic mood.

Title: Modern Photography
Description: Modern Photography as an art style employs various styles such as abstract, portrait, and landscape photography. The medium chiefly employed is photography with a varied color scheme and composition focusing on framing.

Title: Kalyan Joshi
Description: Kalyan Joshi is renowned for his Phad painting style. With emphasis on bright colors and storytelling, his work has a strong narrative composition. His medium is predominantly painting, and he comes from a lineage of revered artists.

Title: Prakash Joshi
Description: Prakash Joshi's art style is strongly identified by Phad painting with a vibrant color scheme. His medium is painting focused on storytelling in a mythological environment. The works are grouped alongside other notable artists in this field.

Title: Indian Folk Art
Description: Indian Folk Art is a traditional visual art style originating from different regions of India. It generally narrates mythological and natural themes in vibrant colors. Notable artists include Jamini Roy and Bhaskar Mahapatra.

Title: Graphic Novel Art
Description: Graphic Novel Art is a visual art style used primarily in the creation of graphic novels, employing a range from black and white to full color. The composition is sequential and arranged in panels. Notable artists include Art Spiegelman, Will Eisner, and Alan Moore.

Title: Contemporary Photography
Description: Contemporary Photography isn't tied down by traditional concepts and can feature varied moods, lighting, and color schemes. Predominantly used as a tool for personal expression, it extends boundaries while capturing truth and reality. Notable artists include Cindy Sherman, Andreas Gursky, and Steve McCurry.

Title: Pre-Columbian Art
Description: Pre-Columbian Art refers to the visual art traditions of the indigenous peoples of America before the arrival of Christopher Columbus. It primarily comprises of earthen sculpture, often rendered in a figurative style. Notable civilizations include the Olmec, Maya, Aztec, Inca, and Zapotec.

Title: Quibe
Description: Quibe, a renowned artist, is famous for his minimalist and one-line art style. His drawings are usually in monochrome and feature complex ideas simplified to a single flowing line. His unique style showcases the depth that simplicity can convey.

Title: Antoni Gaudí
Description: Antoni Gaudí, a renowned architect of the modernist era, mixed Art Nouveau and Gothic styles to create unique buildings mostly found in Barcelona, Spain. His compositions were uniquely asymmetric, often featuring unexpected and unconventional design elements with variable color themes.

Title: Akira Yoshizawa
Description: Akira Yoshizawa, considered as the grandmaster of origami, evolved the traditional Japanese art into a modern form of sculptural creation using paper. His works were often symmetric and most of his compositions were created with a single sheet of paper, often monochrome.

Title: Robert J. Lang
Description: Robert J. Lang is a contemporary origami artist known for his complex and intricate designs that often portray animals and insects. He has elevated the art of origami with his geometric compositions and has contributed to the development of mathematical theories in folding techniques.

Title: Louis Comfort Tiffany
Description: Louis Comfort Tiffany, an American artist and designer, is best known for his work in stained glass during the Art Nouveau period. He incorporated multifaceted colors into his designs that often included floral and nature-inspired compositions. Clara Driscoll, one of his associates, played a crucial role in some of his most famous designs.

Title: Peter Carl Fabergé
Description: Peter Carl Fabergé, a Russian goldsmith and jeweler, is predominantly celebrated for his series of opulent Easter eggs created for Russian Tsars. His work, characterized by exquisite craftsmanship, often featured diverse colors and asymmetric compositions. His style was deeply rooted in the Art Nouveau movement.

Title: Decorative Art
Description: Decorative art is primarily concerned with the design and decoration of objects, rather than their construction. Its varieties are extremely diverse, including ceramics, furniture, glassware, metalwork, textiles. It is often characterized by elegant designs and symmetrical compositions. Key artists working within this art form include Sonia Delaunay and František Kupka.

Title: Religious Item
Description: In visual arts, religious items take a significant place. These items are rich in symbolism and iconography, carried out through mediums like metal works, sculptures, and paintings. The mood is typically solemn or spiritual, and color schemes often involve gold tones. Notable artists include Andrei Rublev and Cimabue.

Title: Icon
Description: Iconography in religious art depicts holy figures or events in a characteristic symmetrical composition, mainly using painting techniques. The mood is devout or sacred, achieved through vibrant yet limited color palettes. Notable artists famous for their Iconography include Andrei Rublev, Theophanes the Greek, and Duccio.

Title: Byzantine Art
Description: Byzantine Art originated as a Roman artistic style which transitioned when Rome split into East and West. Known for its iconic religious depictions, it typically used a flat two-dimensional style with a big emphasis on gold and vivid colors, often seen in mosaics and frescoes in a spiritual Christian setting.

Title: Religious Art
Description: Religious art is a broad style encompassing various forms of media used to represent religious beliefs and figures, often as a focus for devotion. Styles can include Iconography, Stained Glass and Sculpture. Renowned artists like Michelangelo and Leonardo Da Vinci have contributed significantly to this art style.

Title: Street Artists
Description: Street artists are people who create artistic works, typically anonymously, in public spaces. The art form has roots in graffiti and evolved into diverse styles like Stencil Graffiti and Poster Art. The art is often characterized by its freestyle approach, vibrant colors, and its placement in an urban setting, making a revolutionary statement.

Title: Graffiti Art
Description: Graffiti Art, often seen in urban settings, features freestyle compositions and can encompass various styles including Tagging, Stenciling, and Bombing. The art is produced using spray paint, giving it a vibrant and varied color palette. Esteemed for its rebellious representations, the milieu has given birth to highly respected artists like Banksy and Jean-Michel Basquiat.

Title: Manga Artist
Description: A Manga Artist, often called a 'Mangaka', specializes in creating Manga - a comic art form originating from Japan. The Manga art style is typically characterized by dramatic narratives and is categorized into various genres such as Shōnen, Shōjo, and Seinen. It often utilizes a frame-by-frame composition and is usually inked in monochrome.

Title: Fashion Designer
Description: The Fashion Designer art style is diverse, with influences ranging from high fashion to avant-garde. Typically realized through the medium of cloth, the environment in which this art style shines is the runway. The compositions focus on the human form and vary greatly, as does the color scheme, depending on the designer and collection. Notable designers include Coco Chanel, Louis Vuitton, and Giorgio Armani.

Title: High Fashion
Description: The High Fashion art style is sophisticated and trendsetting, primarily seen in designer runways and fashion shows. Medium employed is typically cloth, and there's an emphasis on the human form in composition. The color scheme is diverse, often providing dramatic contrast. Notable designers renowned for this style include Christian Dior, Karl Lagerfeld, and Alexander McQueen.

Title: Fashion Design
Description: The Fashion Design art style ranging from couture to ready-to-wear. The primary medium is fabric, with the designs displayed in fashion shows. The compositions often revolve around human forms and the color palette varies dramatically depending on the designer and collection. Renowned artists in this style include Vera Wang and Tom Ford.

Title: Brazilian Brutalism
Description: The Brazilian Brutalism art style is a branch of brutalism showcasing raw, functional, and geometric structures, typically molded in concrete. This style is prominently seen in urban landscapes with a largely monochromatic scheme. Notable artists linked with this art style include Paulo Mendes da Rocha and Oscar Niemeyer.

Title: Animator
Description: The Animator art style spans a gamut of styles from 2D and 3D animation, to stop motion and computer animation. Their work is majorly digital and orchestrated in animation studios, focusing on frames as their composition. Colors are stylistically varied. Prominent artists embodying this style include Hayao Miyazaki and Walt Disney.

Title: Abstract Animation
Description: Abstract Animation is a visual music-like art style, free from the constraints of representation and narrative, focusing on the rhythmic movement of shapes and colors in a non-representational composition, expressed through the medium of film. Well-known artists include Walter Ruttmann, Len Lye, and Oskar Fischinger.

Title: Color Photography
Description: Color Photography is an art style that utilizes color as a fundamental aspect of the photographic image. The medium is photography with various compositions and both natural and artificial lighting can be used. Notable artists include Steve McCurry, William Eggleston, and Annie Leibovitz.

Title: Fashion Photographer
Description: A Fashion Photographer works in the art style of Fashion Photography, which often takes place in both studio and location environments. They use controlled lighting to create glamorous moods in multicolored photographic images. A few well-known fashion photographers are Richard Avedon, Mario Testino, and Annie Leibovitz.

Title: Dot Arrangement
Description: Dot Arrangement is an art style that uses distinct dots or points to construct an image, often observed in styles like Pointillism, Dot Art, and Aboriginal Art. The medium is usually painting and well-known artists of this style include Georges Seurat, Roy Lichtenstein, and Damien Hirst.

Title: Prehistoric Artists
Description: Prehistoric Artists belong to the era of Prehistoric art, a style encapsulating Cave Paintings, Petroglyphs, and Pictographs. These artists used mediums like stone, bone, and ivory, typically creating art in caves and outdoors. Their Artist identities are usually unknown. The color scheme was often earth-toned, and compositions frequently depicted narrative scenes.

Title: Primitive
Description: Primitive art style is characterized by a simplicity, directness and naïveté of artists away from the sophistication and traditions of the art scenes of their times. The artwork typically features outdoor environments, painted with natural, earthy colors reflecting the rustic mood. Aboriginal, African, Oceanic, Prehistoric, and Folk are some of the styles associated with this concept.

Title: Textile Art
Description: Textile art style involves the creation of artwork using plant, animal, or synthetic fibers, including fabric. This style focuses on crafting an aesthetic or functional piece using techniques such as weaving, knitting, embroidery, dyeing, and quilting. The composition of textile art is typically patterned, featuring complex designs and motifs.

Title: Nick Park
Description: Nick Park is a well-known animator recognized for his whimsical art style. He often uses the methods of stop-motion and claymation. Most of his works are character-centric films created in studio settings.

Title: Sequential Arrangement
Description: Sequential arrangement refers to an art style where a series of images or scenes are arranged in a specific order to convey a story, typically found in comics, storyboarding and film. Notable sequential artists include Will Eisner, Jack Kirby and Sergio Aragonés.

Title: Raymond Loewy
Description: Raymond Loewy was an industrial designer known for his streamlined and functional design aesthetic. His works, often showcases simplified forms and lean towards a monochromatic color scheme, significantly influenced the Streamline Moderne and Industrial Design movements.

Title: Documentary Photography
Description: Documentary Photography, as an art style, is a form of photography used chiefly to chronicle significant and historical events. It is typically covered in professional photojournalism, but it may also be an amateur, artistic, or academic pursuit.

Title: Studio
Description: Studio art involves the types of art that you create in a studio or your own space, like painting, sculpture, illustration, or printmaking. It offers controlled environment and lighting conditions for the artists to work.

Title: Installation Artist
Description: An 'Installation Artist' produces works of art that are designed to change the perception of a space. Notably, the art style that marks 'Installation Art' is characterized by its immersive nature, involving the viewer's participation.

Title: Installation
Description: Installation art refers to three-dimensional works that are often site-specific and designed to transform the perception of a space. These could be both temporary or semi-permanent, and are intended to engage the viewers with their environment.

Title: Fine Art Photography
Description: Fine Art Photography is a visual art style produced with traditional or digital photographic techniques. It evokes a wide range of moods, and the composition often uses selective focus. It includes different styles like abstract, candid, documentary, fashion, and street photography. Renowned fine art photographers include Ansel Adams, Richard Avedon, Dorothea Lange, Cindy Sherman, and Man Ray.

Title: Digital Media
Description: Digital Media art style involves creating artwork using digital tools and platforms. It emanates various moods and often uses a layered composition. Styles include digital painting, 3D modeling, graphic design, digital collage, and pixel art. Notable artists in this domain include Banksy, David Hockney, Maurizio Bongiovanni, Pascal Campion, and Patricio Betteo.

Title: Historical Dressmakers
Description: Historical Dressmaking art style depicts the costumes from different historical periods like Victorian, Edwardian, Gothic, Baroque, and Renaissance. The medium is primarily textile art and it often evokes a nostalgic mood. Famous artists in this category include Charles Frederick Worth, Madeleine Vionnet, Jeanne Lanvin, Rose Bertin, and Adrian Greenberg.

Title: Social Realism
Description: Social Realism art style is characterized by its depiction of working-class activities and urban settings. It seeks to expose social issues and is often provocative. The composition is typically dynamic, utilizing painting as the primary medium. Notable sub-styles include socialist realism, kitchen sink realism, photorealism, critical realism, and neo-realism. Key artists are Diego Rivera, Ben Shahn, Edward Hopper, Grant Wood, and Jacob Lawrence.

Title: Balanced
Description: The Balanced art style shows harmony via even distribution of visual weight. This equilibrium can be realized through symmetrical, asymmetrical, radial, crystallographic, or geometric compositions. This style often returns a harmonious mood. Artists who've employed this style notably include Piet Mondrian, Leonardo da Vinci, Sandro Botticelli, Kazimir Malevich, and Paul Klee.

Title: Filippo Brunelleschi
Description: Filippo Brunelleschi was a renowned Italian architect and designer, noted for his immense contributions to Renaissance architecture. One of his well-recognized works is the design of the dome of Florence Cathedral, marking the beginning of the Renaissance era of architecture. His style is known for the harmony of elements and the use of geometric shapes, inspiring later artists like Leon Battista Alberti and Lorenzo Ghiberti.

Title: Leon Battista Alberti
Description: Leon Battista Alberti was an Italian humanist architect, who brought significant impacts on the period of Renaissance and Neoplatonism in architecture. He stressed the importance of balance and harmony and added a mathematical precision similar to that of Filippo Brunelleschi. His style was innovative, featuring the solidity, clear composition, and the unity of parts, contributing to the foundation for modern architecture.

Title: Mural Painting
Description: Mural Painting, a form of expressive art painted directly onto walls or large surfaces, can be found in various art styles like fresco, graffiti, modernism, realism, and figurative. The purpose is to make art accessible to a broader audience while decorating or political messaging. Notable muralists include Diego Rivera, José Clemente Orozco, and David Alfaro Siqueiros.

Title: Multiple Media
Description: Multiple Media, an art style that incorporates numerous mediums in a single artwork, includes styles like collage, mixed-media, Dada, Futurism, and assemblage. The medium can be anything an artist wishes to use. The creation process in Multiple Media involves creating layered effects, textures, and depth to convey complex visual experiences. Artists notable for their work in this style include Robert Rauschenberg, Kurt Schwitters, and Marcel Duchamp.

Title: Visual Art
Description: Visual Art, a broad category of creative forms, includes styles like abstract, realism, impressionism, surrealism, and expressionism. Visual arts explore the aesthetic and conceptual potential of the visual world; it's typically displayed in galleries or museums. Renowned artists in this field include Pablo Picasso, Vincent Van Gogh, and Claude Monet.

Title: Nostalgic
Description: Nostalgic art style rouses sentimental feelings, often portraying vintage scenes and using soft lighting to enhance the mood. It brings in traits from vintage and retro art styles. The composition is usually detailed, and uses warm tones to enhance feelings of nostalgia. Notable artists include Norman Rockwell, Audrey Flack, and Jeremy Mann.

Title: Propaganda Art
Description: The Propaganda art style, typically dramatic and vivid, falls under Socialist Realism and Pop Art. Used primarily in political scenes, the composition is usually assertive, utilizing symbolic elements to convey messages. This style was largely seen in posters, with pioneering artists including Dmitri Moor, Shepard Fairey, and Ben Shahn.

Title: Political Art
Description: The Political art style encompasses a multitude of styles but is generally satirical or related to Pop Art. It is provocative and often uses direct lighting and contrasting colors to emphasize its narrative. Renowned artists such as Banksy, Ai Weiwei, and Guerrilla Girls have made significant contributions to this style.

Title: Anime Series
Description: The Anime Series art style is marked by its detailed compositions, bright colors, and varied lighting. This style exists predominantly in fantasy worlds and spans a wide range of moods and themes. Art styles such as Kawaii and Chibi are often seen. Prominent artists in this field include Hayao Miyazaki, Osamu Tezuka, and Mamoru Oshii.

Title: Shōjo
Description: The Shōjo art style, usually associated with romantic and magical girl themes, is most noticeable in school settings within manga. With soft lighting, pastel colors, and detailed compositions, it tends to evoke emotional responses. Artists like Yuu Watase, Ai Yazawa, and Yoko Kamio have made notable contributions to Shōjo Manga.

Title: Lenore Tawney
Description: Lenore Tawney is a significant figure in the post-war fiber arts movement. Known for her innovative work in weaving and her expressible textile art. Her style is often Modernism and Postmodernism characterized by an interlaced composition.

Title: Basketry
Description: Basketry is an art style related to the craft of making artifacts by weaving or sewing flexible materials into two- or three-dimensional artifacts. Artists like Ruth Asawa and Mary Jackson are known for their exceptional skills in this medium.

Title: Interlaced
Description: Interlaced, an art style rooted in Celtic and Islamic Art, is a design technique of interweaving bands, strips, or lines of contrasting color or material. It is often seen in pieces by Charles Rennie Mackintosh and Leonardo Da Vinci.

Title: Chinese Painting
Description: Chinese Painting is an ancient art style, emphasizing harmonious composition and natural lighting. Masters of this style include Qi Baishi, Zhang Daqian, and Xu Beihong. Styles are typically Ink and Wash, Gongbi, and Shan shui.

Title: Ink and Wash Painting
Description: Ink and Wash painting is an East Asian art style, typically seen in Chinese, Korean, and Japanese Painting. Characterized by its meditative mood and monochrome color scheme, figures like Shitao, Li Tang, and Zhang Daqian have left their mark on this style. The environment and lighting conditions often reflect natural outdoor scenes.

Title: Naturalistic
Description: Naturalistic art style, often associated with Realism and Photorealism, portrays the image as seen in nature with a focus on detail-oriented representation. Key elements include outdoor environments, natural light, and a varied color palette. The harmony brought by the balanced composition often results in a serene mood, capturing life in its purest form. This style has been adopted by artists ranging from da Vinci to Van Gogh.

Title: Medical Art
Description: The medical art style is highly precise and highly-detailed, focusing on anatomical, biological, and clinical imagery. Usually executed in controlled light conditions in a studio, the work often adopts a monochrome color scheme for clarity and to emphasize the clinical mood. This style's intricate composition portrays realistic medical conditions, anatomy or biological phenomenon.

Title: Scientific Art
Description: Scientific art style intricately merges the disciplines of art and science, often used to realistically illustrate various scientific phenomena and concepts. The style encompasses a variety of sub-genres, including anatomical, astronomical, and geological art. With a wide-ranging color palette and meticulous composition, it interprets scientific understanding in a visually educative manner.

Title: Radiography
Description: Radiography art style incorporates the use of X-rays to create visually arresting images, by revealing the internal structures of objects. Primarily in monochrome, this style establishes an inquisitive mood, often incorporating elements of medical and scientific art styles. Artists of note include Hugh Turvey and Nick Veasey, who have extensively explored this unique art style.

Title: Anatomical
Description: Anatomical art is a realism-based art style, focusing on accurate depiction of the human or animal body. It is closely associated with medical illustration and scientific art. This style is often characterized by neutral colors and realistic composition. Notable artists include Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo.

Title: Cinema
Description: Cinema art embodies a variety of styles including Film Noir, Neo-noir, German Expressionism, and more. The medium is film, with arranged lighting, various color schemes, and dynamic composition as key characteristics. Notable cinema artists include Federico Fellini and Jean-Luc Godard.

Title: Drama
Description: Drama art style is associated with intense mood and is often depicted through various mediums such as painting, sculpture, or performance art. This style is identifiable by a figurative composition, often narrating intense moments. Notable artists include Caravaggio and Edvard Munch.

Title: Psychological
Description: Psychological art style tends to provoke thought, embodying styles including Surrealism and Abstract Art. Medium change based upon message, but the mood is often provocative. Composition is subjective, often interpreted differently by separate individuals. Notables include Salvador Dali and Vincent Van Gogh.

Title: Eduardo Paolozzi
Description: Eduardo Paolozzi was an influential British sculptor and artist of the 20th century, heavily associated with the Pop Art movement. His works are characterized by a diverse color palette and the technique of assemblage, creating complex, multi-faceted sculptures. Other artists of the similar style include Richard Hamilton, David Hockney, and Peter Blake.

Title: Copy Art
Description: Copy Art style makes use of repetition in the composition, often seen in abstract expressionism and minimalism. The medium usually involves mixed media and can elicit a pensive mood. Major artists like Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein, and Jasper Johns have utilized this style in their works.

Title: Symbolic
Description: Symbolic art is predominantly characterized by the use of symbols to convey abstract concepts.
