It explores a variety of artistic styles including cubic, abstract, and minimalistic art. The color scheme can vary greatly depending on the artist's choice while painting being the most commonly used medium.

Title: Streamline Moderne
Description: Streamline Moderne art style, also known as Art Moderne, is an architectural style that emerged in the 1930s. It emphasizes curving forms, long lines, and sometimes nautical elements. Mostly seen in urban environments, the style is characterized by a simplified and sleek composition with a largely neutral color scheme.

Title: Organic Forms
Description: Organic Forms art style often involves the use of natural and biological forms as an inspiration. It is closely associated with Art Nouveau, Surrealism, Modernism, Abstract Expressionism and Biomorphism. The art medium of preference in this style is sculpture, with a strong emphasis on nature and use of natural color palette and asymmetrical composition. Notable artists include Henry Moore, Barbara Hepworth, Joan Miro, Jean Arp, and Isamu Noguchi.

Title: Pre-Raphaelite Art
Description: Pre-Raphaelite art style emerged as a rebellion against the industrial age and values of Victorian Art. It relates closely to Romanticism, Victorian Art, and Symbolism. The art primarily manifests in painting medium, featuring historical settings, natural light, vibrant colors, emotional themes, and highly detailed compositions. Notable artists include John Everett Millais, Dante Gabriel Rossetti, Edward Burne-Jones, and William Holman Hunt.

Title: Group of Seven Art
Description: Group of Seven art style is a form of art unique to Canadian artists, focusing primarily on Canadian landscape. Relating to Impressionism and Post-Impressionism, its paintings portray the inspirational beauty of the untouched Canadian wilderness, with art composed under natural outdoor light and characterized by bold, vivid colors. Crusaders of this style include Lawren Harris, A.Y. Jackson, J.E.H. MacDonald, Arthur Lismer, and Franklin Carmichael.

Title: Golden Age of Illustration Art
Description: The Golden Age of Illustration art style was characterized by Romanticism, Realism, and Art Nouveau. The preferred medium was drawings, with a focus on story-based environments evoking feelings of fantasy, using artificial light and silver and gold tones. The composition tends to be narrative, often used in books and magazines. Influential artists of this era include Arthur Rackham, Walt Disney, N.C. Wyeth, Howard Pyle, and Edmund Dulac.

Title: Realism Art
Description: Realism art style is characterized by the truthful and objective representation of the subject, aligning closely with Naturalism, Impressionism, and Social Realism. The preferred medium is painting, often depicting scenarios from everyday life under natural lighting conditions with true-to-life colors and a serious mood. The composition is usually very lifelike with realistic perspectives and proportions. Notable artists include Gustave Courbet, Jean-François Millet, Édouard Manet, Winslow Homer, and Thomas Eakins.

Title: Naïve Art
Description: Naïve Art is a visual art style characterized by a childlike simplicity and frankness. Paintings of this style typically feature a vague and often brightly colored representation of the visual world.

Title: Impressionism Art
Description: Impressionism Art is an art style that seeks to capture the sensory effects of a scene rather than physical detail, often portraying the fleeting visual impressions of the everyday world.

Title: Australian 19th-century Landscape Art
Description: Australian 19th-century Landscape Art reflects the unique spectacle of Australian nature, illustrating the tranquil and rich landscape of Australia's outback with a strong emphasis on light and color.

Title: Surrealism Art
Description: Surrealism Art is an artistic movement that seeks to depict the world of the unconscious, dreams, and fantasies. This art style is known for its unusual juxtapositions and non sequitur.

Title: Animal Art
Description: Animal Art style focuses on the realistic depiction of animals in their natural environment or mythological context. Its influence can be seen across various art styles, representing the relationship between humans and animals in different cultures.

Title: Cubism Art
Description: Cubism was an innovative art movement pioneered by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque. In Cubism, subjects are analyzed, broken up and reassembled in an abstracted form—instead of depicting objects from a single viewpoint, the artist depicts the subject from a multitude of viewpoints to represent the subject in a greater context.

Title: Victorian Art
Description: Victorian art is a term associated with the art produced during the reign of Queen Victoria (1837–1901). It was heavily influenced by both the industrial revolution and the romantic ideals of the time. The art often portrays historical scenes, daily life, and an idealized vision of nature.

Title: Occult Art
Description: Occult art is associated with symbolism and mysticism and often represents esoteric themes, spiritualism, and magic. Often dark and foreboding, these works can be both enigmatic and fascinating.

Title: Avant Garde
Description: Avant-garde is a term used to describe innovative approaches to art that are against the norm. It's associated with nonconformity and rejection of traditional artistic conventions.

Title: Experimental Fashion
Description: Experimental fashion pushes the boundaries of what is accepted as the norm or the status quo. It is often seen as an art, with designers challenging traditional norms with unique and bold designs.

Title: Dark Fantasy
Description: Dark Fantasy art style merges fantastical elements with darker, horrifying themes. This includes surreal and grim landscapes portrayed with a complex composition. Artists utilize a dark color palette and low-key lighting to evoke a sense of mystery and fear.

Title: Mesoamerican Art
Description: Mesoamerican art style prominently features sculpture medium, with designs heavily reliant on symbolic and complex geometrical patterns. The color palette often includes earthy tones. Despite being minimalistic in design, each piece carries significant historical and cultural value.

Title: Portuguese Tile Art
Description: The Portuguese Tile art style focuses primarily on ceramic medium, often decorated with blue and white patterns. Art styles like Azulejo, Baroque, and Rococo heavily influence the art concept. The intricate details of geometric and pictorial compositions evoke a strong sense of Portuguese history and culture.

Title: Moorish Art
Description: The Moorish Art style is predominant in architecture, displaying an intricate geometric composition. Imbued with earth tones, the art focuses on spiritual mood with elements of Andalusian Art, Berber Art, and Arabic Calligraphy.

Title: Ancient Babylonian Art
Description: Ancient Babylonian art, a branch of Mesopotamian art, predominantly utilizes sculpture medium. The art style embodies historical mood with narrative compositions and earth-toned color scheme. It is often associated with Akkadian, Assyrian, and Sumerian arts.

Title: Feminist Art
Description: Feminist art is a category of art associated with the late 1960s and 1970s feminist movement. The art style addresses the role of women in society and challenges the foundations of the art world itself. Mediums like painting are common. The mood often reflects empowerment, and figurative compositions prevail.

Title: Dramatic Art
Description: Dramatic Art involves the creation of hyperbolic, emotionally charged situations, often resulting in tense atmospheres and dynamic compositions. It is prevalent in theatre and analogously in visual arts, particularly in styles like Baroque and Gothic. Key artists include John Webster and Thomas Kyd.

Title: Ornate Art
Description: Ornate Art is marked by intricate, highly decorative aesthetics. Known for its detailed compositions, it often incorporates gold color in the art. Key styles include Baroque, Rococo, and Byzantine with notable artists like Gian Lorenzo Bernini and Jean-Honoré Fragonard.

Title: Grandeur
Description: Grandeur in art is expressed through a sense of majesty and greatness often found in Romanticism, Renaissance, and Baroque styles. Typical mediums include painting, and the mood set is exalted. Symmetrical compositions are common, featuring work from artists like Albrecht Dürer and Caravaggio.

Title: Dramatic Architecture
Description: Dramatic Architecture depicts a style characterized by bold, eye-catching designs that create an impactful aesthetic. Seen in the urban environment, key styles include Gothic, Baroque, and Brutalism. The compositions are oftentimes asymmetrical, and the color scheme is often monochromatic, applied through Chiaroscuro lighting. Zaha Hadid and Frank Gehry are renowned architects of this art style.

Title: Ornate Architecture
Description: Ornate Architecture Art Style embodies designs that are intricately detailed and richly decorated. Characterized by its grandeur and complexity, this art style can be seen in past eras like the Gothic, Baroque, Rococo, and Mughal. Artists like Antoni Gaudí and Bernini are known for their work in this style.

Title: Imposing
Description: The Imposing Art Style often conveys a sense of force, dominance, or grandness through its representation. It is frequently utilized in art forms like Expressionism, Suprematism, and Futurism, with artists like Jackson Pollock and Kazimir Malevich known for crafting such impactful work.

Title: Elaborate Fashion
Description: Elaborate Fashion Art Style is characterized by its detailed and intricate clothing designs. This art style is prevalent in Couture, Baroque, and Rococo fashions. Renowned fashion designers, such as Christian Dior and Yves Saint Laurent, have created extraordinary works in this style.

Title: Opulent Fashion
Description: The Opulent Fashion Art Style is associated with wealth and affluence, often featuring luxurious materials and extravagant designs. The style is embraced in Couture and Baroque fashions. Designers like Elie Saab and Alexander McQueen have produced stunning examples of this style.

Title: Extravagant
Description: Extravagant Art Style is typically characterized by excess, complexity, and richness, going beyond the ordinary or regular. It can be seen across various artistic trends such as the Baroque, Rococo, and Expressionism. Notable artists include Peter Paul Rubens and Gustav Klimt.

Title: Editorial Cartooning
Description: Editorial Cartooning is a form of art that uses drawing as its medium. It's usually associated with styles such as Cartooning, Satire, and Caricature. The mood of the art piece is often provocative, and it is typically set in a political context. Pioneers like Thomas Nast and Herbert Block have significantly contributed to this style.

Title: Crafts
Description: Crafts art style involves creating functional art pieces using various media. Common styles include Pottery, Textile Art, and Jewelry Making. The color scheme varies depending on the medium used. Famous artisans include William Morris and Bernard Leach, known for their innovative approach to crafts.

Title: Counterculture
Description: Counterculture is an art style that often utilizes vivid colors and mixed media. It's connected to styles like Pop Art, Graffiti, and Psychedelic Art and embodies a rebellious mood. The pieces can be placed in an urban environment and their composition could be chaotic. Notable artists in this style are Andy Warhol and Banksy.

Title: Cityscape Painting
Description: Cityscape Painting art style involves painting city life in a realistic or impressionist manner. The environment highlighted is the urban city, and the mood, light, and colors vary depending on the time of day depicted. Well-known artists of this style include Claude Monet and Edward Hopper.

Title: Horror
Description: The Horror art style often falls into Gothic, Surrealism, or Expressionism. The medium is usually painting, with dark tones and low lighting to create a frightening mood. The environment is generally dark and gloomy and the composition dramatic. Artists known for this style include Francisco Goya and Edvard Munch.

Title: Traditional African Cultural Mathematician Fractal Art
Description: Traditional African Cultural Mathematician Fractal art style uses abstract, geometric, symbolic patterns with fractal arrangements. This style is often vibrant, contrasting, and bears an intellectual mood. It's often painted, representing African tribal math concepts and cultures. Key artists like Ron Eglash, Helene J. Rother, and Hassan Musa are known for their explorations in this art style.

Title: Mathematical Art
Description: Mathematical art is a genre of art that employs both the aesthetic and formal aspects of mathematical theory. It often features geometric shapes, symmetry, and stylized presentation of mathematical concepts using varied mediums. It could be either two or three-dimensional and of any color scheme.

Title: Venetian School
Description: The Venetian School art style was a major movement during the Renaissance and Baroque periods, originating from Venice, Italy. It is recognized for the use of color, light and texture and primarily boasted paintings of religious and mythological themes. Artists used a unique method of layering and blending color to produce a rich, glowing effect.

Title: Horror Illustration
Description: Horror illustration is an art style depicting eerie and frightening scenes or entities. This genre of art is associated generally with the darker aesthetics in visual culture. Drawings capture an essence of fear and often use low light and dark tones. The composition can vary from organized to chaotic compositions, depending on the narratives presented.

Title: Flamboyant
Description: The flamboyant art style is characterized by a lavish and ornate aesthetic, with radiant light, vibrant colors, and an overall joyful mood. This style emphasizes the decorative aspect of art and often features elaborate compositions. It spans across a range of periods and movements, including Rococo and Art Nouveau.

Title: Erotic Photography
Description: Erotic photography is an art style that focuses on sensual and titillating imagery. It captures the eroticism and allure of the human form via deliberate compositions, often employing soft light and neutral tones. This art style is famed for its aesthetic appeal and freedom of expression, showcasing passion and intimacy at its core.

Title: Narrative Figuration
Description: Narrative Figuration, an art movement originating in the 1960s, focuses on artistically exploring and explaining complex concepts or stories through visual art, particularly through painting. The style features a multi-colored palette and employs eloquent moods captured through figural composition. Notable artists include Hannelore Baron, Eduardo Arroyo, and Peter Saul among others.

Title: Bold Colors
Description: The Bold Colors style is characterized by vibrant hues used in various painting styles, such as Pop Art and Fauvism. The choice of bold spectrum colors and dynamic composition create a lively, vibrant mood. Artists well-known for utilizing these bold colors include Piet Mondrian, Henri Matisse, and Paul Gauguin.

Title: Classic
Description: The Classic art style has roots in historical periods like the Renaissance, Romanticism, and Neoclassicism. With a fondness for sculptural mediums and neutral tone color schemes, the style exhibits an elegant and symmetrical composition offering an air of sophistication. Such classic artistry can be seen in works by Michelangelo, Leonardo da Vinci, and Johannes Vermeer.

Title: Contemporary Art Photography
Description: Contemporary Art Photography is an art style that captures images with underlying meanings and interpretation. The styles involve abstract expressionism, conceptual art, and photojournalism. Artists like Cindy Sherman and Andreas Gursky have made significant contributions. The compositions are often balanced, captured in both urban and rural environments with varied color schemes and lighting.

Title: Artistic Photography
Description: Artistic Photography is a style that emphasizes artistic expression and often leads the viewer to think or feel in a certain way. Styles include abstract, still life, and aerial photography. Renowned artists include Annie Leibovitz and Richard Avedon. The compositions are varied and often provoke reflective moods.

Title: Japanese Woodblock Printing
Description: Japanese Woodblock Printing is a technique characterized by a multistep process that results in a print. Styles include Ukiyo-e, Shin-hanga, and Sosaku hanga. Prominent artists include Hokusai and Hiroshige. The compositions are layered and the prints often evoke a peaceful mood.

Title: Block Printing
Description: Block Printing is an art style involving carving an image into wood or another material, then using it to create prints. Styles include woodcut, letterpress, and relief printing. Notable artists include Albrecht Durer and Katsushika Hokusai. The art portrays a quiet mood and the compositions are often symmetrical.

Title: Dark Fantasy Art
Description: Dark Fantasy Art is a genre that combines fantasy elements with a darker, often menacing or somber atmosphere. Styles include gothic, surrealism, and horror art. The scenarios are fantastical and dark with complex compositions that evoke a mysteriously alluring mood. Influential artists include H.R. Giger and Zdzisław Beksiński.

Title: Cyberpunk Art
Description: Cyberpunk Art encapsulates a dystopian futuristic perspective that often features an oppressive, urban setting. The genre embraces elements of science fiction, futurism, and noir, and it often uses mediums like digital art. Its color schemes consist of vibrant tones with a profound use of neon lighting. Renowned artists like Syd Mead, Josan Gonzalez, and Katsuhiro Otomo have significantly contributed to this art style.

Title: Narrative Art
Description: Narrative Art is an art style that tells a story within the artwork. The style varies depending on the story line and can include classical, realism, and romanticism. While the environment, color, and lighting can vary, the artwork generally delivers complex storytelling within the composition. Renowned artists like Hieronymus Bosch, Eugene Delacroix, and Pablo Picasso significantly worked within narrative art.

Title: Looney Tunes
Description: Looney Tunes exhibits a unique and recognizable art style within the animation realm. Using mediums like cartoon and caricature, the Looney Tunes series typically features a humorous disposition with exaggerated character features and movements. The works are usually set in a fantasy environment with a multicolored scheme. Some key artists associated with Looney Tunes include Chuck Jones, Tex Avery, and Friz Freleng.

Title: Television Art
Description: Television Art is a comprehensive term that encompasses different styles, including abstraction, expressionism, and realism. With film as the primary medium, the art style invariably uses moving images. The environment, color, mood, and lighting vary widely depending on the genre and subject matter. Notable artists within the realm of Television Art include Mary Blair, Norman Rockwell, and Saul Bass.

Title: Thriller
Description: The thriller art style is closely linked with cinema, characterized by elements of suspense, tension, and excitement. It often employs techniques from styles like film noir, Gothic, and surrealism to depict an urban setting. In visual aesthetics, this style tends to have a dynamic composition, monochromatic color themes, and low-key lighting.

Title: Social Commentary
Description: Social commentary art employs a variety of visual techniques and styles like political art, satire, and propaganda to communicate opinions or criticism about societal issues. These works tend to be provocative, using vibrant colors and a mix of mediums for a powerful impact.

Title: Horticulture
Description: Art inspired by horticulture often falls under styles such as botanical art or impressionism, focusing on depicting nature's beauty. These pieces typically exude peace, with natural color palettes, organic compositions and are usually created through painting techniques.

Title: Miniature
Description: Miniature art style is intricately detailed, typically featuring refined compositions. Often painted, it comprises styles like illumination, portraiture, and Persian miniature. Notable artists in this field include Nicholas Hilliard and Samuel Cooper.

Title: Japanese
Description: Characterized by styles such as Ukiyo-e, Nihonga, and Anime, the Japanese art style promotes a balanced composition, harmony, and natural colors. It often depicts traditional Japanese environments and is typically rendered through painting. Notable artists include Hokusai and Kazuki Takamatsu.

Title: Cell Shading
Description: Cell shading is a type of non-photorealistic rendering designed to make 2D illustrations and graphics appear more three-dimensional. It utilizes flat colors and sharp edges often seen in comic arts or graphic novels. The cell shading art style is also typically used in video games and animations, which is distinguishable through defined outlines, sharp lighting, and bright color schemes.

Title: Glowing Aesthetic
Description: The glowing aesthetic art style involves the use of vibrant colors and intense lights to create a radiant, ethereal atmosphere. It's often seen in neon art, light art, and digital art, set in a dark environment to emphasize the brightness and vibrance of the design. The glut of neon and radiating composition adds an ethereal mood to the artwork.

Title: Cel-shading
Description: Cel-shading is a technique used in 3D rendering that makes the final visual appear two-dimensional or flat, often seen in anime, illustrations, cartoons, and video games. Saturated colors and no gradient shading is a common characteristic of this art style, creating a high contrast lighting effect that simplifies shading and creates a cartoonish aesthetic.

Title: Open World
Description: The open world art style is often observed in video games featuring expansive environments that can be explored freely. The open-ended structure encourages an explorative mood among players. The visual composition includes various sceneries, terrains, structures, and objects that construct a detailed and immersive experience.

Title: Indigenous Art
Description: Indigenous art is a visual expression incorporating tribal and folk art styles, often rooted in the customs and traditions of indigenous cultures worldwide. It routinely uses painting as a medium, employs earth tone colors reflecting natural elements, and depicts a spiritual mood. This art form often includes imagery and symbolism inherent to the respective culture.

Title: Character Design
Description: Character Design art style is a fundamental aspect of visual art, primarily in fields like animation and comic books. Artists like Walt Disney and Hayao Miyazaki have used this style to develop unique, vibrant characters. The style, mood, composition, and color vary greatly, encapsulating the essence of the character.

Title: Animal Painting
Description: The Animal Painting art style captures the essence of the animal kingdom in different art styles like Realism and Surrealism. Artists such as Ray Harris-Ching and Bruno Liljefors focus on capturing the natural environment and the behavior of the animals, often using natural lighting and varied colors.

Title: Archaeological
Description: Archaeological art style refers to visual depictions associated with historical significance and antiquity. Works characterized by this style, found in sculptures and other archaeological artifacts, often exhibit earthen tones and classical themes. Artists well-respected in this field include Antonio Canova and Praxiteles.

Title: Mannerism
Description: Mannerism art style represents the period between the High Renaissance and Baroque. It's characterized by exaggerated postures, dramatic lighting, elegant moods, and asymmetrical compositions. Notable artists include El Greco and Parmigianino.

Title: Fairy Tale Illustration
Description: Fairy Tale Illustration art style largely caters to storybooks, concentrating on whimsical, vibrant, and fantastical representations to accompany the narrative. famed artists like Arthur Rackham and Beatrix Potter have significantly contributed to this style.

Title: Romantic Nationalism
Description: Romantic Nationalism is an art concept based on national identity. Often through painting, artists depict historical landscapes using warm colors, expressing patriotic moods. The Romantic Nationalism art style is often seen in Romanticism, Historicism, and Folk Art, with notable artists such as Caspar David Friedrich and Johan Christian Dahl.

Title: Book Cover Illustration
Description: Book Cover Illustration art style varies in style and mood, reflecting the theme of the book it represents. This art form employs various art styles, from Realism to Pop Art and Graphic Design. Renowned Book Cover artists include Chip Kidd and Peter Mendelsund.

Title: Lighting Installations
Description: Lighting Installations art style is a form of Installation Art, Contemporary Art, and Conceptual Art. Artists use mixed media to create immersive experiences using artificial light indoors or outdoors. Notable artists in this field include James Turrell and Dan Flavin.

Title: Superhero Art
Description: Superhero Art style is often vivid and heroic, characterized by dramatic lighting and dynamic poses. The style is seen in Pop Art, Comic Art, and Concept Art, with prominent artists like Jack Kirby and Steve Ditko. Most notably, this art style is showcased in comics, in diverse urban landscapes.

Title: Animation Art
Description: Animation Art style is characterized by sequential, vibrant artwork often seen in film. Styles vary between Anime, 3D Animation, and Stop Motion. Hayao Miyazaki and Walt Disney are celebrated artists in this field. The mood, lighting, and environment change in line with the narrative.

Title: Figurative Sculpture
Description: Figurative Sculpture art style relates to realistic representations of human or animal figures, often inspired by Classical Greek, Renaissance and Modern styles. The sculpture form allows for three-dimensional, tangible compositions, often placed in outdoor environments. The mood is diverse and can invoke various emotions based on the artist's interpretation.

Title: Experimental Design
Description: The Experimental Design art style is characterized by breaking traditional rules and forms. It utilizes various art styles like Surrealism, Minimalism, or Postmodernism. The medium is usually mixed media in a studio environment with studio lighting. The color scheme is diverse, as is the mood - capturing a spirit of innovation and non-tradition.

Title: Line Drawing
Description: The Line Drawing art style simplifies the artist's interpretation into lines and shapes, often incorporating Abstract, Expressionism or Impressionism styles. The mood is subtle, created with a monochrome color scheme in two dimensions. Typically, this style is created in an indoor studio with controlled lighting.

Title: Superhero Comic Art
Description: The Superhero Comic Art style is distinguished by its vibrant and dramatic mood, often depicting urban environments. Its composition is in the form of sequential panels that tell a story. Art styles like Pop Art, Graffiti, and Expressionism greatly influence the genre. The medium of choice is typically illustration.

Title: Cartoon Animation
Description: The Cartoon Animation art style is characterized by frame-by-frame movement, brought to life through various animation techniques like Anime, CGI, Stop-motion and more. They often depict vibrant, light-hearted scenes with artificial lighting in a studio environment.

Title: Steampunk Artists
Description: Steampunk as an art style blends Victorian aesthetics with elements of science fiction and fantasy. Artworks often compose of industrial machinery with a retro-futuristic design, usually presented in sepia tone. Notable artists like James Ng, Megan Baehr, and Cliff Overton are known for their works in this genre.

Title: Cartoonists
Description: Cartoonists represent a unique art style, often distinguished by its exaggerated features, colorful palette and figurative composition. They focus on creating drawings that are usually satirical or humorous. Renowned cartoonists include Charles Schulz, Bill Watterson, and Jim Davis.

Title: Geodesic Dome
Description: A Geodesic Dome represents a modernist structural art style. It's a spherical form in which triangular or polygonal faces composed of light skeletal structure distribute the structural stress. Buckminster Fuller was instrumental in popularizing this concept.

Title: Pin-up
Description: Pin-up is an art style famously known for its representation of alluring and often provocative images of women. Artists like Gil Elvgren, Alberto Vargas, and George Petty have greatly contributed to this art style, crafting sensual, predominantly multicolored, figurative works.

Title: Glamour
Description: The glamour art style is associated typically with fashion and cinema, often captured through the medium of photography. It exudes an aura of elegance and often features high contrast color schemes. Well-known artists in this domain include George Hurrell, Cecil Beaton, and Horst P. Horst.

Title: Animated Cartoon
Description: Animated Cartoon as an art style is primarily associated with digital media and is marked by its creative range of animation methods such as Anime, Cartoon, and 3D Animation. Artists like Walt Disney and Hayao Miyazaki have made significant contributions in this area. Subjects and moods in animated cartoons are far-reaching, but are often characterized by their vibrant colors and imaginary settings, reflecting the boundless potentials of this medium.

Title: Pop Artists
Description: Pop Artists work within the Pop Art style, which emerged in the mid-20th century as a response to consumer culture and mass media. Associated with artists like Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein, Pop Art often makes use of mixed media and introduces vibrant colors and flat, bold compositions. The work usually has an optimistic mood and is set against urban environments, reflecting the influence of contemporary culture.

Title: Comic Artists
Description: Comic Artists follow the Comic Art style, which extends across a range of sub-genres like Manga, Graphic Novel and Superhero Comics. The art generally involves illustration with vibrant colors and high contrast, developing in sequential frames that narrate a story. Artists like Jack Kirby, Neil Gaiman, and Mark Millar have popularized this style across different environments and moods.

Title: Fairy Tale
Description: The Fairy Tale art style is distinguished by its fantastical worlds and magical settings, often depicted using illustration and fantasy art styles. There's a fairytale-like mood conveyed through vibrant colors, magical lighting, and mystical scenes. Artists like Arthur Rackham and Kay Nielsen have significant contributions in this area.

Title: Architects
Description: Architects work in the field of architectural art, a medium that has various styles including Modernist, Brutalist, and Futuristic, among others. Architects like Frank Lloyd Wright and Zaha Hadid have made significant contributions to this field. Architectural art often features neutral colors, natural lighting, and is set in both urban and rural environments. The composition is deeply tied to functionality and structure.

Title: Traditional Art
Description: Traditional Art largely covers art styles that originated before the 20th century. It includes a broad range of styles from Realism to Baroque. Traditional art primarily employs painting as a medium, using a multicolor palette. The art is usually balanced in composition.

Title: Dreamscape Photography
Description: Dreamscape Photography is an art style that blends elements of Abstract and Surrealism. The medium is primarily photography, often set in an outdoor environment, with varied lighting conditions. The mood captured is dreamy, and the composition tends to be surreal.

Title: Neue Sachlichkeit
Description: Neue Sachlichkeit, or New Objectivity, is an art style rooted in realism and expressionism. The majority of Neue Sachlichkeit art is done via the medium of painting. The mood is often sober, emphasizing the harsh realities of life, and it is known for its detailed composition.

Title: Disney
Description: The Disney art style is iconic and features a unique blend of cartoon and animation. The primary medium is animation, usually set in vibrant and fictional worlds. Composition is fluid and flowing. Well known artists from this style are Walt Disney, Ub Iwerks, among others.

Title: Interior Painting
Description: Interior Painting as a style can vary greatly, though commonly features elements of Modernism and Minimalism. The medium is painting, typically set in indoor environments. The mood can vary depending on the artist's intent, and the composition is often spatial.

Title: Swedish Impressionism
Description: Swedish Impressionism is an art style characterized by vibrant colors, natural light, and casual compositions. It often depicts outdoor environments and is associated with artists like Anders Zorn and Carl Larsson.

Title: Biedermeier
Description: The Biedermeier art style arose during the Romantic period characterized by its subdued colors, soft lighting, and rigid compositions. Associated artists include Georg Friedrich Kersting and Carl Spitzweg, the style often depicts peaceful indoor scenes.

Title: Italian Renaissance
Description: Italian Renaissance is an art style marked by a return to Classical influences, characterized by balanced compositions, natural colors, and contrasting lighting. Associated with monumental artists like Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Raphael.

Title: Glass Art
Description: Glass Art is a style that falls under the Contemporary art movement, focusing on the manipulation of glass into creative designs. Characterized by vibrant colors, geometric compositions, and associated with artists such as Dale Chihuly and Louis Comfort Tiffany.

Title: Haute Couture
Description: Haute Couture is an art style associated with the world of fashion, commonly seen in Modern and Contemporary design. It is characterized by extravagant and complex designs, typically showcased on the runway. Influential haute couture designers include Christian Dior, Coco Chanel, and Karl Lagerfeld.

Title: Sound Art
Description: Sound Art is an artistic discipline where sound is utilized as a primary medium. Like many genres of contemporary art, sound art may be interdisciplinary in nature, or be used in hybrid forms. Sound art often intersects with other forms of art such as performance, installation, and music.

Title: Ancient Egyptian Art
Description: Ancient Egyptian Art refers to the style of painting, sculpture, crafts, and architecture developed by the civilization in the Nile Valley from 5000 BCE to 300 CE. It is characterized by a sense of order, clear and simple lines, and symbolism.

Title: Funerary Art
Description: Funerary art is any work of art forming, or placed in, a repository for the remains of the dead. The term encompasses a wide variety of forms, including cenotaphs, tomb-like monuments which don't contain human remains, and communal memorials to the dead, such as war memorials, which may or may not contain remains.

Title: Stone Carving
Description: Stone carving is an artistic form where pieces of rough natural stone are shaped by the controlled removal of stone. It is one of the oldest forms of artistic expression.

Title: Industrial Architecture
Description: Industrial architecture is a style that incorporates elements of historic factories, warehouses and other industrial structures into aesthetic design. It is characterized by simplicity, and a utilitarian, efficient, and cost-effective design.

Title: Botanical Art
Description: Botanical art style focuses on the realistic representation of plants and nature, commonly using painting as a medium. The style originates from naturalism and realism, and the color palette typically consists of natural hues to accurately depict plant life. The artwork often reflects a peaceful mood and organic arrangement.

Title: Lettering
Description: Lettering art style, often used in calligraphy, typography, and graffiti, works primarily with ink to create intricate text design. This style is characterized by a variety of colors and is mainly recognized by its linear arrangement of letters that create an aesthetic rhythm.

Title: Lacework
Description: The lacework art style, prominently featured in Victorian and Baroque eras, utilized textiles to create complex designs. The art is typically white or off-white and characterized by an elegant mood. Notably, the composition showcases a delicate and intricate arrangement.

Title: Sketching
Description: Sketching is an art style connected with realism, impressionism, and surrealism. Typically, artists use pencils for sketching, which results in a monochrome color scheme. Regardless of the setting, sketching often conveys an intimate mood and features a freeform composition.

Title: Macabre
Description: The macabre art style, associated with gothic and surrealistic styles, often uses painting as its medium. The artworks are set in dark environments with low lighting and dark color tones. The mood is typically disturbing, and the composition relies on dramatic arrangements.

Title: Underground Comix
Description: Underground Comix is a term referring to an alternative art movement that emerged in the 1960s, focusing on the counterculture of the time, using a comic or graphic novel format. The art style is often more personalized and grotesque, combining illustrative drawings with bold, multicolored visuals.

Title: American Scene Painting
Description: American Scene Painting refers to a naturalistic style of painting and other works of art of the 1920s and 1930s in the United States. Artworks of this style often portray rural or small-town America.

Title: Regionalism
Description: Regionalism is an American art movement that emerged in the Midwest in the early 20th century. The paintings predominantly depict rural life themes with a realistic color palette. It is closely related to American Scene Painting and often conveys a nostalgic mood.

Title: Western Art
Description: Western Art primarily depicts themes of the American West. The art style is known for its adventurous spirit and is often characterized by a natural color palette. It combines many art styles like Realism and Romanticism. The environment is often set in the 'Wild West', capturing landscapes, cowboys, Native Americans, and life on the American frontier.

Title: Silent Film
Description: Silent Film art style, synonymous with early 20th century cinema, often uses exaggerated expressions and pantomime to compensate for the lack of sound, making Expressionism and Surrealism key art styles. The Mood can be described as 'Dramatic' due to the narrative nature of the medium.

Title: Space Art
Description: Space Art is an art style that depicts scenes of outer space. It combines elements of Realism and Science Fiction. Space Art typically uses cool colors to capture the vastness of space and diffused light to produce a 'Mystical' mood. The composition mainly focuses on offering a perspective.

Title: Cute
Description: Associated with Japanese art and animation, the Cute art style, otherwise known as 'Kawaii' or 'Chibi', often features character-centered compositions set in fantasy environments. The color schemes are typically soft pastels, creating a 'Joyful' mood and soft lighting.

Title: Wang Xizhi
Description: Wang Xizhi was a Chinese writer and official, recognized as the 'Sage of Calligraphy.' His style is classic and elegant, demonstrating fluid movements and meticulous brushwork. His main medium was ink.

Title: Zhao Mengfu
Description: Zhao Mengfu was a renowned Chinese calligrapher and painter during the Yuan Dynasty. Known for his monochrome ink-and-brush paintings, his deeply cultural work often employed Chinese Painting techniques, placing a large emphasis on brushwork and ink preparation.

Title: Dong Qichang
Description: Dong Qichang was an iconic figure in the art of the Ming Dynasty. Known for his ink and wash art, he maintained a monochrome colour palette and his work often reflects landscapes. He has a reflective mood in a majority of his compositions.

Title: Ink Wash
Description: Ink Wash is a type of Chinese art that emerged prominently during the Ming and Qing dynasties. Executed in monochrome palette, this style usually depicts landscapes using ink and water. Artists like Wu Changshuo, Qi Baishi, Dong Qichang and Bada Shanren are known for this style.

Title: Brush
Description: Brush art involves using a brush to apply mediums like oil or watercolor to a surface. This style often varies greatly in its environment, lighting, color and composition. Renowned artists like Vincent van Gogh, Claude Monet, Pierre-Auguste Renoir are known for their brushwork.

Title: Writing
Description: The art style of Writing involves the visual arrangement of text in a manner that influences its meaning. This can include styles like Concrete Poetry and Calligraphy, usually rendered in ink on paper and mostly in a monochrome colour scheme, it includes artists like e e cummings and Gu Wenda.

Title: Bada Shanren
Description: Bada Shanren was a renowned painter during the Ming and Qing Dynasties. He is known for his monastic mood, monochrome colour scheme and landscape compositions in his paintings.

Title: 3D Art
Description: 3D art style is a genre of art that creates a three-dimensional physical representation of visual forms that are tangible or semi-tangible. This style is predominantly seen in sculpture, digital, and installation art genres.

Title: Editorial Photography
Description: Editorial Photography art style is a branch of photography that features images aiming to tell a story or express an idea in a story's context. These photos can be in color or black and white, with lighting conditions depending on the desired effect or story requirements.

Title: Monumental Art
Description: Monumental art style involves large-scale sculptures or installations in public spaces, often linked with public art, architectural sculpture, or site-specific art. Noteworthy for their impressive size and impact, these works dynamically interact with their surrounding environment.

Title: Theatrical Costume Design
Description: Theatrical Costume Design art style involves the creation of attire for characters in theater, mirroring the story, era, and character traits in visual form. This style intersects with fashion design, textile art, and performance art.

Title: Visual Storytelling
Description: Visual Storytelling art style employs visual imagery to transmit narrative content. Illustrations, animations, and graphic designs are frequently used mediums to bring stories to life with a series of images that flow sequentially.

Title: Traditional Animation
Description: Traditional Animation, often referred to as cell animation, is a hand-drawn animation technique where each frame of a cartoon is drawn individually. The art colors are typically bright and vibrant with fictional characters and environments.

Title: Neoclassical Fashion
Description: Neoclassical Fashion is a style of fashion influenced by the themes and aesthetics of the neoclassical period. Often featuring lightweight, flowing garments, and pastel color palettes, it conveys a sense of elegance and class.

Title: Baroque Art
Description: Baroque Art is a dramatic, emotional style that emerged in the 17th century. It uses contrast between light and dark to achieve a sense of movement and employs rich colors and intricate details to evoke a sense of grandiosity.

Title: En Plein Air Painting
Description: En Plein Air Painting is a style of painting done outdoors in natural light, often rapidly to capture the changing qualities of light and color in the landscape. Artists focus on the natural aspects of the environment, portraying it with vivid, often impressionistic colors.

Title: Will Vinton
Description: Will Vinton was an animator known for developing the Claymation technique. His distinctive art style featured colored, mouldable clay animated in fantasy worlds. Besides Claymation, Vinton's creativity also extended to the realm of stop-motion animation.

Title: Japanese Animation
Description: Japanese Animation, conventionally known as 'Anime', demonstrates characteristics such as vibrant colors, fantastical elements, culturally embedded themes, and a rich variety in mood and tone. In anime, character designs and settings can vary greatly, from lifelike designs to highly stylized ones, delving from the essential urban settings to abstract, supernatural realms. The lighting often creates dramatic, high contrast scenes, accentuating the distinct composition of the art. The art medium most commonly observed is digital art, but traditional methods are also used.

Title: Chanel
Description: Chanel is renowned for its revolution in women's fashion, introducing a stronger emphasis on comfort yet maintaining elegance and simplicity. The artistic style of Chanel is signified by its clean lines, minimalism, and the strong influence of Art Nouveau and Cubism. The brand disregarded the norms of the early 20th century and pursued a more practical and accessible approach towards fashion. Coco Chanel originally spearheaded this movement, and it has been further evolved by Karl Lagerfeld and now Virginie Viard.

Title: Yves Saint Laurent
Description: Internationally acclaimed fashion designer, Yves Saint Laurent encapsulated his distinctive couture aesthetics influenced by cubism, art deco, and pop art. His designs were distinguishable by boldness and flamboyance, utilizing geometric patterns and audacious color palettes. Saint Laurent has radically transformed the fashion sphere through his innovative and unconventional ideas, like introducing the concept of luxury prêt-à-porter. His artistic sense has been further evolved by designers Stefano Pilati, Hedi Slimane, and currently, Anthony Vaccarello.

Title: Utilitarian
Description: The utilitarian art style is primarily characterized by its functionality and efficiency. It conceives the philosophy that the practical purpose of a design or art is paramount, often eclipsing aesthetic concern. Influences of minimalism can be noted, with an emphasis on simplicity and symmetry. Functionalism and Industrial are other associated art styles. The mood rendered through this style is often one of practicality and usability. However, the mediums used and the artists associated can be diverse.

Title: Golden Age of Illustration
Description: The Golden Age of Illustration was an era of unprecedented excellence in the field of book and magazine illustrations during the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Characterized by a highly detailed and contrasted style, compositions were often brimming with fantasy elements, reflecting a sense of whimsy and charm. The color palette varied greatly, from subdued tones to vibrant hues. Influenced by realism, art nouveau, and impressionism, it witnessed the crucial works of renowned artists such as Norman Rockwell, Maxfield Parrish, and Arthur Rackham, among others.

Title: American Art Deco
Description: American Art Deco art style, originated in the 1920s and 1930s, is an energetic, vibrant style characterized by geometric composition and sharp lighting. The art style is influenced by modernism, cubism, and futurism and its major elements depict urban environment.

Title: Hannah Höch
Description: Hannah Höch was a German Dada artist who is best known for her provocative photomontage and collage work. Her art, often in monochrome, features a fragmented composition and contrast lighting, provoking deeper thought. Her style drew heavily on the Dada and Photomontage movements.

Title: Wet Plate Photography
Description: Wet Plate Photography is an early photographic technique that was practiced in the mid-19th century. The style is characterized by sepia coloring, natural lighting and a sense of historical mood due to its realistic composition.

Title: Visual Note-taking
Description: Visual Note-taking is a drawing-based technique used to visually represent information. Its multicolor style is typically informative and features flowing composition. It takes inspiration from infographics and illustration styles, with the environment being educational.

Title: Children's Illustration
Description: Children's Illustration is an art form designed to appeal to children, often found in children's books. The style features vivid colors, narrative composition, and joyful mood. It often involves drawings with bright lighting, depicting a fantasy environment. The styles of Cartoon and Anime strongly influence it.

Title: Cosplay
Description: Cosplay art style is commonly associated with two main art styles: Pop Art and Modern. Main elements include costume design, character portrayal, and fun mood. It typically takes place in conventions. Popular artists in this space include Yaya Han, Jessica Nigri, and D-Piddy.

Title: TV Show
Description: The TV Show art style is often associated with Realism, Surrealism, and Abstract styles. Key elements consist of film medium, frame composition, vibrant colors, and a controlled environment often inside studios with artificial lighting. Renowned creators in this domain include David Lynch, Vince Gilligan, and Joss Whedon.

Title: Childhood
Description: Childhood art style is marked by styles such as Impressionism, Pop Art, and Surrealism. The primary medium is drawing, often set in rural environments with bright, joyful colors. Simplicity in composition is another major element. Notable artists include Pablo Picasso, Jean-Michel Basquiat, and Joan Miro.

Title: Comedic
Description: The Comedic art style leans towards Pop Art, Caricature, and Cartoon. This style's major elements include drawing medium, humorous mood, and exaggerated composition. Prominent artists associated with this style are Gary Larson, Matt Groening, and Charles Schultz.

Title: Art Medium
Description: The Art Medium style is a diverse area that includes a wide range of styles such as Abstract, Impressionism, Surrealism, Realism, and Cubism. The medium varies across artists and art styles. Renowned artists such as Pablo Picasso, Vincent Van Gogh, Salvador Dalí, Rembrandt, and Georgia O'Keeffe have used diverse mediums to express their artistry.

Title: Childish
Description: Childish art style is often associated with Naive, Primitive, Folk, Outsider, and Illustration styles. The medium of choice is usually drawing, simple in composition, embodying a joyful mood. Artists notable for this style include Henri Rousseau, Alfred Wallis, and Grandma Moses.

Title: Expressionist
Description: Expressionist art style revolves around Abstract, Fauvism, Symbolism, Surrealism, and Dadaism styles. This style is typically displayed through painting with a focus on representing emotional experience, rather than physical reality. It often portrays a mood of angst and uses distorted composition. Noted artists include Edvard Munch, Egon Schiele, and Wassily Kandinsky.

Title: Atmospheric
Description: Atmospheric art style falls under Impressionism, Tonalism, Luminism, and Romanticism styles. Predominantly in painting medium, this style is known for its outdoor environments, diffused lighting, and muted colors to convey an aerial perspective. Noteworthy artists in this field include J.M.W. Turner, Claude Monet, and John Constable.

Title: Sunset
Description: Sunset art style gravitates towards Landscape, Romanticism, and Impressionism styles, featuring warm lighting and often employing shades of orange. This tranquil art style commonly presents a clear horizon composition. Artists associated with this style include Frederic Edwin Church, J.M.W. Turner, and Claude Monet.

Title: Yarn
Description: The Yarn art style, rooted in the Textile, Fiber, Tapestry, Knitting, and Crochet styles, utilizes fabric as its preferred medium. Artists historically influential in this art style include Sheila Hicks, Miriam Schapiro, and Faith Ringgold.

Title: Needlework
Description: Needlework art style is a form of textile-focused art that uses stitching techniques to create intricate, patterned designs. Embroidery, Cross-stitch, Crewel, Quilling and Bargello are notable styles. Notable artists include Elizabeth Parker, Mary Queen of Scots, Jane Bostocke, Richelieu, and Betty Ring. The needlework medium usually engages fabrics. The color scheme is often multicolor, with moods tending towards the delicate.

Title: Thread
Description: Thread art style includes styles such as Thread painting, Embroidery, Weaving, Quilting, and Macramé. It tends to use a layered composition in textile medium. The color scheme is usually vibrant and multicolored. Artists like Sheila Hicks, Alberto Burri, Sabatina Leccia, Tracey Emin, and Joana Vasconcelos are associated with the thread art style.

Title: Vintage Animation
Description: Vintage Animation art style includes Cel animation, Stop-motion, Cutout animation, Silhouette animation, and Puppetry. The medium used in Vintage Animation is usually celluloid film. These animations typically exist as 2D cartoons, with artificial lighting, generally in black and white. Vintage Animation is associated with artists like Walt Disney, Ub Iwerks, Max Fleischer, Chuck Jones, and John Halas.

Title: Adam Elliot
Description: Adam Elliot is an animator particularly known for his Stop-motion and Clay animation styles. His work often uses clay as a medium, within the environment of animated film. Elliot's animation tends to convey melancholic moods with muted colors and soft lighting. Relevant artists in a similar style are Nick Park, Barry Purves, Jiri Trnka, Ray Harryhausen, and Frank Mouris.

Title: Anna Atkins
Description: Anna Atkins is a botanist and photographer known for her Pictorialism, Photograms, and Alternative process photography styles. She utilizes photography in nature environments. Atkins's compositions are typically symmetrical, colored with hues of Cyanotype blue, often conveying peaceful moods. Her style resonates with the work of artists like László Moholy-Nagy, Man Ray, Christian Marclay, Calvert Richard Jones, and Heinrich Riffarth.

Title: Alternative Fashion
Description: Alternative Fashion is an art style characterized by vibrant, rebellious, and often asymmetric designs that defy mainstream fashion norms. It encompasses various sub-styles like Gothic, Punk, Steampunk, Emo, and Lolita. Notable artists include Vivienne Westwood, Malcolm McLaren, and Alexander McQueen.

Title: Interactive Art
Description: Interactive Art is an art style that engages the viewer directly, often through digital media. Works in this style occur within an immersive space, and the lighting conditions vary to enhance viewer experience. Sub-styles include Digital Art, Kinetic Art, Virtual Reality, Augmented Reality, and Installation Art with artists like Scott Snibbe, Rafael Lozano-Hemmer, and Golan Levin as key figures.

Title: Ready-made
Description: Ready-made is an ironic art style that utilizes 'found objects' in their inherent state as art. This style is associated with concepts such as Dadaism and Conceptual Art. Artists known for working with this style include Marcel Duchamp, Damien Hirst, and Man Ray.

Title: Louis Daguerre
Description: Louis Daguerre, a historical photographer, significantly contributed to the art style of early photography, particularly 'Daguerreotype'. His works are known for their reality-captured compositions. He was contemporary with other pioneers of photography such as William Henry Fox Talbot and Nicephore Niepce.

Title: Early Photography
Description: Early Photography is an art style characterized by reality capture compositions, natural lighting, and a monochrome color scheme. Distinct styles within this category include Daguerreotype, Calotype, and Tintype. Central figures in the development of this style are Louis Daguerre, William Henry Fox Talbot, and George Eastman.

Title: Gritty
Description: The Gritty art style is often associated with Urban and Street Art. Typical works in this style are paintings set in an urban environment. The lighting is usually highly contrasted and the color schemes often involve dark tones. The mood is typically dreary and the compositions are often cluttered. Associated artists include Banksy and Shepard Fairey.

Title: Victorian Gothic
Description: The Victorian Gothic art style merges Gothic Art with Victorian Art, mostly in architecture. These artworks are usually based in urban settings. The often dimly lit, dark-toned designs convey melancholy moods. The compositions interestingly feature asymmetry. Augustus Pugin and Eugène Viollet-le-Duc are known for their work in this style.

Title: Retro-futurism
Description: Retro-futurism combines Futurism with Art Deco in illustration. The setting is usually a vibrant, futuristic urban environment. The use of vivid colors suggests an optimistic mood, while the abstract composition hints at imaginative possibilities. Artists associated with Retro-futurism include Syd Mead and Roger Dean.

Title: Death Metal Art
Description: The Death Metal art style is notably seen in Gothic and Horror Art, specifically album cover art. Featuring dark fantasy environments and contrasted lighting, the art usually has dark color schemes. The mood is often disturbing and the composition can be overwrought. Prominent artists in this style are Dan Seagrave and Vincent Locke.

Title: Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood
Description: The Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood art style blends Pre-Raphaelite Art with Romanticism, primarily in painting. Generally set in natural surroundings, these artworks illuminate soft lighting and vivid color schemes. The mood they evoke is reflective and meditative, with symmetrical compositions. The style is associated with artists such as John Everett Millais and Dante Gabriel Rossetti.

Title: Giallo
Description: Giallo is an Italian 20th-century genre of mystery, typically in cinema, characterized by its blend of horror and crime fiction. The distinctive 'Giallo' art style often incorporates high contrast colors, dramatically bold and often non-linear composition, and has a mysteriously terrifying mood.

Title: Academic
Description: Academic art is a style of painting and sculpture produced under the influence of the art academies. In this art style, artists work is characterized by vibrant colors, a formal mood, and a balanced composition. This art often follows the teachings of Neoclassicism, Realism, and Romanticism.

Title: Action Role-Playing Game
Description: The Action Role-Playing Game art style commonly incorporates elements from fantasy and sci-fi genres and often uses digital art mediums. These games create glamorous environments in imaginative worlds, with varying lighting, dynamic compositions, and an adventurous mood.

Title: Apocalyptic
Description: The apocalyptic art style is characterized by a post-apocalyptic environment that often uses dark lighting, desaturated colors, and a chaotic composition. The mood is typically gloomy, reflecting the dystopian themes commonly associated with this style.

Title: Action-Adventure
Description: The Action-Adventure art style relevant to video games often involves elements from fantasy, realistic, and comic styles. The game environments are typically set in fictitious worlds with dynamic lighting, vivid colors, and an overall exciting mood. The composition is action-packed, reflecting the genre’s runtime thrill.

Title: Psychological Thriller
Description: Psychological Thriller art style often utilizes the medium of film, set in urban scenes with a dominant low key lighting. It tends to use asymmetrical compositions and a monochromatic color scheme to evoke a mood of angst. The art style is closely related to Expressionism, Surrealism, and Film Noir, with notable artists being Alfred Hitchcock, David Lynch, and Christopher Nolan.

Title: Inking
Description: Inking art style commonly uses the medium of illustration, often layering stark black lines on a white backdrop for maximum contrast. Its compositions are line-based and the art style is closely associated to Printmaking, Graphic Art and Manga. Notable artists using this style include Winsor McCay, Bill Watterson and Akira Toriyama.

Title: Editorial
Description: Editorial art style typically uses the print medium, and the compositions are balanced with bold colors to catch the reader's attention. It is often associated with art styles such as Graphic Design, Collage, and Pop Art. Relevant artists include Noma Bar, Pablo Picasso, and Roy Lichtenstein.

Title: Long Exposure
Description: Long Exposure art style focuses on the medium of photography. This art style uses both natural and artificial light to create a dynamic composition that shows passage of time, displaying a full spectrum of colors. It is closely associated with Abstract art, Time-Lapse Photography, Light Painting. Noteworthy artists include Michael Kenna, Alexey Titarenko, and Hiroshi Sugimoto.

Title: Functionality
Description: Functionality art style is a concept rooted in simplifying form to emphasize function, seen in art styles such as Modernism, Industrial art and Minimalism. Notable artists in this domain include Frank Gehry, Dieter Rams, and Charles Eames.

Title: Detail-oriented
Description: The Detail-oriented art style is known for its emphasis on portraying intricate details in a manner that mirrors reality. Often associated with art styles such as realism and hyperrealism, the focus is on capturing minute details with accuracy and precision. This technique is commonly employed in indoor settings with natural lighting, utilizing the full color spectrum. Artists known for this style include Leonardo da Vinci and Jan van Eyck among others.

Title: Perspective Art
Description: Perspective Art style is about portraying depth and three dimensional structures convincingly which gives the viewer a sense of space. The styles include Renaissance, Baroque and others with techniques varying from linear to aerial perspective. The paintings often depict outdoor settings with a varied color pallet and mood. Famous artists associated with perspective art include Leonardo Da Vinci and Salvador Dalí.

Title: Neo-plasticism
Description: Neo-plasticism is an art movement related to the De Stijl and Modernism art styles. Champions of this style, like Piet Mondrian, aimed to purify art by reducing it down to its basic vertical and horizontal elements, and primary colors. The compositions in this style are usually geometrical and simplified. This style marked a significant departure from traditional representational art.

Title: Tsugumi Ohba
Description: Tsugumi Ohba, a writer, is prominent in the Manga and Anime art scenes. Her works are accompanied by illustrations, typically in a black and white color scheme. The compositions in her works are often narrative-centric, with an emphasis on storytelling. She is often related to artists like Naoki Urasawa and Akira Toriyama.

Title: The Misfits
Description: The Misfits are a punk rock band known for their aggressive and bold art styles. They often incorporate elements of horror punk, underground comics, and gothic art into their music albums. Notable artists include Glenn Danzig, Jerry Only, and Michale Graves.

Title: The Cramps
Description: The Cramps, a punk rock band, often use a psychedelic, punk, and garage art style in their music albums. The artwork is typically wild and chaotic, with a primary color scheme of red. Key artists include Lux Interior and Poison Ivy.

Title: Music Genre
Description: Music genres often express their unique characteristics and themes through album cover art. The art styles can range from abstract to symbolic to pop art, and the composition is typically graphic.

Title: Sticker Art
Description: Sticker art, a form of street art, is commonly seen in urban areas. It utilizes graffiti, pop art, and street art styles. The stickers are generally multi-colored and convey a rebellious mood.

Title: Koyoharu Gotouge
Description: Koyoharu Gotouage is known for his manga, fantasy, and Japanese art styles in comic books. His work often presents a dramatic mood in a black and white color scheme, with an illustrative composition.

Title: Bungie
Description: Bungie's art style spans realistic and futuristic visuals set in science fiction environments. Used primarily in video game design, the art boasts detailed compositions and lighting that varies according to the scene. Key artists include Jason Jones and Harold Ryan.

Title: Gosho Aoyama
Description: Gosho Aoyama's art style is a blend of traditional manga and anime, often depicting contemporary Japanese scenarios. His work primarily appears in manga, characterized by sequential composition and a black-and-white color scheme, with a focus on mystery. Aoyama himself is the key artist.

Title: Masaaki Yuasa
Description: Masaaki Yuasa's art style is characterized by its unique, elastic composition and the vivid, colorful lighting that inhabit his fantasy environments. The enchanting style is a unique contribution to anime, with absurd moods playing a prominent role, and Yuasa himself as the primary artist.

Title: Prints
Description: Print art styles, such as woodblock and silkscreen prints, are denoted by their layered composition through a process called printmaking. Characteristics like environment, lighting, color, and mood can vary considerably, with notable artists like Hokusai and Andy Warhol well-known for their work in this area.

Title: Computer Animation
Description: Computer Animation art style encompasses 3D animation and pixel art, among others. It is a digital medium that creates virtual environments. It holds variable lighting, color, and mood conditions, but is characterized by computer-generated lighting and digitized composition. Renowned artists in this field include John Lasseter and Hayao Miyazaki.

Title: Family
Description: Family art style prominently deals with themes of family, relationships and domestic harmony. Depending on the artists perspective it spans various styles like realism, impressionism, surrealism and more. It often emphasizes warmth and harmony, frequently depicted in a domestic setting.

Title: Surf Art
Description: Surf art style emerges from surfing subculture, depicting vibrant coastal scenes and derived energy from fluid dynamic compositions. It draws on varied styles like pop art, abstract art or expressionism with distinct energetic mood.

Title: Movie Posters
Description: Movie posters art style is a category of graphic design focused on creating striking, eye-catching compositions to promote films, often drawing on pop art, minimalism or art deco elements. Its color scheme and composition varies based on individual movies' themes.

Title: Textures
Description: Textures in art refers to the surface quality or 'feel' of an object, its smoothness, roughness, softness, etc. Textures may be actual or simulated. Actual textures can be felt with the touch while simulated textures are suggested by an artist in the painting of different areas of a picture.

Title: Color Film
Description: Color film is a style of film that uses color to enhance the cinematic experience. The style emerged in the early 20th century, after the advent of sound in film. It gave filmmakers new creative avenues to explore and influenced the aesthetics of filmic storytelling.

Title: Soviet Avant-Garde
Description: Soviet Avant-Garde art style represents a wave of modernist art that was directly influenced by the Russian Revolution and the socio-political atmosphere surrounding it. The style often involves geometrical shapes and minimal colors, reflecting the industrial environment and ideology of the time.

Title: Documentary Film
Description: The Documentary Film art style aims to depict reality and relay factual information. Filmmakers often employ a 'fly-on-the-wall' aesthetic, attempting to make their influences on the events they're filming as invisible as possible. Techniques can vary from the observational to the interactive or reflexive.

Title: Motion Photography
Description: Motion Photography is an art style focusing on capturing movement in a still image. Using either blur or freeze techniques, artists create an abstract representation of action. With long exposure or sequential shots, motion photography provides a dynamic viewpoint of life.

Title: Marbled Paper Art
Description: Marbled Paper Art is a style of painting and printmaking that typically involves dropping paints onto a liquid surface to create an abstract pattern, mimicking the smooth, random patterns seen in marble. Prominent artists like Jemma Lewis, Miki Lovett, and Paolo Olbi are known for this style.

Title: Architectural Eclecticism
Description: Architectural Eclecticism is an art style involving a mix of architectural styles from different periods, such as the Victorian, Neo-Classical, and Gothic Revival styles. Notable proponents include Charles Garnier, Eugene Emmanuel Viollet-le-Duc, and Owen Jones.

Title: Climate Fiction
Description: Climate Fiction is an artistic representation of a narrative that deals with climate change and global warming. Typically seen in realism and sci-fi art styles, artists such as Paolo Bacigalupi, Kim Stanley Robinson, and Margaret Atwood have made significant contributions in this genre.

Title: Comic Book Writing
Description: Comic Book Writing is an art style distinguished by its use of sequential narratives and illustrations. It encompasses various genres such as manga, graphic novels, and superhero comics. Famous artists in this line include Stan Lee, Alan Moore, and Neil Gaiman.

Title: Southwestern Landscape Painting
Description: Southwestern Landscape Painting is an art style that captures the unique landscapes found in the Southwestern United States. Prominent styles include realism and impressionism, with artists like Georgia O'Keeffe, Frederic Remington, and Ernest L Blumenschein making notable contributions to the genre.

Title: Kustom Kulture
Description: Kustom Kulture art style is a lively, audacious artistic outlook inspired by underground car and motorcycle cultures. Its bold art styles often include Pop Art, Street Art and the Lowbrow genre. The narrative is told through vibrant colors and extravagant graphics, with Ts artists like Von Dutch, Ed 'Big Daddy' Roth, and Robert Williams spearheading the subculture.

Title: B-Movie
Description: B-Movie art style is a distinctive subset of cinema, often characterized by low-budget, suspenseful narratives and stark compositions. The dominant art styles include Film Noir, Exploitation, and Pulp Fiction, with monochromatic coloring as a common characteristic of the cinema palette. Prominent B-Movie makers include Roger Corman, Ed Wood, and Samuel Z. Arkoff.

Title: Exploitation
Description: Exploitation art style is characterized by films revolving around taboo subject matter, pushing the boundaries of traditional cinema. The style borrows elements from Trash Cinema, Cult, and B Movies, predominantly set in urban environments and often featuring controversial topics. It is known for its saturated color schemes, with prominent figures like Russ Meyer, Herschell Gordon Lewis, and David F. Friedman.

Title: Nabis
Description: The Nabis art style is a post-impressionism movement that combines elements of symbolism. Known for its use of outdoor scenes, soft, diffused light, the Nabis art style often employed flat compositions with earthy tones. Renowned artists within this movement include Pierre Bonnard, Édouard Vuillard, and Paul Ranson.

Title: Native American Art
Description: The Native American art style stems from various indigenous cultures across the Americas. It carries symbolism and visual narratives, often created with materials like pottery and beads. The use of natural dyes for coloration and patterns in geometric composition is customary. Pioneers of the style include artists such as Maria Martinez, R.C. Gorman, and Fritz Scholder.

Title: Black Humor
Description: Black Humor Art is often visual satire presented in a cynical or grimly humorous manner often using monochromatic colors. Focused on critique of society, it presents chaos in stark lighting. Renowned artists of such style include George Grosz and Francisco Goya.

Title: Urban Isolation
Description: Urban Isolation art captures the modern day feelings of alienation & loneliness within an urban environment. Artists such as Edward Hopper depict sparse, gloomy urban landscapes in dull light that convey a profound sense of isolation.

Title: Social Critique
Description: Social Critique in art style is a visual commentary on societal issues. Utilizing provocatively arranged elements in their work, artists like Banksy and Picasso, present reflective & thought-provoking pieces to spark change.

Title: Nonsense Literature
Description: Nonsense Literature Art Style is often used in illustration, most famously by artists like René Magritte and Edward Lear. Their work often boasts vibrant colors and illogical compositions, reflecting the absurdity of the concept.

Title: Marine Painting
Description: Marine Painting concerns itself with the representation of the sea & marine landscapes. Artists like Joseph Turner and Claude Monet create scenic compositions in natural light primarily using shades of blue.

Title: American Landscape Painting
Description: American Landscape Painting art style involves the representation of the natural beauty found within America. This style was particularly popular during the 19th-century period of Romanticism and Hudson River School. The paintings often portray tranquil, serene environments, using perspective to capture vast landscapes, generally with vibrant, natural color palettes.

Title: Word Art
Description: Word Art is a digital art style that utilizes words and phrases as its main subject matter. Artists using this style manipulate typography and symbols to create visually striking designs. It can be seen in various art movements such as Conceptual Art, Postmodern Art, and Pop Art. The color schemes are usually multicolored.

Title: Straight Photography
Description: Straight Photography is a style of photography that strives for sharp clarity and detailed representation of reality, often with a monochromatic color scheme. This style is associated with Modernism, Documentary Photography, and Photojournalism. The composition is typically unmanipulated and the lighting is natural.

Title: Data Visualization
Description: Data Visualization is an art style that involves the creation of visual representations of data, using color, shapes, and symbols. It closely aligns with Information Design and Visual Communication. The composition is generally symbolic and it often uses a multicolored palette.

Title: Edwardian Style
Description: The Edwardian Style art style emerged during the reign of King Edward VII and carries a sense of elegance and sophistication. This style has connections to Realism and Art Nouveau, featuring pastel color schemes and soft lighting. Paintings in this style often include portraiture and indoor settings.

Title: Visual Design
Description: Visual Design is a modern, technical-driven art style. It combines elements of Graphic Design, UX/UI Design, Interaction Design, and others, to form a cohesive and appealing interface for users. Often digitally-based, artists like Saul Bass, Paul Rand, and Dieter Rams have heavily influenced this design-centric practice.

Title: African Art
Description: African Art encompasses a vast range of multi-disciplinary arts from the African continent. From traditional sculpture to modern textiles, African art often utilizes earth tones, symbolic composition, and incorporates rich cultural symbolism. Notable artists include El Anatsui, Sokari Douglas Camp, and Ben Enwonwu.

Title: Spanish Renaissance
Description: Spanish Renaissance signifies an art style that prospered during the renaissance period in Spain, marked by the ornate composition, transcendental lighting, and sublime mood. The Spanish Renaissance utilizes Mannerism and Naturalism and is famous for its rich saturated colors. Notable artists include El Greco, Diego Velázquez, and Bartolomé Esteban Murillo.

Title: Electronic Music
Description: Electronic music is an art form that manipulates sounds electronically through music software. Styles such as House, Techno, Ambient, and Trance represent various moods and atmospheres. Renowned artists in the field include Aphex Twin, Kraftwerk, and Daft Punk.

Title: Red Carpet Glamour
Description: Red Carpet Glamour is an art form displayed through the medium of haute couture and luxury fashion. Set against the backdrop of the red carpet, this style exudes an elegant mood with a varied color palette and sophisticated compositions. Iconic designers like Valentino Garavani, Giorgio Armani, and Donatella Versace are notable artists in this field.

Title: Luxury Fashion
Description: Luxury Fashion as an art style revolves around the use of high-quality materials and intricate designs to produce expensive and exclusive clothing items. Giants of this art style include Giorgio Armani, Coco Chanel, and Yves Saint Laurent.

Title: Religious Painting
Description: Religious Painting as a art style was born out of religious fervour and was often used to visually depict religious stories and figures. Masters of this divine craft include Michelangelo, Leonardo Da Vinci, and Caravaggio.

Title: African American Art
Description: African American art style visually explores the history, cultural heritage, and contemporary experiences of African Americans. Influential artists of this style include Romare Bearden, Henry Ossawa Tanner, and Jacob Lawrence.

Title: Nature Photography
Description: Nature Photography as an art style encapsulates the raw beauty and undisturbed state of natural landscapes. Prominent photographers known for this style include Ansel Adams, David Muench, and Eliot Porter.

Title: Golden Age Illustration
Description: Golden Age Illustration was a period of innovation in the illustrative arts. Key figures such as Arthur Rackham, Norman Rockwell and Edmund Dulac created vibrant and romantic works that continue to inspire today.

Title: Humorous Photography
Description: In the Humorous Photography art style, artists use conceptual, abstract and contemporary approaches to evoke laughter or amusement. The medium primarily used is photography. The mood of the art is usually joyful and the composition applies various photographic tricks to create humor. Notable artists in this field include Elliott Erwitt and Martin Parr.

Title: Nature Illustration
Description: The Nature Illustration art style encompasses botanical, wildlife, and landscape illustration techniques to create detailed depictions of nature through painting. Art of this style often uses natural color palettes and is set in natural environments. Prominent artists include John James Audubon and Maria Sibylla Merian.
