Title: Watercolor Illustration
Description: Watercolor Illustration art style includes landscape, portrait, and abstract forms. The main medium is painting, specifically with watercolors. The color scheme is predominantly transparent and light, as typical of watercolors. The composition is free-flowing to accentuate the inherent transparency of watercolor paints. Artists like Alfred Wainwright have contributed greatly to this style.

Title: Night Photography
Description: Night Photography art style combines forms like long exposure, street, and astrophotography. The medium used is photography and the environment in which the art is set is primarily night, characterized by low-light settings. Compositions typically consist of long-exposure shots. Brassai and Michael Kenna are key artists in this field.

Title: Urban Exploration Photography
Description: The Urban Exploration Photography art style merges techniques of architectural, street, and documentary photography to portray urban environments. Medium of choice is photography. The environment often depicted is urban with a raw and unfiltered color scheme. Compositions mostly comprise of candid shots to capture the urban life authentically. Henri Cartier-Bresson and Walker Evans played significant roles in developing this style.

Title: Mystery Photography
Description: Mystery Photography is a style of art that primarily uses photography as a medium to create mysterious and thought-provoking imagery. Often adopting a monochrome color scheme and low lighting, it can take forms such as Noir, Pictorialism, and Surrealism. Notable practitioners of this style include Helene Leane and Rachel Bate.

Title: Relief Sculpture
Description: Relief Sculpture refers to an artistic style in which sculptures are carved to stand out from a flat background. The degrees of relief vary, with forms such as Bas-Relief, High Relief, and Sunken Relief. Renowned artists in this field include Donatello and Augustus Saint-Gaudens.

Title: Bookbinding
Description: Bookbinding is an art form that involves piecing together a book from individual sheets of paper, covers, and a spine. It takes various styles including Coptic Binding, Japanese Stab Binding, and Case Binding. Artists like Julie Chen and Daniel E. Kelm have made significant contributions to this art style.

Title: Hand Embroidery
Description: Hand Embroidery is an art style that involves the detailed stitching of designs onto a piece of textile. It includes styles such as Cross-stitch, Blackwork embroidery, and Crewel embroidery. Significant artists in this field are Elisabetta Sforza and Trish Burr.

Title: Cross-stitch
Description: Cross-stitch is a popular form of embroidery that involves creating pictures and designs by stitching crosses onto cloth. It typically follows a grid-based composition, with styles ranging from Counted Cross-stitch to Stamped Cross-stitch. Noteworthy artists include Jane Greenoff and Paula Vaughan.

Title: Embroidery Art
Description: Embroidery art is a form of decorative sewing that uses thread to embellish fabric. Within this art style, designs vary from simple line art to intricate patterns and imagery. Artists such as Cayce Zavaglia and Rachael Ashe often incorporate vibrant colors, depicting everything from landscapes to human portraits.

Title: Contemporary Embroidery
Description: Contemporary embroidery is a modern interpretation of traditional hand-sewn art style. Artists often experiment with form, color, and subject matter, blending traditional techniques with modern themes. Artists such as Maurizio Anzeri and Richard McVetis often exert unconventional imagery or abstract patterns in their designs.

Title: Crewelwork
Description: Crewelwork is a type of embroidery that uses wool yarn on a linen background. Characterized by its intricate floral and fauna patterns, it often presents a riot of colors. Renowned artists like Jenny Adin-Christie and Anna Scott specialize in this style, creating beautiful designs that stand out for their level of detail and colorfulness.

Title: Colorful Painting
Description: Colorful painting is a style characterized by the use of vibrant, diverse colors. Artists experiment with color to evoke emotions, express ideas, or recreate reality in a more whimsical way. The style lays its foundation in various art movements like abstract, expressionism, and pop art, with artists like Piet Mondrian and Wassily Kandinsky pushing the boundaries of color in art.

Title: Cinematographer
Description: Cinematographers, sometimes known as directors of photography, are artists who use their technical expertise and aesthetic judgement to capture moving images on screen. Their work contributes to the overall look and feel of a film, employing various styles like Realism or Film Noir. Renowned cinematographers include Roger Deakins and Emmanuel Lubezki, whose works are praised for their stunning visual storytelling.

Title: Natural History Illustration
Description: Natural History Illustration represents an art style that focuses on the detailed, scientifically accurate, and often aesthetic illustration of the natural world. This includes plants, animals, and other aspects of nature. The art form is often considered a blend of art and science.

Title: Die Brücke
Description: Die Brücke art style is marked by its dramatic use of color and distorted forms. As a part of the larger German Expressionist movement, it worked to convey raw, emotional reactions to urban life, oftentimes through distorted and exaggerated visuals.

Title: Experimental Photography
Description: Experimental photography isn't confined to a specific style or method. It's an umbrella term for any photography that pushes boundaries and involves unique, experimental techniques and creative ways in using cameras, providing an unconventional view of the world.

Title: Chronophotography
Description: Chronophotography is a type of art that involves taking several sequential images to study or capture the motion of a subject over time. The process is often used for scientific or artistic purposes, leading to groundbreaking developments in areas like film and animation.

Title: Scientific
Description: Scientific art is primarily concerned with the accurate and detailed depiction of scientific subjects—from mechanical objects to biological life forms. It combines a methodical approach with artistic interpretation, often resulting in an informative and aesthetically pleasing art form.

Title: Memphis Design
Description: Memphis Design is a postmodern art style mainly in the field of interior design, which was founded by Ettore Sottsass. The art style is known for its abstract, geometric composition and the use of vivid, contrasting colors, drawing influence from movements like Pop Art and Futurism.

Title: BONES
Description: BONES is a Japanese animation studio founded by Hiroshi Ōsaka, Masahiko Minami, and Toshihiro Kawamoto. The art style is characterized as Anime with a detailed, fluid animation composition. The mood in their works varies depending on the story.

Title: Hideaki Anno
Description: Hideaki Anno is a Japanese animator and director known for his detailed and surreal artistic style in animation. His work often explores psychological and complex moods, evident in works like 'Neon Genesis Evangelion'. He has collaborated with artists such as Hayao Miyazaki and Yoshiyuki Sadamoto.

Title: German Expressionism
Description: German Expressionism is an art style originating in Germany in the early 20th century, featuring dark colors, harsh lighting, and exaggerated, distorted compositions. The style, often represented in painting describes feelings of angst and conflict. Prominent artists include Ernst Ludwig Kirchner and Emil Nolde.

Title: American Realism
Description: American Realism is an art style that emerged in the late 19th and early 20th century. Often portrayed through painting, it depicts scenes of daily life with natural lighting, true-to-life colors, and a calm objective mood. The composition is accurate and artists like Edward Hopper and Winslow Homer are associated with this movement.

Title: Kawaii
Description: Kawaii is a significant part of Japanese culture and a prominent art style. It is characterized by a sense of innocence, playfulness, and cuteness. The illustrations in this art style are typically simplified, featuring bright and pastel colors. The mood portrayed is joyful and the medium is generally illustration.

Title: Decora
Description: Decora is an art style evolved from the Harajuku fashion scene in Japan. It's characterized by its playful and colorful attributes. The medium is primarily in fashion design with heavy emphasis on layering objects and vibrant colors.

Title: African-American Art
Description: African-American Art involves a diverse range of visual artistic expression inspired by the culture and experiences of African-Americans. From abstract forms to social realism, the art styles often reflect historical and contemporary themes. Paintings depict both urban and rural settings with varied color options, ranging from muted to vibrant colors.

Title: Story Quilts
Description: Story Quilts is an art style that narrates a story through quilt making. It incorporates pictorial elements in a block pattern composition. A prominent style in Folk Art, Story Quilts are known for their vibrant color choices and the emotional mood of storytelling they portray.

Title: Group Arrangement
Description: Group Arrangement is an art concept often seen in painting where objects or figures are purposefully arranged to create an organized composition. Seen prominently in Still Life, Renaissance, and Baroque styles, these works usually depict an interior environment, using rich, deep colors. The mood often suggests drama, enhanced by the use of chiaroscuro lighting.

Title: Junko Mizuno
Description: Junko Mizuno is known for her unique art style that blends elements of pop art, gothic art, and Japanese manga. Her illustrations are usually highly detailed, set in a grotesque mood, and feature a color scheme filled with bright and vivid hues.

Title: Hilary Knight
Description: Hilary Knight is recognized for her signature art style including children's book illustration and American mid-century illustration. Her works generally possess a playfully serious mood, created using dynamic scenes and a pastel color palette.

Title: Antonio Lopez
Description: Antonio Lopez's art style is a fusion of fashion illustration and pop art. His drawings always exhibit an energetic mood, employing a vibrant color scheme and presenting the subjects in dramatic poses.

Title: Fashion Figures
Description: The fashion figures art style primarily falls under fashion illustration and haute couture genres. These drawings exhibit a sophisticated mood, with elongated figures being a common compositional trait, opening up for a broad array of color palettes.

Title: Individual Subject
Description: Art featuring an individual subject often involves styles like portraiture, surrealism, and realism, depending on the artist's intent. The mood, color scheme, and overall aesthetic can vary, typically focusing on a single subject and the environment surrounding them.

Title: Donatella Versace
Description: Donatella Versace, a renowned Italian fashion designer known for bold and vibrant art styles. Her style relies on intricate detailing, glamour, and high fashion that often breaks boundaries, pushing the envelope of what is considered couture.

Title: High-speed
Description: High-speed art style, prominently seen in photography, captures motion effectively, lending itself to styles such as Impressionism and Abstract Expressionism. The environment is often outdoor with an emphasis on action, and lighting is variable.

Title: Frozen Motion
Description: Frozen motion is an art style primarily utilized in photography. This style involves capturing a fluid movement and freezing it in a single, bright, and clear image. The compositions often depict dynamic action and they are rooted in Photorealism and Impressionism.

Title: Metaphysical
Description: Metaphysical art is a style of painting, associated with artists like de Chirico and Carrà. This style is characterized by a mysterious mood and a composition often involving a juxtaposition of ordinary objects in unconventional, dreamlike settings.

Title: Pre-Surrealism
Description: Pre-Surrealism, as its name suggests, is an art style that preceded and influenced Surrealism. It is noted for its dream-like mood characterized by strange juxtapositions in painting and was pioneered by artists like Giorgio de Chirico.

Title: Fiber Art
Description: Fiber Art is a type of art that uses plant, animal, or synthetic fibers to construct practical or decorative artworks. This style is closely associated with textile arts, often involving techniques like weaving, embroidery, and macramé. Artists such as Magdalena Abakanowicz and Tracey Emin have used these methods to create three-dimensional pieces imbued with a creative mood.

Title: Craft Art
Description: Craft Art refers to handcrafted works of art, involving the skillful use of materials and tools to create unique pieces. This concept covers a range of art styles including pottery, woodcraft, and metalcraft, among others. Renowned artists like Peter Voulkos and Louis Comfort Tiffany have created artwork in this style, typically characterized by an intricate mood and a three-dimensional structure.

Title: Sculptural Fiber Art
Description: Sculptural Fiber Art incorporates textile art techniques, such as weaving, crocheting, or knitting, to create three-dimensional sculptural objects. This art style can produce a diverse range of colors and is often displayed in gallery environments. Its mood is generally expressive, as seen in works by artists like Claire Zeisler or Lenore Tawney.

Title: Needle Felting
Description: Needle Felting is an art style that uses a barbed needle to interlock wool fibers to form a more condensed material. Artists like Ayako Satoh and Hannah Streefkerk craft delicate and often intricately detailed three-dimensional objects from wool using this method.

Title: Fiber
Description: Fiber as an art style utilizes textile-based materials to explore multiple concepts and techniques, including weaving, embroidery, and knitting. It may involve a range of colors that can create a textured mood in its typically two-dimensional compositions. The work of artists like Anni Albers and El Anatsui exemplifies this style.

Title: Felted Art
Description: Felted Art is a type of textile art where wool is manipulated to create non-woven fabric. Artworks are multi-colored, often displaying intricate patterns and the composition tends to be three-dimensional. Notable artists in this field include Faig Ahmed and Sheila Hicks.

Title: Painting En Plein Air
Description: The phrase 'Painting En Plein Air' refers to the practice of painting outdoors, capturing landscapes under natural light. This art style is closely associated with Impressionism. The color palette used is vibrant, mimicking the brightness of natural light. Notable artists include Claude Monet and Pierre-Auguste Renoir.

Title: Florentine
Description: Florentine art style is deeply rooted in the cultural richness of the Italian Renaissance. Paintings feature historical settings with earthy tones. The mood of artworks often leans towards the sacred, accompanied by a composition emphasising symmetry. Renowned Florentine artists include Botticelli and Leonardo da Vinci.

Title: Role-playing Game (RPG)
Description: Role-playing Game (RPG) is a genre of game where the player controls a character in a mythical environment. The art style largely follows fantasy themes embodying various lighting and color approaches depending upon the game's setting and atmosphere. Prominent artists include Shigeru Miyamoto and Hironobu Sakaguchi.

Title: Japanese Role-playing Game (JRPG)
Description: Japanese Role-playing Game (JRPG) is a sub-genre of games blending gameplay with strong narrative elements. The art style is heavily influenced by anime and set in fantasy worlds. The color characterization is typically bright and vibrant. Well-known artists in this domain include Akira Toriyama and Yuji Horii.

Title: Tactical Role-playing Game (TRPG)
Description: The Tactical Role-playing Game (TRPG) art style commonly includes digital mediums, often using styles like pixel art, isometric art, and concept art. The game's art is typically set in immersive fantasy worlds, colour schemes are varied and the composition is generally grid-based to complement turn-based game mechanics.

Title: Turn-based Strategy
Description: Turn-based Strategy art style often involves pixel art, isometric art or concept art and is realised mainly via digital mediums. The environment varies from game to game. The mood is often challenging and the composition is typically top-down.

Title: Wide-angle
Description: The Wide-angle art style is commonly used in landscape, architecture, and street photography. The medium is photography and it often utilizes natural lighting. The environment varies greatly based on the subject matter.

Title: Photomanipulation
Description: Photomanipulation art style resonates with surrealism, pop art, and abstract aesthetics. The medium used is usually digital art, and while colors can vary, the mood is often surreal. The composition is typically non-linear as photomanipulation allows for greater freedom of expression.

Title: Floral
Description: Floral art style is typically associated with Impressionism, Art Nouveau, and Botanical Illustration. The mood is usually cheerful with vibrant colors, often with painting as the medium capturing natural environments. The composition frequently involves still life.

Title: David Carson
Description: David Carson is a prominent figure in the world of graphic design, associated with the modernist, grunge, and expressionist art styles. His work is known for its asymmetrical compositions and bold use of color. Other artists of a similar style include Stefan Sagmeister, April Greiman, and Neville Brody.

Title: Howard Finster
Description: Howard Finster was known for his work in outsider, folk, and naïve art styles. Renowned for his narrative compositions and the colorful vividness of his paintings, his art suggests a realm of spirituality interpreted through his unique vision. Influential artists within this domain include James Hampton, Nellie Mae Rowe, and William Edmondson.

Title: Naïve
Description: Naïve art style is a form of visual art that is characterized by a simplified and often exaggerated artistic expression. Medium is primarily painting, with artists using multicolored palettes and simplified compositions. Renowned naïve artists include Henri Rousseau, Camille Bombois, and Ivan Generalić.

Title: Various Photographers
Description: The term 'Various Photographers' could encompass various styles prevalent in the photographic art realm, which range from documentary and fine art to portrait photography. The medium is primarily photography, and lighting, color, and composition greatly vary depending on the specific type or artist. Renowned photographers include Ansel Adams, Diane Arbus, and Steve McCurry.

Title: Unknown Forensic Photographers
Description: The concept of 'Unknown Forensic Photographers' refers to photographers who work in the field of forensics, often for legal proceedings or investigative purposes. The art style tends to reflect a strict documentary style that exudes a clinical mood. The lighting is usually harsh or neutral, and the compositions are practical, focusing on representing evidence accurately.

Title: Religious
Description: Religious art refers to the various artistic forms inspired by religious themes. The style embodies a diversity of cultures and periods, carrying a rich history of symbolism, interpretation, and purpose. The central figures are often highlighted by divine light, creating a sense of sanctity.

Title: Benoit Mandelbrot
Description: Benoit Mandelbrot is best known for developing the theory of fractal geometry, a concept widely used in digital and mathematical art styles. The artwork often features intricate, complex patterns and shapes, making use of advanced geometrical concepts. Colors vary, meaning these artworks can fit a range of perspectives and interpretations.

Title: Georgy Kepes
Description: Georgy Kepes was an eminent figure in the Light and Space art style. This practice typically involves the innovative use of light to affect the viewer's perception of space. Natural light and spaces play key roles, and the medium often overlaps with installation and sculpture. Abstract, kinetic, and op art styles are also related.

Title: Mathematical
Description: Mathematical art is an innovative form of art inspired by mathematics and its intricacies. The composition predominantly features the use of precise, geometric forms, often breaking down complex algorithms and equations into visually engaging art. The style usually fits in the realm of optical and geometric abstract art.

Title: Noir
Description: Noir, commonly associated with Film Noir, is an art style characterized by moody, high-contrast visual aesthetics. It often involves chiaroscuro lighting, starkly contrasting shadows and light. Its color palette is dominated by blacks, grays, and whites, and it frequently projects a melancholic mood. Much Noir art presents a depth of scene, making use of deep shadows and often set in an urban landscape.

Title: Narrative Film
Description: Narrative film art style is typical of most mainstream cinema and focuses on a well-structured plot that leads the viewer from one event to another. It usually adheres to specific formats and techniques sonorous with movies and often employs elements of various film art styles including 'Cinema Verite,' 'Neorealism,' and 'Expressionism'.

Title: New Hollywood
Description: New Hollywood, or the 'Hollywood Renaissance,' marked a shift in filmmaking style in the US in the 1960s-80s. Breaking away from protocols of the Golden Age, directors adopted experimental techniques and controversial themes. It is closely related to the French New wave and Neorealism, influencing a variety of film genres.

Title: Dadaism
Description: Dadaism originated in the 20th century as a protest movement against the horrors of World War I. It challenges all traditional conventions of art and encourages spontaneity. Using a variety of mediums including painting, photography, or sculpture, artists often employed absurd, nonsensical, or satirical elements in their work.

Title: Prairie School
Description: Prairie School is an architectural style born in the Midwest United States in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. It stressed the importance of harmony with the surrounding environment and utilized horizontal lines and earth tones, often incorporating Arts and Crafts, and Art Nouveau influences.

Title: Wildlife Photography
Description: Wildlife Photography as an artistic genre involves capturing appealing or educational images of wildlife. It encompasses a variety of sub-genres from macro to aerial photography. Lighting and composition play a crucial role, often adhering to the 'Rule of thirds.' Relevant artists include Ansel Adams and Frans Lanting.

Title: Der Blaue Reiter
Description: Der Blaue Reiter was an art movement based in Germany that focused on the emotional effect of artworks. Prominent artists like Wassily Kandinsky and Franz Marc were part of this movement, producing vibrant and emotional paintings with an abstract composition.

Title: American Impressionism
Description: American Impressionism was an art style that originated in the US during the late 19th and early 20th centuries. With loose compositions, natural lighting, and varied colors, the style focused on capturing the visual impression of the moment. Artists like John Henry Twachtman and William Merritt Chase were notable in this field.

Title: Heidelberg School
Description: The Heidelberg School was an Australian art movement of the late 19th century. This style, under Australian Impressionism, featured paintings with a realistic mood depicting the Australian landscape in natural light. Notable artists included Tom Roberts and Charles Conder.

Title: Australian Impressionism
Description: Australian Impressionism, also known as the Heidelberg School, was an art movement that aimed to depict the natural environment of Australia. Its prominent artists, like Arthur Streeton and Charles Conder, created bright, naturalistic, and realistic compositions.

Title: Medieval Art
Description: Medieval Art was a broad art style during the Middle Age, encompassing various sub-genres like Gothic Art, Romanesque Art, and Byzantine Art. The artworks, primarily paintings, were religious, portraying sacred moods with a flat perspective. Muted tones and lighting were common characteristics. Noted artists include Cimabue and Giotto di Bondone.

Title: Symbolist
Description: The Symbolist art style focuses on the depiction of emotions and ideas, instead of faithful representation of the natural world. Artists use intense and soft color schemes to create mysterious and often mystical feelings. Symbolism encourages ambiguous compositions and the depiction of intangible concepts.

Title: Impressionist
Description: Impressionism is a 19th-century art movement characterized by relatively small, thin, yet visible brush strokes, emphasis on accurate depiction of light in its changing qualities, and ordinary subject matter. It captures the artist's perception of the scene with bright and saturated colors.

Title: Realist
Description: Realist art style depicts everyday scenes and life as it truly is without adding fantastical or whimsical elements. It focuses on accurate depictions of environments and people, using natural lighting and natural tones. This style emerged as a counterpart to Romanticism that embraced idealism and exaggerated emotionalism.

Title: Photographic
Description: Photographic art style heavily relies on capturing moments with accuracy. The mood, color, and composition largely depend on the subject being photographed. The art style can range from photojournalism, which captures pivotal moments in time, to portrait photography, which focuses on capturing a person's likeness.

Title: Full Body
Description: Full body art style, prevalent in sculpture, refers to the visual arts technique where the entire body of the subject is represented. Artists like Michelangelo and Rodin have utilized this style to depict person's anatomy and emotions. This style can take many forms, from realistic to abstract figures.

Title: Animated Series
Description: Animated series art style often employs art styles such as cartoon, anime, rotoscoping, computer animation, and stop-motion. The medium is typically digital, set in dynamic cartoon landscapes. The color schemes are usually vibrant and multicolored. The composition of this art style is largely determined by a frame-by-frame approach. Notable artists include Walt Disney, Hayao Miyazaki, and John Lasseter.

Title: Music
Description: Music's visual art style often takes form in abstract, surreal, pop art, poster art, and album cover art. Artists create using mixed media, invoking an energetic mood. The composition is non-linear and varied. Renowned artists known for music-related visual art include Andy Warhol, Roger Dean, and H.R. Giger.

Title: Groovy
Description: Groovy art style is most closely associated with psychedelic art, pop art, and abstract expressionism. The medium generally consists of a variety of mixed media, characterized by vibrant colors, presenting a joyful mood. The composition tends towards fluidic forms. Notable artists include Peter Max, Victor Moscoso, and Milton Glaser.

Title: Glass
Description: Glass art style includes techniques like glassblowing, stained glass, and fused glass. The medium is purely glass with significant emphasis on translucency in lighting. The colors are often transparent and the composition is typically sculptural. Noteworthy artists include Dale Chihuly, Louis Comfort Tiffany, and René Lalique.

Title: Dutch Golden Age Painting
Description: Dutch Golden Age Painting art style is marked by genre painting, landscape, still life, and portrait painting. Painters preferred oil as their medium, illuminated by chiaroscuro lighting. The mood is realistic, often set in dutch landscapes, and constructed with a great deal of detailed composition. Outstanding artists of this period include Rembrandt van Rijn, Johannes Vermeer, and Frans Hals.

Title: Underground
Description: Underground art refers to art forms that exist outside of the mainstream. This includes graffiti, street art, and urban art, often created in the urban environment using mediums like mural. Artists such as Banksy and Jean-Michel Basquiat have popularized the Underground art style, characterized by vibrant colors, natural lighting, rebellious mood, and abstract composition.

Title: Role-playing Game
Description: The art style of Role-playing Games (RPG) varies greatly, from Japanese RPGs to Western RPGs, with media primarily being digital. Environment settings are generally fantasy-based, with a wide range of colors and dynamic lighting to create an adventurous mood. Scenic compositions are common. Notable artists include Yoshitaka Amano and Akira Toriyama.

Title: Technical Pen Drawing
Description: Technical Pen Drawing art style is characterized by precise and highly detailed works. It's often applied in disciplines like architecture and engineering for detailed drawings using mediums such as ink. Renowned artists like Albrecht Durer utilized technical pen drawing. The style usually features monochrome color and flat lighting.

Title: Commercial Art
Description: Commercial Art focuses on design intended for commercial purposes, such as graphic design, advertising, and package design. The medium commonly used is mixed media. Bold colors and striking composition are characteristic traits of commercial art. Artists like Andy Warhol have significantly influenced commercial art through their work.

Title: Sci-fi Art
Description: Sci-fi Art style is characterized by futuristic elements, often depicting planets, spaceships, robots, and other elements related to science and technology. It typically employs bold, dynamic compositions with predominantly cool tones and artificial lighting. Artists working in this genre often use digital painting techniques.

Title: Applied Arts
Description: Applied Arts style is a blend of artistic design and practical application. It includes fields like craft art, commercial art, and industrial design. The works in this genre are often functional and may be created using a myriad of different mediums. Modernism played a key role in the development of this style.

Title: Ashcan School
Description: The Ashcan School is an art movement known for its departure from academic art norms, choosing instead to depict urban life in an informal, realistic fashion. The primary mediums were oil paintings and lithographs, featuring muted colour palettes, and natural lighting. This art style was home to many artists who found beauty in everyday life.

Title: Folk Art
Description: Folk Art is an art style rooted in traditions that come from community and culture. This art style expresses cultural identity by conveying shared community values and aesthetics. Mediums greatly vary in folk art but traditionally include wood, ceramics, textiles, and more. It is characterized by its nostalgia, simplicity, and often rustic compositions.

Title: American Indian Art
Description: American Indian Art style represents the work of Indigenous tribes across North America. This art style often reflects cultural, religious, and political values of the tribes. It incorporates symbolic and spiritual elements, with mediums ranging from pottery, weaving, basketry, to monumental architecture. Each tribe often has its distinct aesthetic styles.

Title: Naturalistic Art
Description: Naturalistic art style aims to depict subjects realistically and devoid of artistic interpretation. It involves accurate rendering, with strong emphasis on detail and lack of idealization, often displaying vibrant colors.

Title: Genre Art
Description: Genre art style refers to the depiction of everyday life, with details providing narratives or stories painted in a manner mimicking the actual appearance of things.

Title: Hollywood Glamour Photography
Description: Hollywood Glamour Photography is a art style which involves deliberate dramatic lighting, and often black and white imagery. The images are usually staged, exuding an air of elegance, and are prominent in fashion and portrait photography.

Title: Space Opera
Description: Space Opera art style is a sub-genre of science fiction that emphasizes large-scale narratives set in outer space with dramatic adventure and space warfare. Usually seen in film, it favors epic, vibrant visuals and grand-scale compositions.

Title: Film Direction
Description: Film Direction is a role within filmmaking where an individual oversees the creative aspects of a film, composing the narrative and directing the performances of actors. The artistic style can vary widely, ranging from documentary to drama.

Title: African Modernism
Description: African Modernism art style emerged in the post-colonial period during the mid-20th century, it incorporated indigenous African aesthetic traditions with the ideas and techniques of Western Modernism. The art is notable for its geometric compositions, vibrant colors and expressive style.

Title: National Romanticism
Description: National Romanticism art style, prominent in the late 19th and early 20th century, emphasized the spirit and folklore of each nation. The style is most visible in architecture, with structures often inspired by natural landscapes and built with earthen colors. The compositions have organic forms and the mood tends to be majestic.

Title: Comic Book Art Style
Description: The Comic Book art style is a visual form focused on vivid colors and dynamics. This style uses strong contrast for dramatic effect and is often associated with sequential compositions to narrate a story. The environment is usually depicted as urban landscape.

Title: Superhero Art Style
Description: The Superhero art style is a subset of comic book art, distinguished by its focus on strong, heroic characters often set in fantasy worlds. The style uses vibrant colors, dramatic lighting, and dynamic compositions to portray action and conflict.

Title: Decorative Art Style
Description: The Decorative art style is artistic works made with a focus on their aesthetic or ornamental value, more so than their functionality. This style covers a broad range of mediums but is especially prominent in interior design. The primary mood is aesthetic, and the color and compositions are varied.

Title: Gilded Age Art Style
Description: Gilded Age art style broadly encompasses several art trends of late 19th-century America, anonymizing realism, romanticism, and impressionism. Artists often painted detailed and vivid depictions of the prosperous industrial age, using natural lighting cues. Revered artists of this era include John Singer Sargent, Winslow Homer, and Augustus Saint-Gaudens.

Title: Futurist Art Style
Description: Futurist art style emerged in the early 20th century, focusing on speed, technology, and urban life. The art is often characterized by dynamic colors, materialistic lighting and fragmented compositions, signifying the energetic mood of a rapidly changing society. Premier artists include Umberto Boccioni, Carlo Carra, and Gino Severini.

Title: Cubist Art Style
Description: Cubist art style, pioneered by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque, revolts against traditional perspective rendering, presenting simultaneous multiple viewpoints within fragmented, geometric compositions. Often flat and monochromatic, Cubist artworks exemplify a new abstract mood, focusing on the inner realities rather than external appearances.

Title: Anime Art Style
Description: Anime art style, a significant facet of Japanese animation, is characterized by vibrant colors, dramatic lighting, and dynamic composition. Through a range of styles like Shōjo, Shōnen, and Seinen, it portrays a wide spectrum of expressive moods, predominantly set in imaginative fantasy worlds. Notable artists in this domain include Hayao Miyazaki, Akira Toriyama, and Yoshiyuki Tomino.

Title: Manga Art Style
Description: Manga art style, an integral part of Japanese comic books, embraces monochrome illustrations to depict a multitude of expressive moods. Known for its dramatic lighting, dynamic compositions, and elements of fantasy, it employs varied art styles like Shōjo, Shōnen, and Seinen. Prominent manga artists include Osamu Tezuka, Eiichiro Oda, and Takehiko Inoue.

Title: Proto-Renaissance Art Style
Description: Proto-Renaissance art style is characterized by increased realism and expression compared to the flat and stylized Byzantine art. This period laid the groundwork for the aesthetic shifts of the Italian Renaissance. The style typically includes religious subject matter with a balanced composition and vibrant colors.

Title: Fresco Art Style
Description: Fresco, a technique rather than an art style, was predominantly used during the Renaissance period. It involves applying water and pigments on a wet plaster surface to create murals. Frescoes typically portray narrative scenes and are admired for their durability and the depth of their colors.

Title: Neoclassical Art Style
Description: Neoclassicism, a Western art movement, is characterized by simplicity, symmetry, and grandeur drawing inspiration from classical antiquity. The art style portrays historical and mythological subjects. Neoclassical artists valued discipline, restraint, and clarity of form.

Title: Architectural Art Style
Description: The architectural art style varies greatly and is closely tied with visual and structural considerations. It engages a variety of mediums such as buildings, sculptures, public spaces, etc. The color, mood, and composition heavily vary depending on the architectural movement, artist, or period.

Title: Early Renaissance Art Style
Description: The Early Renaissance is known for the novel use of perspective, naturalistic representation of space, and light. During this period, artists started to portray a more accurate and lifelike vision of reality, moving away from the more stylized and symbolic medieval art.

Title: Venetian School Art Style
Description: The Venetian School art style emerged in Venice during the Renaissance where artists were distinguished by their use of color and luminous, atmospheric effects. Renowned artists include Titian, Tintoretto, and Giovanni Bellini.

Title: Mannerism Art Style
Description: Mannerism is an artistic style that emerged in the late Renaissance period, characterized by exaggerated proportions, tension, and a preference for intellectual sophistication over naturalistic representation. Noteworthy artists include El Greco, Parmigianino, and Jacopo da Pontormo.

Title: Portrait Art Style
Description: The Portrait art style is a representation or likeness of an individual often focusing on the face and its expression. It varies greatly depending on the artist's style and the subject. Famous portrait artists include Rembrandt, Vincent Van Gogh, and Pablo Picasso.

Title: Light Painting Photography Style
Description: Light Painting photography style is characterized by the use of long exposure times and movement of light sources to create illuminous images. It can be used to create abstract or surrealistic images. Notable artists include Gjon Mili, Man Ray, and Pablo Picasso were known to experiment with this style.

Title: Hollywood Regency
Description: The Hollywood Regency art style originates from the Golden Age of Hollywood and is characterized by its opulent and glamorous aesthetic. The style emphases on high-contrast color schemes, luxurious fabrics, and elaborate detailing. Notable artists include William Haines, Dorothy Draper, and Billy Baldwin.

Title: Satoshi Araki
Description: Satoshi Araki is known for his art involving painstaking detail. His medium of choice is modeling and his style features extreme realism. His work primarily includes miniature models that portray real-life settings.

Title: Disney Animation
Description: Disney Animation's art style includes both classic Cel animation and modern 3D animation. The animations are vibrant and colorful, often portraying joyful moods. The dynamic composition in their animations has become a signature style for the brand.

Title: Philipp Igumnov
Description: Philipp Igumnov is known for his surrealistic art style that often features fantasy environments. The artist's work is mainly in digital art, which displays his imaginative composition skills.

Title: Rosa Menkman
Description: Rosa Menkman is a designer who works primarily with digital media. Her style, characterized as Glitch art, uses distortion and abstraction to create works that are visually striking.

Title: Kim Asendorf
Description: Kim Asendorf is a digital artist known for her pixel art style. This style gives her work a uniquely pixelated composition, often using digital art to create abstract environments.

Title: Judith Braun
Description: Judith Braun is a New York-based artist known for using fingerprints as the primary component in her large-scale, symmetrical, charcoal drawings. Often considered part of abstract expressionism, her works present monochromatic colorations in indoor settings.

Title: Nick Gentry
Description: Nick Gentry is a British artist from London, notable for integrating obsolete media formats, such as VHS tapes, floppy disks, and film negatives, into his work. His art can be described as a blend of social art and pop art. Mostly portrait-oriented, Gentry's artworks exhibit a multi-colored and urban feel.

Title: Mixed Media Art
Description: Mixed Media Art refers to an art style that combines various traditional and non-traditional media in a single work. The styles associated with Mixed Media Art include Collage, Assemblage, and Installation. The composition often involves layering of different materials. It gained prominence through artists like Robert Rauschenberg and Kurt Schwitters.

Title: Mangaka
Description: Mangaka is the term for an artist or author of Manga, a style of Japanese comic books and graphic novels. The art style often features panel-based compositions, typically in black-and-white. Famous Mangaka include Akira Toriyama and Osamu Tezuka. The atmosphere in Manga can vary broadly, encompassing a wide range of genres and settings.

Title: Jean-Baptiste Belin De Fontenay
Description: Jean-Baptiste Belin de Fontenay was a French painter noted for his baroque and rococo style still-life works. His art often captures nature in vibrant color with soft lighting, evoking a romantic mood. His painting medium of choice was oil on canvas, and he often depicted floral arrangements. He was a popular court painter during the reign of Louis XIV.

Title: François Boucher
Description: François Boucher was a French painter known for his lavish style epitomizing the Rococo art movement. His use of pastel colors, soft lighting, and luxurious depictions of the royal court are defining characteristics. His style influenced many other artists like Jean-Honoré Fragonard.

Title: Historical Art
Description: Historical Art encompasses various art styles that aim to represent significant historical events or periods. Classical, Medieval, Renaissance, Victorian, and Impressionism are a few art styles that fall under this category. The artwork is usually reflective and unfolds stories from different historical contexts.

Title: Guan Daosheng
Description: Guan Daosheng was a Chinese painter, recognised for her prominent contributions to the Chinese Litai, a traditional form of painting. Her works usually feature monochromatic ink paintings of bamboo and natural landscapes. Daosheng's style is known to provoke a sense of contemplation and exhibits fluid composition.

Title: Iconography
Description: Iconography refers to the study and interpretation of images and symbols in art. It is seen predominantly in Byzantine, Renaissance, and Baroque art styles, where symbols and images were systematically used to convey spiritual or religious narratives. The mood in most Iconographic art is devotional.

Title: Indian Art
Description: Indian Art boasts of various unique styles including Mughal, Rajput, Madhubani, Warli, Tanjore art etc. The art forms are often drawn from folklore and mythological tales, featuring vibrant color schemes, symmetrical compositions, and a ritualistic mood. Eminent Indian artists include Raja Ravi Varma and Amrita Sher-Gil.

Title: No Specific Artists Associated
Description: 'No Specific Artists Associated' is a unique concept where art isn't attributed to any specific individuals but collectively appreciated as a culture or movement. It often involves mixed media with an overall serene mood. The compositions may vary widely, with asymmetry commonly seen.

Title: Street Style
Description: 'Street Style' is an art style that can be seen in Graffiti, Stencil Art, Poster Art, Public Murals, and Street Installations. It is often created using spray paint, set against the backdrop of urban environments, and features vibrant colors. With expressive compositions, it carries a rebellious mood.

Title: Post-Soviet Fashion
Description: The 'Post-Soviet Fashion' art style embraces Deconstructivism, Avant-garde, Minimalistic, Functionalism, and Eclecticism. Medium of this style is clothing, and is often displayed on Fashion Runways. The style is characterized by monochrome colors, a nostalgic mood, and abstract composition.

Title: Casual
Description: 'Casual' is an art style encompassing Pop Art, Minimalist Art, American Realism, Rustic Style, and Country Style. Mixed media are often used, with art set in everyday environments. It predominantly uses natural hues, and its mood is relaxed. Simplicity is key in the composition of Casual Art.

Title: Layering
Description: 'Layering' is an art method widely used in Collage, Decoupage, Mixed Media, Layered Painting, and Digital Art. The medium varies, but the environment is typically a studio. The color scheme is generally multi-colored, and the mood conveyed is complexity due to the layers. The artists often arrange elements in a layered composition.

Title: Subculture Fashion
Description: Subculture Fashion art style can range from street art, pop art, surrealism, modernism, and punk art. The medium of use is usually fashion design. Artists like Vivienne Westwood and Alexander McQueen adopted these Idiosyncratic styles.

Title: Dark Fashion
Description: Dark Fashion art style is often associated with art styles like Gothic, Grunge, and Cyberpunk. It involves dark color schemes and a somber mood. Artists such as Rick Owens and Alexander McQueen are known for this style.

Title: Symmetry
Description: Symmetry art style is mainly associated with Minimalist Art, Op Art, and Geometric Abstraction. It uses the painting medium and features symmetrical compositions. Artists such as Bridget Riley and Frank Stella are famous proponents of this style.

Title: Architectural Style
Description: Architectural Style art style is connected to art movements such as Baroque, Gothic, and Romanesque. The medium used is architecture in an urban environment. Renowned architects such as Bernini and Frank Gehry have employed these styles.

Title: Grand
Description: Grand art style is associated with art movements such as Baroque, Renaissance, and Romanticism. It often involves large-scale compositions in paintings that evoke an epic mood. Artists like Michelangelo and Caravaggio have championed this grandeur.

Title: Mismatched Elements
Description: Mismatched Elements art style is a genre that intentionally combines unrelated or unusual themes together. It often manifests in styles like Abstract Expressionism, Surrealism, and Pop Art. The composition of the art is usually asymmetrical offering a thought-provoking mood. The environment for these works is typically an indoor setting.

Title: Painting Technique
Description: Painting Technique art style refers to the method and manner in which an artist applies paint onto a medium. This concept encompasses a broad range of artistic styles including Impressionism, Cubism, Realism, Expressionism, and Abstract. Lighting, color, mood, and composition can vary greatly among these styles.

Title: Lino Tagliapietra
Description: Lino Tagliapietra is world-renowned for his glass art, known for its rich colors and organic composition. His works are often placed in outdoor environments under natural lighting, eliciting a lively mood. Other relevant glass artists in this style include Dale Chihuly.

Title: Transparent Glass With Colorful Overlays
Description: Transparent Glass With Colorful Overlays art style is a technique mostly seen in Stained Glass art style. The composition usually involves geometric patterns and the art is often backlit, which makes the colors glow and lend a luminous mood to the work. Louis Comfort Tiffany is a notable artist of this style.

Title: Ethnographic Photography
Description: Ethnographic Photography art style is a subset of Documentary Photography that centers on capturing cultures, societies, and people in their natural environments. This style generally uses natural lighting and is done in monochrome, creating an informative mood. The composition of the shots is often carefully framed. Notable artists include Edward Curtis and Dorothea Lange.

Title: Urban Settings
Description: Urban Settings art style depicts the aspects of city life in a wide array of mediums including oils, watercolors, and acrylics. Artists capture the essence of cities, displaying the beauty of urban landscapes and architecture. The art style can include various techniques from realism to abstraction, embodying the diversity and dynamism of urban environments.

Title: Realistic 3D Graphics
Description: Realistic 3D Graphics art style is a form of computational art that utilizes digital tools to create lifelike artistic creations. It involves creating 3D models or scenes on a computer that closely resemble real-life objects and environments. The art style focuses primarily on detail, resolution, and the accurate representation of light.

Title: Open-world Game
Description: Open-world Game art style is a type of video game that players explore a virtual world freely. The artwork of these games is as diverse as the worlds they depict, ranging from fantastical landscapes to realistic urban environments. The art style is closely tied to gameplay and narrative elements, creating an immersive, interactive experience for the player.

Title: Virtual Cities
Description: Virtual Cities art style is found in video games, digital animations and virtual reality experiences. Artists design cityscapes within the digital realm, taking those who engage in the artwork to new or futuristic environments. Virtual Cities involve complex compositions, creating realistic 3D digital models of a city that can be explored and interacted within.

Title: Primitivism
Description: Primitivism is an art style and philosophical approach that embraces the aspects of primitive or naive art. Often inspired by ancient or non-Western cultures, it seeks simplicity, rawness, and emotional intensity, stripping away the sophistication and complexities of modern art and society. Artists use simplified shapes, bold colors, and raw compositions to mimic primitive art styles.

Title: American Gothic Style
Description: American Gothic Art style often presents realistic, yet highly symbolic pictures of rural America, typically depicting stern figures in simplistic, rustic settings. Its prominent characteristic is that it relies heavily on realism with a muted color palette, understated lighting, and formal, balanced compositions.

Title: Illustrative Storytelling
Description: Illustrative Storytelling involves the use of artistic skill and narrative devices to tell a story, often within a single work or series of sequential artworks. Artists utilize symbols and visual metaphors, constructing narratives with rich details and various moods.

Title: Brom
Description: Brom is an American fantasy artist known for his unique Gothic style. His work usually explores dark and haunting themes, with complex compositions set within a gloomy, fantasy environment. Brom's art tends to have a rather menacing mood and a heavy use of dark colors.

Title: Grimdark Art
Description: Grimdark Art style takes inspiration from dark fantasy and dystopian genres, generally characterized by grim and macabre themes. The environments are typically gritty or desolate, rendered in dark colors, low lighting, and chaotic compositions, communicating a sense of despair and hopelessness.

Title: Gris Grimly Art
Description: Gris Grimly is an illustrator known for his distinctive art style that combines aspects of macabre and Gothic genres in a fantastical setting. Grimly's work often has a chilling mood, characterized by dynamic compositions, eerie lighting, and a muted color palette.

Title: Grayscale Painting
Description: Grayscale painting art style refers to artworks created primarily using various shades of gray. It is a technique often associated with photography, but is used in painting as well. The monochromatic scheme of grayscale paintings can create a striking contrast, allowing for deep emotional connectivity and a dramatic visual impact. Famous artists like Pablo Picasso and Georges Seurat have utilized this style effectively.

Title: Monochrome Painting
Description: Monochrome painting art style involves the use of a single color, with different shades, tones and textures to convey depth and perception. The style focuses on the form and structure of the subject, rather than its color. This art style has been leveraged by artists like Yves Klein, Kazimir Malevich and Ad Reinhardt to produce profound and impactful pieces of art.

Title: Subtle Tonal Variations
Description: Subtle tonal variations art style is characterized by close attention to light and color details, often utilizing layers of subtly different hues and illuminations to provide a sense of depth, form, and texture. This technique is widely used in impressionist and minimalist painting, giving a calming and balanced effect. Artists associated with this style include Claude Monet, Vincent van Gogh, and J.M.W. Turner.

Title: Alternative
Description: Alternative art style represents a break from traditional artistic conventions. It encapsulates a wide range of styles that may include anything from pop art to graffiti. Notably, the mood in these types of art tends to be quite rebellious and the composition non-traditional. Some well-known artists who have explored alternative art styles include Jean-Michel Basquiat, Banksy, and Eduardo Kobra.

Title: Luxury
Description: Luxury art style is often associated with a sense of prestige and opulence. It includes art styles like Baroque, Rococo, and Neoclassical, all of which have lavish decoration, intricate details, and a display of wealth and power. Artists such as Peter Paul Rubens, Giovanni Battista Tiepolo, and Jacques-Louis David are associated with this artistic concept.

Title: Erotic
Description: Erotic art style encompasses the use of provocative and sensual themes that are often accompanied with vibrant colors and dynamic compositions. Mainly found in painting mediums, it has various affiliated art styles such as Realism, Surrealism, and Abstract.

Title: Neo-noir
Description: Neo-noir art style is characterized by the use of urban environment, mysterious mood and monochrome color scheme. It is mainly associated with low-key lighting and high contrast composition, related to Conceptual Art and Film Noir styles. Christopher Nolan and David Lynch are prominent artists of this style.

Title: Cel-shaded
Description: Cel-shaded art style is predominantly used in animation medium with a particular emphasis on bright colors and flat composition. This style is closely related to Anime and Cartoon art styles. Some renowned artists include Hayao Miyazaki and Osamu Tezuka.

Title: Arcade
Description: Arcade art style found its existence in the digital medium, specifically in virtual environments. This style showcases dynamic colors, projecting a sense of fun. Mainly associated with Pixel Art and Vector Art styles, artists like Shigeru Miyamoto and Masahiro Sakurai made a mark in this field.

Title: Hiroyuki Imaishi
Description: Hiroyuki Imaishi, an animator by profession, created defiant renditions in the Anime and Mecha art styles. His work clearly speaks for his eloquent use of vibrant colors and dynamic composition, predominantly used in the animation medium.

Title: Kazuki Nakashima
Description: Kazuki Nakashima's art style is often seen in dramatic TV scripts, with an intense mood and emphasis on strong plot development. He's often collaborated with Hiroyuki Imaishi, Akira Amemiya, and Yō Yoshinari.

Title: Glamour Photography
Description: Glamour Photography art style showcases a focus on the subject, often with a soft light and vivid colors. Fashion, Beauty, and Boudoir Photography are related styles. Noted artists include Helmut Newton, Mario Testino, and Annie Leibovitz.

Title: Contemporary Figurative Art
Description: The Contemporary Figurative Art style often uses varied colors, with painting as a medium. It's expressive, featuring figures and objects as a main component. Similar styles are Abstract Figurative Art, Neo-Expressionism, and Postmodern Art. Jenny Saville, Lucian Freud, and Eric Fischl are associated artists.

Title: Crime Film
Description: Crime Film art style is a filmic concept often set in urban environments. Typical mood is suspenseful, with varying lighting and color. The composition primarily focuses on situations. Artists like Quentin Tarantino, Martin Scorsese, and Francis Ford Coppola are known for this style.

Title: Action-comedy Film
Description: The Action-comedy Film art style takes the form of film, set in varied environments. It displays an exciting mood, utilizes vibrant colors with bold lighting, and dynamic composition. Noted artists include Jackie Chan, Edgar Wright, and Shane Black.

Title: Gritty Visual Style
Description: Gritty Visual Style art is a subset of fine art characterized by a raw, harsh, and unrefined aesthetic. Its use of muted colors and low key lighting creates an intense mood. The style is often found in realism, modern art, and street art genres, with notable artists like Edward Kienholz, Jean-Michel Basquiat, and Banksy leaving their mark on the genre.

Title: Russian Folk Art
Description: Russian Folk Art style is a traditional and decorative art form. It employs vibrant colors and commonly involves craftsmanship in sculptures. Often reflecting rural environments, the art form presents a symmetrical composition imparting a nostalgic mood. Some of the renowned artists include Ivan Bilibin, Maria Prymachenko, and Sergei Malyutin.

Title: Traditional Craftsmanship
Description: Traditional Craftsmanship style is commonly found in classical and folk art genres. The prime medium often includes detailed sculptural work. This art style invites a reflective mood while celebrating craftsmanship. Notable artists of this style include Daniel Brush, Boris Sipek, and Edgar Brandt.

Title: Horror Literature
Description: Horror Literature art style is characterized by fearful mood and often found in macabre, gothic and dark fantasy genres. This style is unique to the literature medium with prominent authors such as Stephen King, Edgar Allan Poe, and H.P. Lovecraft.

Title: Cosmic Horror
Description: Cosmic Horror art style is distinctive in the literature medium and is characterized by a mood of dread. It's often found in dark fantasy, macabre, and surreal genres. Renowned writers of this style include H.P. Lovecraft, Clark Ashton Smith, and Robert W. Chambers.

Title: Weird Fiction
Description: Weird Fiction art style is an artistic interpretation of literary 'weird fiction'. Often adopting elements from surrealism, dada, and outsider art, it may feature unsettling or 'weird' scenarios echoing the uncanny nature of its literary counterpart. The composition is intentionally random to stress the chaotic, strange and eerie atmosphere, often manifesting through painting.

Title: Biomechanical Art
Description: Biomechanical art style merges organic with mechanistic. Elements of Futurism, Surrealism, and Industrial styles are commonly applied. The environment is typically industrial, reflecting a fusion of flesh and metal. These are often brought to life via sculptures with a predominantly metallic color scheme.

Title: Greek Mythology
Description: Artistic representations of Greek Mythology typically adopt the styles of Classicism or Hellenistic period. The media often selected is sculpture, portraying the grandeur and epic nature of the myths. A common color palette is monochromatic, emphasizing the antiquity and historical iconicity.

Title: Underworld Aesthetics
Description: Underworld Aesthetics art style is marked by dark, enigmatic symbolism often seen in Gothic art. The setting places emphasis on underground or cavernous spaces, painted under low-light conditions, to instigate a sense of mystery and fear associated with the underworld.

Title: Sophisticated Minimalism
Description: Sophisticated Minimalism art style is an offshoot of Minimalism, valued for its stark simplicity and calm mood. Often presented via sculptures, its color palette is generally monochromatic, emphasizing the simpleness yet elegance of its composition.

Title: Manga Art
Description: Manga art refers to comics created in Japan or by creators who adhere to the recognizable style of Japanese manga. Often crafted in black and white, Manga art is typically characterized by its unique panel-oriented composition. Artists use a range of styles such as Shōnen, Seinen, Josei, Shōjo, and Kodomomuke, each catering to different demographic groups. Manga can depict a variety of moods and environments.

Title: Shonen Manga
Description: Shōnen Manga style falls under Manga Art and targets young teen male demographic with its dynamic, action-oriented visual storytelling. It's characterized by its high paced action scenes whether in sports, fantasy, or adventure. While the color scheme is typically black and white, the mood, environment, and lighting can vary greatly depending on the narrative.

Title: Dynamic Action Scenes
Description: The dynamic action scenes art style is characterized by its emphasis on movement and energy. Various styles such as Impressionism, Expressionism, Futurism, and Cubism have been used to convey vigor and dynamism. The style is often characterized by vibrant color schemes and a composition that's oriented to depict motion. The mood is generally energetic, shown against a backdrop of active environments with varying lighting.

Title: Print Design
Description: The Print Design art style focuses on creating designs for print, including typography, illustration, branding, photography, and layout design. The color and mood can range across the spectrum depending on the brief or design goal. The compositions are layout oriented, which properly manage both the design elements and information flow. Notable artists in this field include Paul Rand, Milton Glaser, Massimo Vignelli, David Carson, and Neville Brody.

Title: Photograph
Description: Photography is an art form that uses cameras to create images on light sensitive materials. Various styles emerged, including photorealism which strives for utmost detail; to more abstract or conceptual approaches, employing various moods, colors, and compositions. Iconic photographers include Ansel Adams and Henri Cartier-Bresson.

Title: Tachisme
Description: Tachisme originated as a reaction to cubism in painting, denoting a return to the spontaneous transcription of emotion onto canvas. It's associated with the wider European movement of Art Informel. The style is characterized by spontaneous brushwork, drips and blobs of paint straight from the tube, and sometimes scribbling reminiscent of calligraphy.

Title: Kawaii Fashion
Description: Kawaii Fashion is an art style originating from Japan that is centered around the concept of cuteness, or 'kawaii'. This style manifests in varied substyles, including Decora, Gothic Lolita, Harajuku, etc. Typically cheery and bright, significant figures include Kyary Pamyu Pamyu and Misako Aoki.

Title: Norwegian National Romanticism
Description: Norwegian National Romanticism is an art style marked by the celebration of Norwegian nature, rural life, and national history. The style is derivative of Romanticism and Romantic Nationalism, characteristically portrayed through careful scenic composition and a nostalgic mood. Notable figures include Johan Christian Dahl and Erik Werenskiold.

Title: High-speed Photography
Description: High-speed Photography is a style capturing extremely fast phenomena. Using technical skills to master light and movement, artists like Harold Edgerton and Eadweard Muybridge have been able to freeze moments in time that are too quick for the human eye, often resulting in dynamic and spectacular compositions.

Title: Gibson Girl
Description: Gibson Girl is an artistic concept characterized by illustrations that define the social and cultural standards of the new, modern woman in the early 20th century America. The art style is usually associated with Art Nouveau, and typical illustrations depict elegant and independent women.

Title: International Style
Description: As an art concept, the International Style was a major architectural style in the 1920s and 1930s. It is associated with an emphasis on volume over mass, regular repetitions of modular forms, and the avoidance of ornamentation. The style is most widely seen in urban environments.

Title: Yasuhiro Wada
Description: Yasuhiro Wada is best known for his work in the field of video game design. His art style emphasizes vibrant colors, casual moods, and imaginary environments. It often fosters interactions with objects and characters within the game world.

Title: Rural
Description: Rural art style revolves around scenes of countryside and less populated, pastoral areas. It often features natural tones that capture the peaceful atmosphere of rural life. These artworks, largely composed in painting medium, can be found in realism, impressionism and landscape art styles.

Title: Traditional Japanese
Description: Traditional Japanese art is known for its distinctive styles - from ukiyo-e woodblock prints to Nihonga paintings. This art style often reveals a rich culture and tradition, featuring bold colors, simple compositions, and historical environments through various mediums, including origami.

Title: Courtly
Description: The courtly art style is associated with the royal courts of the Renaissance, Baroque, and Rococo periods. This cultural phenomenon portrays refined and dignified moods in paintings, characterized by symmetrical composition and soft, rich colors and often depicted in natural light.

Title: Manga Series
Description: Manga series art style is characteristic to Japanese comic or graphic novel series, which portrays a wide array of moods. It mainly includes Shōnen, Shōjo, and Seinen styles, distinguished by panel layouts and depicted in either black-and-white or color, set against urban and fantasy environments.

Title: Body Art
Description: Body art style uses the human body as a medium for self-expression. The mood portrayed is typically expressive and it comes in various colors. This style includes a variety of forms such as Tattoo, Henna, and Body Paint, with the composition shaped by the body's anatomy.

Title: Temporary Tattoo
Description: The Temporary Tattoo art style applies transient designs on the skin. Including Henna, Airbrush, and Stick-on styles, this art fits a casual mood and varies in color. The composition of a temporary tattoo piece is dependent on the body part where it is applied.

Title: Botanical Illustration
Description: Botanical Illustration art style is a precise, realistic depiction of plants in their natural environment under natural light. This peaceful art style uses vibrant colors and puts a singular focus on the botanical subject. Renowned artists of this style include Pierre-Joseph Redouté and Maria Sibylla Merian.

Title: Clear Line
Description: The Clear Line (ligne claire) art style originated in the powerful lines of comic-strip artwork popular in French and Belgian comics. It is characterized by strong, distinct, and clean lines devoid of cross-hatching, typically in black and white. Clear Line compositions often emphasize alignment and balance. Artists like Hergé and Joost Swarte have been great proponents of this particular style.

Title: Early Netherlandish Painting
Description: Early Netherlandish Painting refers to the prominent period of art in the 15th and 16th centuries which emerged from the Northern Renaissance. Famed for detailed, complex compositions and naturalistic representation, it exploited natural lighting and rich, subtle colors. The mood is usually reverent with settings ranging from indoors to outdoors. Artists like Jan van Eyck and Rogier van der Weyden were figureheads of this artistic movement.

Title: Sports Photography
Description: Sports Photography is an art style and discipline that captures exciting, action-filled moments in various sports events. The composition mainly focuses on the athleticism, drama, and thrilling moments unfolding at sports venues. The lighting can vary widely, ranging from natural to artificial stadium lights. Prominent sports photographers like Walter Iooss and Neil Leifer have brought to life some of the most iconic moments in sports history.

Title: Action Photography
Description: Action Photography is an art form that focuses on capturing pivotal moments in high motion environments. It's an expansive genre covering areas like photojournalism, nature, and sports photography. The compositions are action-oriented, capturing tense and highly charged moments. The lighting conditions can range greatly, as can the environments, from riots to bustling cities, to wild plains. Famous photographers like Henri Cartier-Bresson and Elliott Erwitt have made substantial contributions to this field.

Title: Urban Fashion
Description: Urban Fashion is an art style in fashion design that emerged from streetwear and hip hop cultures. It incorporates aggressive, daring styles and is usually showcased in an urban environment. The compositions are often layered and daring, with a color palette that can vary greatly. Designers like Virgil Abloh and Alexander Wang have made substantial contributions to the Urban Fashion scene.

Title: Toy Camera Photography
Description: Toy Camera Photography art style is a form of experimental or alternative photography using low-fidelity cameras. The art style often includes elements of Lomography, Holga, and Pinhole Photography. It’s characterized by a blurry and unpredictable composition which adds a 'nostalgic' mood to the image. The color scheme is often vivid. Notable artists include Diane Arbus, Sally Mann, and David Burnett.

Title: Animated Video Game
Description: Animated Video Game art style brings imaginary worlds to life through digital art. This style can be diverse but often includes components of Pixel Art, 3D Graphics, or a cartoonish look. Environment is a key element, often portraying fantasy or adventurous realms. The mood is commonly adventurous with a dynamic composition. Artists like Shigeru Miyamoto, Hideo Kojima, and John Carmack have made significant contributions.

Title: Edward Leedskalnin
Description: Edward Leedskalnin is a famous stone sculptor known for his mysterious stones and geometric composition. His work, largely done outdoors, exemplifies the Stone Sculpture art style and is mostly presented in monochrome. He created a sense of mystery in his work. Edward himself is the most renowned artist of this style.

Title: Dick Termes
Description: Dick Termes is a painter notable for his uniqueness in creating 'Termespheres', paintings on spherical canvasses that provide a 360° view of a surreal environment. His work typically entails various colors, and a sense of surrealism. Dick Termes himself is most associated with this particular style.

Title: Harriet Casdin-Silver
Description: Harriet Casdin-Silver was a renowned artist and photographer, recognized for her pioneering work in the art style of Holography. Her artwork often displayed an ethereal mood with its monochrome color scheme and layered composition. Harriet Casdin-Silver herself is the most celebrated figure in this medium.

Title: Orientalist Painting
Description: Orientalist Painting is an art style characterized by its focus on depicting scenes from the Middle Eastern and North African cultures. It is often associated with Romanticism, Realism, and Symbolism. The art style is known for its rich, colorful, large-scale compositions.

Title: Post-apocalyptic Art
Description: Post-apocalyptic Art refers to an art style that depicts the aftermath of a catastrophic event that has caused the collapse of civilization. The style is often associated with Surrealism and Conceptual Art, representing a gloomy and desolate mood.

Title: Animated Film
Description: Animated Film refers to a cinematic art style that involves the perception of motion created by displaying a series of drawings or photographs. It is characterized by its use of digital animation techniques and encompasses a range of styles including Anime, Cartoon, and 3D Animation.

Title: Stylized Realism
Description: Stylized Realism is an art style that synthesizes realistic and stylized techniques, often characterized by dramatic lighting, vibrant colors, and dynamic composing. It is associated with Impressionism, Expressionism, and Modern Art styles.

Title: Beaux-Arts
Description: Beaux-Arts refers to an art style that originated from the influential French art school, École des Beaux-Arts. It is associated with Neoclassicism, Baroque, and Academic Art styles, and is often seen in architectural designs characterized by bright lighting, balanced color schemes, and symmetrical compositions.

Title: Fairy Art
Description: Fairy Art is an art style that largely falls into the category of Fantasy art. It characteristically portrays fantastical creatures, especially fairies, emphasizing magic and nature. The style borrows elements from Romanticism, with pastel color schemes, and soft lighting often illustrated in a painting medium. Prominent artists include Brian Froud and Amy Brown, who have significantly contributed to the style with their whimsical and magical depictions of fairies.

Title: Ikea
Description: The Ikea art style is predominant in its range of furniture and product design which leans heavily on principles of minimalism and Scandinavian design. The style is marked by functionality and an appeal to sustainability that promotes efficient usage of materials. Color schemes tend to be neutral, with a focus on clean lines and geometric patterns. The style doesn't have a specific artist directly associated with it, as it more draws from an ethos of design rather than an individual artist's approach.

Title: Japanese Traditional
Description: Japanese Traditional art style is a general term encompassing a variety of distinctive styles, including Ukiyo-e, Yamato-e, and Nihonga. Known for its painting medium, this art style commonly uses fluid colors and depicts an intricate balance between figure and ground. Artists often use natural lighting with natural themes in an asymmetrical composition. Notable artists include Hokusai and Maruyama Okyo, who have contributed significantly to the development of Japanese traditional art.

Title: New Vision
Description: New Vision is an art style originating from the 1920s-30s, primarily dealing with photography. It sought to break away from traditional perspectives and engage with a fresh, abstract approach. The style uses contrasting lighting, often depicting urban environments in a non-linear, dynamic composition. Key artists associated with this art style are Laszlo Moholy-Nagy and Alexander Rodchenko, who fundamentally explored new possibilities of perception within this movement.

Title: Neo-Primitivism
Description: Neo-Primitivism is described as an early 20th-century art style that blends aspects of modern techniques like Abstract Art and Cubism alongside inspiration drawn from indigenous and folk art forms. The style is often reflected in painting, with bold lighting and vibrant colors. It presents an intense mood through a simplistic yet abstract composition. Artists including Natalia Goncharova and Kazimir Malevich are major contributors to the movement.

Title: Steam Age Fashion
Description: Steam Age Fashion refers to an art style influenced by the late 18th and early 19th-century industrial steam-powered machinery fashion. Often set in industrial era landscapes, artworks in this style employ various metallic and brown hues and display a peculiar asymmetrical composition.

Title: Giorgia Lupi
Description: Giorgia Lupi is best known for her data visualization art style where she applies an evocative, human touch to data. Her artworks involve medium of digital art and interactive designs.

Title: David McCandless
Description: David McCandless is renowned for his distinctive style of data visualization. His approach involves the digital medium, often interweaving information graphics and interactive designs to create visually striking patterns and connections.

Title: Richard Mosse
Description: Richard Mosse is prominent for his unique style of conceptual photography encapsulating war zones. His works employ infrared color scheme predominantly and are often set in turbulent areas.

Title: Robert Buelteman
Description: Robert Buelteman is celebrated for his unique electrophotography style where he creates electrifying images of nature. His work outlines the beauty of natural environments using a rare electroluminescent lighting technique.

Title: Susan Aldworth
Description: Susan Aldworth is an artist who blends science and printmaking to explore human identity. Known for her etchings, drawings, and films, Aldworth draws inspiration from neuroscience, depicting the complexity of the human brain.

Title: Art House Cinema
Description: Art House Cinema refers to a film genre that distinguishes itself through its non-mainstream narrative and experimental techniques. These films are often produced by independent studios, offering a reflective mood and a non-linear narrative in an urban setting.

Title: Psychological Drama
Description: Psychological Drama refers to a film genre that focuses on the inner conflict within characters. They are typically characterized by a complex narrative structure and a tense atmosphere, provided by artists such as Alfred Hitchcock and Stanley Kubrick.

Title: David Linley
Description: David Linley is renowned for his fine cabinetry and furniture art, working exclusively with wood. His designs are often influenced by furniture artists such as George Hepplewhite and George Smith.

Title: Thomas Chippendale
