Description: Thomas Chippendale was a British furniture artist who merged Rococo and Neoclassical styles in his works. His influential designs set in wood continue to inspire furniture designers like George Hepplewhite and John Linnell.

Title: André-Charles Boulle
Description: André-Charles Boulle was a French cabinetmaker who is noted for his exquisite designs in furniture. His art style was mainly Baroque and Rococo, with Marquetry being a pinnacle of his work. He typically used wood as the medium. His works rose to fame for their magnificence and complexity.

Title: Woodworking
Description: Woodworking as an art style involves creating items from wood. Applied methods include carpentry, cabinetmaking, wood carving, turning, and marquetry. It's both an art and a craft, where the artist uses wood to create decorative or practical elements.

Title: Scott Robertson
Description: Scott Robertson is an American concept artist, known for his innovative approach to digital art. His styles span across conceptual art, illustration, and industrial design. He uses digital mediums for his work, creating futuristic, highly-stylized visuals.

Title: Felix Scheinberger
Description: Felix Scheinberger is a German illustrator recognized for his expressive illustrations and cartooning, often painted with vibrant watercolors. His artworks are marked by dynamic lines and vivid color schemes, making his style distinctive and approachable.

Title: Fine Art Printmaking
Description: Fine Art Printmaking is a style of art that involves creating a 'print' onto paper. This includes various techniques like etching, linocut, woodcut, lithography, and screenprinting. Printmaking allows for multiple copies of a piece to be produced.

Title: Wood Inlay
Description: Wood Inlay is an art style which uses pieces of wood, cut in precise shapes, to form decorative patterns, often geometric. Marquetry, Parquetry, and Intarsia are related styles. Andrei Ramniceanu and David Marks are notable artists in this field.

Title: Miniature Sculptures
Description: Miniature Sculptures are tiny, intricately detailed three-dimensional artworks. They can be made from various mediums including clay, wood, and metal. They can encompass various art styles, Hedcut and Pop Art among them. Willard Wigan is a renowned artist in this sphere.

Title: Film Installation
Description: Film Installation is an art style where movies are projected onto surfaces in public spaces or galleries. Related genres include Conceptual art, Performance art, and Installation art. Artists like Doug Aitken and Bill Viola are popular in this sphere.

Title: Multimedia Art
Description: Multimedia Art is an art style that utilizes various types of media to create a cohesive, multifaceted artwork. Related styles include Installation Art, Digital Art, and Electrography. Notable artists include Robert Rauschenberg and Joseph Nechvatal.

Title: Islamic
Description: Islamic art style is characterized by a range of artistic styles, such as Arabesque and Islamic calligraphy, reflecting Islamic culture and spiritual themes. The medium can vary widely. Notable artists include Seyyed Hossein Nasr and El Seed.

Title: Video Games
Description: Video games encompass a wide range of art styles, from pixel art to 3D modeling, often depending on the technology available or the design choice. They provide a virtual environment for storytelling, which often involves dynamic lighting and vibrant colors. Establishing mood is key in video games to make players feel more immersed in the world. Artists such as Hideo Kojima and Shigeru Miyamoto are known for shaping the art of video games.

Title: Contemporary Design
Description: Contemporary Design, using art styles like minimalism and postmodernism, focuses on innovative compositions and often adapts to the surrounding environment. The mood is current and the lighting functional. Colors are balanced, and the medium is varied, encompassing everything from textiles to digital interfaces. Artists like Philippe Starck and Zaha Hadid have famously contributed to contemporary design.

Title: Shin-hanga
Description: Shin-hanga art style was greatly influenced by Ukiyo-e, Impressionism, and Romanticism. It primarily uses woodblock print. The compositions are often narrative-based and set in natural environments. The colors are rich and the lighting soft to establish a peaceful mood. Hiroshi Yoshida and Hasui Kawase are some of the renowned shin-hanga artists.

Title: Relief
Description: Relief art style involves carving into or out of a flat surface, using materials such as stone to create a sculptural environment with styles like Bas-relief, high-relief, and sunken-relief. The compositions are structured and often monochromatic, dependent on artificial lighting. They primarily portray a historical mood. Notable relief artists include Donatello and Augustus Saint-Gaudens.

Title: Ottoman Empire
Description: The Ottoman Empire art style was significantly influenced by Islamic, Byzantine, and Persian art. The medium largely focused on architectural and mural forms. These compositions were geometric with multicolored schemes. The environment was grand and the use of natural light was common. Artists like Sinan and Osman Hamdi Bey were closely associated with this art style.

Title: Tile
Description: Tile art style typically involves the use of small pieces of glazed ceramic or stone, often in geometric formations or illustrative scenes. Artists like Gaudi, Burne-Jones, and Rhead significantly influenced this art style.

Title: Eerie
Description: Eerie art style is characterized by dark palettes, low-key lighting, sparse compositions, and a mysterious mood. It is related to styles including Gothic, Surrealism, and Romanticism. Known artists in this style include Goya, Giger, and Munch.

Title: Action Painting
Description: Action Painting, closely associated with Abstract Expressionism, is focused on the physical act of painting. Irregular strokes reflecting high energy form dynamic compositions. Artists like Pollock, de Kooning, and Kline are famous for this style.

Title: Built Environment
Description: Built Environment art often involves capturing man-made surroundings, such as architecture or cityscapes, often through photography or painting. The style represents realism with complex compositions and natural lighting. Artists like Stoller, Höfer, and Gursky are known for this style.

Title: Snapshot
Description: Snapshot art style refers to candid, raw photographs capturing unposed scenes. Reminiscent of documentary and street photography, this style emphasizes natural lighting and presents a candid mood. Renowned Snapshot artists include Moriyama, Frank, and Winogrand.

Title: Camp
Description: Camp art style is a mode of aesthetics that values over-the-top, artificial elements. It's often humorous, and re-imagines popular culture in bizarre or caricatured ways. Notable artists in this style include Andy Warhol and Jeff Koons.

Title: Decadence
Description: Decadence art style is characterized by a luxurious, ornate, and sophisticated aesthetic that reflects a preference for the extravagant. Associated with late 19th-century Symbolism, its primary artists include Aubrey Beardsley and Gustav Klimt.

Title: Gorillaz Style
Description: The Gorillaz Style art style is a distinctive blend of pop art and graffiti, popularized by artist Jamie Hewlett for the virtual band Gorillaz. This style typically features vibrant colors, dynamic compositions, and animated characters set against urban landscapes.

Title: Single-point Perspective
Description: Single-point Perspective art style introduced a new way of rendering spatial depth in the time of Renaissance. Notable artists, like Leonardo da Vinci and Brunelleschi, used this technique to create realistic and eye-pleasing art pieces.

Title: Digital Manipulation
Description: Digital Manipulation art refers to art that has been created or altered with digital technology. This style often features unconventional compositions and a variety of colors. Notable artists in this art include Banksy and Tara Donovan.

Title: Japanese Graphic Design
Description: Japanese Graphic Design art style is characterized by a broad range of sensibilities, often blending traditional Japanese aesthetics with modern design principles. It can be vibrant in color and flat in composition, showcasing simplicity, minimalism, and strong typography. Notable artists in this art style include Yusaku Kamekura, Shigeo Fukuda, and Tadanori Yokoo.

Title: Retro Aesthetics
Description: Retro Aesthetics art style refers to designs inspired by the visual culture of the past. The art style often features bright colors, dynamic shapes and size contrasts. Common art styles include Pop Art, Art Deco, Dadaism, and Futurism. Notable artists include Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein, and Peter Blake.

Title: Big-eyed Art
Description: Big-eyed Art is a style of art that features paintings, drawings, or sculptures of individuals, predominantly children, with big eyes. It often uses vivid colors and is characterized by a centered composition. Some of the key artists of this art style include Margaret Keane, Mark Ryden, and Audrey Kawasaki.

Title: Gothic Aesthetics
Description: Gothic Aesthetics art style is often characterized by dark themes, historical settings, and a detailed composition, commonly found in the Gothic Art, Gothic Revival, and Victorian Gothic styles. Artists often utilize dim lighting and a dark color palette to create a melancholic mood. Notable artists include Jan van Eyck, Albrecht Durer, and Eugene Viollet-le-Duc.

Title: Neo-Dada
Description: Neo-Dada is an art style that emerged in the 1950s as a reaction against Abstract Expressionism. It is characterized by a return to the use of everyday objects and an emphasis on assemblage. Notable artists associated with this movement include Robert Rauschenberg, Jasper Johns, and Claes Oldenburg.

Title: Academicism
Description: Academicism is an art style characterized by a detailed, polished execution that adheres to the guidelines of the academies where art was officially taught. It often utilizes a realistic color scheme and portrays a serious mood. Well-known artists of this style include Jean-Léon Gérôme and William-Adolphe Bouguereau.

Title: French New Wave
Description: The French New Wave was a film movement known for its experimental techniques, disruptive mood, non-linear narrative and natural lighting. It had a tremendous impact on modern cinema and is closely associated with directors like Jean-Luc Godard and François Truffaut.

Title: Neo-pop
Description: Neo-Pop is an art style which emerged as a reaction to the seriousness of abstract expressionism. It makes use of vibrant colors, irony and collaged compositions. Notable artists include Jeff Koons and Takashi Murakami.

Title: Photorealistic
Description: Photorealism is an art style characterized by paintings that appear to be high-quality photographs. The color is life-like, and the composition is highly accurate. Richard Estes and Chuck Close are significant artists of this style.

Title: Urban Landscape
Description: Urban Landscape art style represents the physical aspects of a city or an urban area. Artists like Edward Hopper, Camille Pissarro, and Grant Wood have all explored this style, with the mood, color, and composition varying depending on the artist’s interpretation and the chosen perspective.

Title: Underground Comic
Description: Underground Comic art style is an alternative comic style emerged as a countertoric to traditional comics, using satire and subversion to explore taboo topics. Primarily created via drawing, these comics are usually sequential and offer a rebellious mood.

Title: Dark Humor
Description: Dark Humor in art style can be grim and macabre. Absurdist and satirical, the themes of death, social taboos, and mental illness are often represented in dark tones in paintings. Key artists include Charles Addams, known for 'The Addams Family'.

Title: Comic Books
Description: Comic Book art style puts storytelling through sequential pieces of art. It can be graphic, superhero or science fiction where drawings are the main medium. Artists like Stan Lee have made considerable contributions to this style.

Title: Period Drama
Description: Period Drama art style involves historical and realistic depictions often set in historic environments. The medium typically is film, featuring naturalistic lighting, pictorial color schemes, and a distinct nostalgic mood.

Title: Puppetry
Description: Puppetry art style involves Marionette, Shadow, and Hand puppet styles. The art is performative, usually set on a stage with spotlight lighting, vibrant colors, and a whimsical mood. Artists like Jim Henson contribute significantly to this style.

Title: Muppet Style
Description: Muppet Style is a unique and vibrant art style seen in the popular puppet-based franchise, The Muppets. The style features simple shapes, vivid colors, and is mainly seen in theatrical set environments.

Title: Cosmic
Description: Cosmic art style expresses the mysteries and wonders of outer space. Lighting conditions generally reflect starlight, with deep blues and purples often predominating the color scheme. The mood is often mysterious, and celestial bodies are generally found in the compositions.

Title: Contemporary Illustration
Description: Contemporary Illustration art style is an ever-evolving field, incorporating elements from various art styles such as Pop Art, Minimalism, or Surrealism. The medium usually involves graphic design, and the moods and compositions are highly varied, reflecting the diversity of this art style.

Title: Storybook Illustration
Description: Storybook Illustration art style is predominantly seen in children's books, fairy tales, and fantasy stories. Its usual medium is drawing, with a playful mood and a narrative composition being characteristic features of this art style.

Title: Menswear
Description: Menswear art style refers to fashion design geared towards men's clothing—with art styles such as Tailoring, Streetwear, and Business Casual. The mood is typically sophisticated, with composition principles often involving layering.

Title: Conservation Photography
Description: The Conservation Photography art style is closely related to Documentary and Wildlife photography, primarily utilizing the medium of photography. The art is often set in a natural environment and takes advantage of natural lighting. The color scheme tends to be vivid, effectively capturing the beauty of nature. The mood is often sobering, as this style aims to show the need for conservation. The composition normally involves wide-angle shots to encompass a full view of the environment. Notable artists in this genre include James Balog and Ansel Adams.

Title: Morbid
Description: The Morbid art style relates heavily to Surrealism and Gothic, mainly practised in the form of painting. It is often characterized by dark and eerie environments with low lighting. Dark tones are commonly used to create a sense of dread and melancholy. The composition tends to be asymmetrical, contributing to the unsettling atmosphere. Significant artists include Francisco Goya and Hieronymus Bosch.

Title: Folklore
Description: The Folklore art style draws heavily from Narrative Art and Symbolism, generally executed through painting. The art often depicts countryside settings, with warm lighting and an earth tone color scheme. The mood conveyed is nostalgic, echoing back to old customs and traditions. The composition is usually detailed, emphasizing the richness of cultural narratives. Artists such as Ivan Bilibin and Marc Chagall are notable for their work with this style.

Title: Independent Film
Description: The Independent Film art style is strongly characterized by Cinéma Vérité and New Wave styles, and naturally, the medium is film. These films often project urban environments with natural colors and ambient lighting, which contribute to creating a realistic mood. The composition tends to be intimate, focusing on personal stories and minute details. Artists like John Cassavetes and Jean-Luc Godard are renowned for their contributions in this field.

Title: Hong Kong Cinema
Description: The Hong Kong Cinema art style is primarily associated with Martial Arts Cinema, Wuxia, and Cantopop, all presented through the medium of film. They usually feature urban settings, dramatically lit, and complemented with vivid colors. The mood is dynamic, reflecting the fast-paced and action-packed compositions common to the style. Famous artists in this genre include Bruce Lee, Jackie Chan, and John Woo.

Title: Crime Thriller
Description: Crime Thriller art style primarily uses the medium of film, focusing on suspense and intrigue. It is typically set in urban environments, often employing low-key lighting and monochromatic color schemes to create a mood of suspense and tension. Composition is dramatically structured to draw attention to key narrative elements.

Title: Shōnen
Description: Shōnen, a popular art style of anime and manga, is characterized by its dynamic composition and vibrant color schemes. Shōnen primarily uses animation, with fantasy settings featuring bright lighting. The mood is exciting, often captivating young male audiences. Notable artists include Akira Toriyama, Eiichiro Oda, and Kohei Horikoshi.

Title: Post-painterly Abstraction
Description: Post-Painterly Abstraction is a term coined by art critic Clement Greenberg for a broad reaction against the expressive gestural abstraction of Abstract Expressionist painting. It is characterized by its multicolored palette, less emotional and more intellectual style, and generally unstructured composition. Notable artists include Kenneth Noland and Frank Stella.

Title: Mexican Muralism
Description: Mexican Muralism developed as a way to inform and provoke the public through narrative images painted on public walls. Notable artists Diego Rivera and José Clemente Orozco created murals with provocative motifs, often depicting socio-political themes in earthy colors, making the medium a powerful tool for social change.

Title: Poetic Photography
Description: Poetic Photography is a style that seeks to depict the beauty, complexity, and subtlety of everyday life. It uses natural lighting and predominantly monochromatic color schemes to create evocative images. Composition tends to be minimalist, stripping away unnecessary detail to focus on the subject. Known practitioners include Henri Cartier-Bresson and Ansel Adams.

Title: Tiki Culture
Description: Tiki Culture art style is heavily influenced by Polynesian, vintage, and retro art forms. The art is mainly presented through sculptures in a tropical environment, boasting a vibrant color scheme. The composition of this style is decorative, setting a relaxed mood for observers. Famous artists like Don the Beachcomber and Trader Vic have significantly contributed to this art style.

Title: Horror Manga
Description: Horror Manga art style is a blend of conventional Manga and Japanese horror, usually presented as illustrations. The setting is often gothic, heavily reliant on dark lighting for its fearful mood. This monochromatic composition mainly follows a narrative structure. Famous artists include Junji Ito and Hideshi Hino.

Title: Various K-pop Fashion Designers
Description: K-pop Fashion art style captures a mix of streetwear, high fashion, and avant-garde art, brought to life through the medium of clothing. The color scheme is often a mix, creating an energetic mood. The composition is usually edgy, with designers like Bajowoo and Hyein Seo at the forefront.

Title: Various Native American Artists
Description: Native American art style incorporates the characteristics of tribal and folk art. Primarily exhibited through sculptures, this style is typically set in a natural environment with an earth tone color palette. It often portrays a solemn mood, with a symbolic composition. Renowned artists include Fritz Scholder and R.C. Gorman.

Title: Native American
Description: Native American art style is a broad term encompassing the work of numerous tribes and artists. Prevalent styles include tribal and folk art, often conveyed through mediums like sculpture, and beadwork. These works typically feature earth tones, and are designed to harmonize with the natural world, often maintaining a solemn, contemplative mood.

Title: African American
Description: African American art style encompasses the visual artistic expressions of the African American community. It uses vibrant colors to create expressive and narrative compositions. Notable artists in this style include Jacob Lawrence, Romare Bearden, Kara Walker, Kehinde Wiley, and Faith Ringgold.

Title: Various Kalighat Painters
Description: The Kalighat painting style, developed by various Kalighat painters, is a type of Indian miniature and Bengali folk art. Employing bold colors, these artists depict spiritual themes through figurative compositions. Notable artists in this style include Nihâl Chand and Kailash Chandra Meher.

Title: Indian Folk
Description: Indian Folk art style is a vibrant blend of local Indian art traditions, including Madhubani, Mysore, Tanjore, and Warli. Known for its decorative and narrative compositions, it employs vibrant colors. Notable artists include Jivya Soma Mashe, Jamini Roy, and Bhuri Bai.

Title: Silhouette
Description: Silhouette art style is a form of graphical art that uses contrasting lighting conditions to create simple compositions in black and white. It's seen in pop art and minimalism, rendering a mysterious mood. Notable artists include Kara Walker, August Edouarts, and William Bache.

Title: Identity
Description: The Identity art style is a reflection of personal exploration in art, often seen in self-portraiture, conceptual art, and feminist art. It uses narrative compositions to depict mood and identity and frequently includes mixed media. Notable artists in this style include Frida Kahlo, Tracey Emin, and Yoko Ono.

Title: Book Covers
Description: Book Covers art style is an amalgamation of graphic design, illustration, and typography. The primary medium is graphic design, which is used on printed surfaces. The color scheme varies based on the theme and genre of the book. Important elements include the overall composition that draws attention and that successfully conveys the book's theme.

Title: Botanical Photography
Description: Botanical Photography art style is associated with close-up, macro, and nature photography. It typically employs the medium of photography in natural environments, primarily outdoors. It uses natural light and the color scheme is often composed of natural colors, emphasizing the tranquility of the natural world. The composition mainly focuses on the details of plants.

Title: Abstract Painting
Description: The Abstract Painting art style is linked to movements such as abstract expressionism, cubism, and surrealism. The primary medium is painting, often with a variable color scheme. The mood can greatly vary depending on the work and artist. The composition is generally non-representational or non-objective, allowing for more interpretation from the viewer.

Title: Brian Donnelly
Description: Brian Donnelly, also known as 'KAWS', creates art in a style primarily influenced by pop art and contemporary art. His medium of choice is painting, often with bold and vibrant colors. He is known for his unique composition which often involves altering and deconstructing popular characters from pop culture.

Title: Metaphysical Art
Description: Metaphysical art style is often associated with surrealism and symbolism. The typical medium is painting, often set in dreamlike or impossible spaces. The lighting conditions are generally unnatural, and the color scheme is desaturated. This art style exudes a mystery mood through the unusual juxtaposition of ordinary objects.

Title: Japanese Comic Art
Description: Japanese Comic Art is a broad term that covers different art styles involved in the creation of Japanese comics or manga. It has a distinct visual storytelling style and can vary greatly in mood, from light-hearted to somber. Drawn mostly in black and white, they are then often colored vibrantly, especially for cover and promotional content.

Title: Studio Ghibli Art
Description: Studio Ghibli Art is known for its unique style, a fusion of classic anime and folk art aesthetics. Hayao Miyazaki, one of Ghibli's main artists, creates immersive compositions with vivid color palettes, often set within fantasy environments. The art typically invokes a nostalgic mood, reflecting Japanese culture and history.

Title: Gutai
Description: Gutai, a Japanese post-war artistic movement, exercises varied media for its creations, often featuring action painting and performance art. The art style is experimental, characterized by a rebellious mood, and is frequently displayed in outdoor environments. Artists, like Jiro Yoshihara, were prominent figures of this movement.

Title: Children's Books
Description: Children's Books art style involves mostly illustration and cartoon styles. The mood is often joyful, with a narrative composition that corresponds with the story. Colors are usually bright and cheerful. Notable artists in this field include Eric Carle and Dr. Seuss.

Title: Metabolism
Description: Metabolism is a post-war Japanese architectural movement. The art style primarily involves modular and organic designs, and is characterized by a futuristic mood. The color scheme is often monochromatic, with the architecture set in urban environments. Kiyonori Kikutake and Kisho Kurokawa are notable architects from this style.

Title: Sculptural
Description: The sculptural art style is a form of visual art that operates in three dimensions. It includes the design and creation of three-dimensional forms, often featuring organic or abstract shapes. Notable artists in this style include Michelangelo and Donatello.

Title: Feminist
Description: The feminist art style is a form of cultural expression aligned with the feminist movement. It uses various mediums from protest art to video art with a mood of activism. Notable artists include Judy Chicago and Barbara Kruger.

Title: Visual
Description: The Visual art style embraces various types of art forms that are primarily visual in nature. It can range from realism to surrealism, typically using mediums like painting. Renowned artists of this style include Vincent van Gogh and Leonardo Da Vinci.

Title: Storyboarding
Description: The storyboarding art style is used in the planning stages of film, animation, and graphic narrative, usually presented in the form of a sequence of drawings. Esteemed artists include Walt Disney and Hayao Miyazaki.

Title: Arthouse
Description: The Arthouse style typically applies to independent, experimental films that are often artistic, intellectual, or unconventional. Artists associated with this style include Ingmar Bergman and Jean-Luc Godard.

Title: Child-friendly
Description: Child-friendly art style is dominated by vibrant colours, simplified shapes, and relatable themes to attract young audiences. It's commonly found in cartoons, animations, and illustrations, painting usually being the preferred medium.

Title: Japanese Gardening
Description: Japanese Gardening art style melds the principles of Zen and aesthetic beauty. Some of its types include Tea and Stroll Gardens. This style is characterized by a calm mood, with a natural and sometimes symbolic composition.

Title: Living Sculpture
Description: Living Sculpture art style is a blend of horticulture and sculpture, which involves creating living artworks using plants. Styles like Topiary, Eco-Art, and Land Art fall under this domain. It exhibits an organic composition with serene mood.

Title: Assemblage Art
Description: Assemblage Art style is an innovative form of visual art that incorporates various everyday objects into an integrated whole, resulting in abstract and provocative pieces. Major subsets include Collage, Constructionist, and Cubism.

Title: Merz
Description: Merz is an art style created by Kurt Schwitters that emerged from Dadaism. It expresses whimsical mood and mainly comprises of works in collage. The peculiar characteristic of Merz is it's largely asymmetrical compositions.

Title: Industrial Landscape
Description: The Industrial Landscape art style features cityscapes and the architectural elements of industrial societies. Artists typically use painting as their medium, featuring earthy colors to capture the grittiness of the environment. The composition often provides a distant view of smokestacks, factories, and bustling cities.

Title: Matchstick Men
Description: Matchstick Men art style, identified with LS Lowry, are characterized by stylized, simplistic human figures set within an urban landscape. Paintings often have a neutral color scheme and portray a melancholic mood, symbolizing the profound solitude within populous cities.

Title: Asian Art
Description: Asian Art style is a broad term encompassing varied art practices from East Asia, representing themes of nature and mythology. Artwork commonly involves painting, utilizing subdued colors to create a serene, peaceful atmosphere. Renowned artists include Hokusai and Qi Baishi.

Title: Craftsmanship
Description: Craftsmanship in art emphasizes the high quality of handcrafted objects, where detail, precision, and skill are paramount. Mediums are numerous, including metalwork, glass-making, and ceramics. Renowned craftsmen include Louis Comfort Tiffany and Peter Carl Fabergé.

Title: Sculptural Art
Description: Sculptural Art style encompasses the creation of three-dimensional artwork, often using materials like marble, clay, or bronze. Styles vary from the hyper-realism of Classical sculptures to the abstract forms of modernists. Renowned artists include Michelangelo, Auguste Rodin, and Henry Moore.

Title: Earthworks
Description: Earthworks, also known as Land Art, is a style of art that involves the arranging and orchestrating of the natural environment to create immersive, large-scale installations. The soil is often the principal medium, with the outdoor environment providing a platform for the works.

Title: Site-specific Art
Description: Site-specific art is a style of artistic expression that is intrinsically connected to its location. The artwork is designed and created to have a specific relationship with its environment, resulting in an immersive, often reflective, experience.

Title: Gemstone Art
Description: Gemstone art is a style that utilizes gemstones as the primary medium. It often boasts luxurious and intricate designs with geometric compositions. This art style can span across various forms, ranging from mosaics to jewelry.

Title: Jewelry Making
Description: Jewelry Making as an art style is an intricate and delicate process requiring the combination of various materials, primarily metals and gemstones. It is often associated with elegance and sophistication, featuring symmetrical designs.

Title: Gritty Realism
Description: Gritty Realism is an art style within realism that places emphasis on the raw, unvarnished, often gloomy aspects of life. It often uses a monochromatic color scheme and low key lighting to emulate a moody and detailed atmosphere.

Title: Social Documentary
Description: Social Documentary art is a genre of photography dedicated to shedding light on significant social issues and life circumstances. This art style contrasts with nature, aesthetic, and commercial photography. Primarily monochrome or color photography captured in natural or available light reflects the realistic mood of this style.

Title: Dogme 95
Description: Dogme 95 art style reflects a filmmaking movement that emphasizes story, acting, and theme over appearance and technical gimmicks. The artists promote the use of natural light, hand-held cameras, and a vow of 'chastity,' eliminating artificial techniques in production. Known for its minimalistic and unadorned composition, Dogme 95 produces films showcasing authentic moods and neutral color tones.

Title: Transgressive
Description: Transgressive art is a genre that seeks to disrupt conventional norms and sensibilities through provocations. Artists often use unconventional compositions and surreal imagery to stage social, political, or cultural subversions, generating a disturbing mood.

Title: Coffee Art
Description: Coffee Art refers to designs created in the foam topping of coffee drinks or using coffee as a medium. This art style combines consumption with aesthetic experience, creating inviting and aesthetic compositions primarily in shades of brown.

Title: Barista Art
Description: Barista Art, often associated with Latte Art, involves the design of patterns or pictures on the surface of coffee. This art style, rooted in culinary skills, is primarily composed of abstract or realistic sketches, crafted in inviting shades of brown and white.

Title: Espresso Art
Description: Espresso Art, or 'Latte Art', is a method of preparing coffee, where patterns are made in the foam topping of an espresso drink. The art styles of abstract, pop, minimal, and conceptual can all be seen in the intricate and whimsical patterns that baristas create. Generally, the colors used are limited to the shades of brown of the coffee and the white of the milk. Requiring a controlled hand and acute attention to detail, Espresso Art is a creative and calming form of culinary visual art predominantly created in cafe or kitchen environments under natural or ambient lighting.

Title: Colorful Art
Description: Colorful art style is vibrant and joyful, often used in styles such as Impressionism, Fauvism, and Abstract Expressionism. This style is noticeable for its multicolored compositions and is typically created through painting. Renowned artists like Pablo Picasso and Wassily Kandinsky have utilized this style in their work.

Title: Imaginary Worlds
Description: The Imaginary world art style often used in Surrealism, Fantasy, and Sci-fi genres, is dreamy and fantastic, set in fantasy landscapes, and typically realized through illustrations. Artists like Salvador Dali and Rene Magritte are renowned for using this style in their works.

Title: Natural Habitats
Description: The Natural habitat art style, commonly seen in Realism, Landscape Art, and Environmental Art, revolves around serene and realistic compositions typically found outdoors. This style is commonly created through painting. Artists like John James Audubon and Charles Darwin have made significant contributions to this style.

Title: Ambient Lighting
Description: Ambient lighting art style, predominantly used in Sfumato, Chiaroscuro, and Tenebrism, is characterized by its soft lighting that creates a mysterious mood. This style focuses on the accurate depiction of light and shadow in its compositions and is usually executed through painting. Artists such as Leonardo da Vinci and Caravaggio are known for their ambient lighting artworks.

Title: Canadian Modernism
Description: Canadian modernism art style is a provocative, stylized interpretation of urban and natural landscapes, usually rendered in neutral colors. It is seen in diverse art movements such as Abstract Expressionism, Realism, and Cubism done primarily through painting. Artists like Lawren Harris, Emily Carr, and Jean Paul Riopelle have substantially contributed to the Canadian modernism art style.

Title: Canadian Landscapes
Description: Canadian Landscapes art style is characterized by bold impressionistic depictions of the great outdoors. The art style captures the serenity and vast beauty of Canada's geographies using a range of bright and neutral colors. Artists like Tom Thomson and Lawren Harris are renowned for their Canadian Landscapes art work.

Title: Victorian Neoclassicism
Description: The Victorian Neoclassicism art style reflects the themes of Classicism and Romanticism prevalent in the Victorian era. The art style is often shown through sculptures or paintings that depict scenes from Victorian-era settings, often showcasing historical, mythological, and Biblical themes. Renowned artists of Victorian Neoclassicism include John Gibson and Thomas Hickey.

Title: Social Documentary Photography
Description: Social Documentary Photography is an art style that captures candid moments and stories from urban environments. It often provokes thought and empathy by depicting the daily struggles and realities of the subjects. Renowned artists of Social Documentary Photography include Jacob Riis and Dorothea Lange.

Title: Mono-ha
Description: The Mono-ha art style originated from Japan, known for its minimalist aesthetic. Artists in this style create works that focus on natural materials and their relation to space. Mono-ha artworks radiate a distinct calmness and simplicity. Lee Ufan and Kishio Suga are well-known artists of Mono-ha.

Title: Brick Art
Description: Brick Art is a contemporary art style that uses bricks, particularly LEGO blocks, to create sculptures. The style is known for its playful and often geometric compositions. Its color palette is typically varied and vibrant. Renowned Brick Art artists include Nathan Sawaya and Jan Vormann.

Title: Lego Mosaic
Description: Lego Mosaic art style is a unique form of artistic expression using Lego bricks. It is inspired by Pop Art and Minimalism, relying on colorful, vivid blocks to construct images. The sculptures can be abstract or resemble traditional paintings, organized in a geometric composition. Artists like Nathan Sawaya and Sean Kenney are known for this style.

Title: Ballet Russes
Description: Ballet Russes art style emerged in the early 20th century, influenced by Art Nouveau, Cubism, and Neoclassicism. It dominated theatre design with rich colors, dramatic moods, and narrative compositions. It showcased complex choreography and storylines, transforming the atmosphere of the theatre. Notable artists include Leon Bakst, Pablo Picasso, and Henri Matisse.

Title: Ligne Claire
Description: The Ligne Claire (clear line) art style is prominent in modern illustration characterized by simplified forms, primary colors, and a neutral mood. The lines are drawn with exacting precision, omitting the use of hatching to create a clean and comprehensive aesthetic. Artists such as Hergé, Joost Swarte, and Bob de Moor are associated with this style.

Title: Poster Art
Description: Poster art style has its roots in Art Nouveau, Art Deco, and Constructivism. It is often expressed through graphic design, displaying bold colors, persuasive moods, and hierarchical compositions. The style primarily aims to advertise or promote, combining text elements with visual imagery. Notable practitioners include Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Nikolai Ostrovsky, and Jules Chéret.

Title: Palette Knife Painting
Description: Palette Knife Painting art style is associated with Impressionism and Abstract Expressionism, where artists use a palette knife instead of a brush to apply paint. This leads to vibrant colors and a dynamic mood, with the layered, textured composition creating a robust visual impact. Artists like Leonid Afremov, Gerhard Richter, and Pino Daeni are known for this style.

Title: Sports Art
Description: Sports Art is a genre of art that captures sports and physical activities in various artistic styles, such as realism or abstract. This style often represents the dynamism and energy of various sports activities, with vibrant colors and natural lighting to portray the spirit of athleticism.

Title: Isidore Isou
Description: Isidore Isou was a Romanian-born French poet and visual artist, known for founding the Lettrism movement. His work combined literature and visual art, distorting texts to introduce a revolutionary vision in the world of art.

Title: Maurice Lemaître
Description: Maurice Lemaître was a French visual artist, known for being a key figure in the Lettrist movement initiated by Isidore Isou. He experimented largely with film, producing works that conveyed a revolutionary artistic perspective.

Title: Experimental Art
Description: Experimental Art refers to art pushing boundaries and questioning traditional beliefs with irregular compositions and a provocative mood. It includes a variety of media, including painting, sculpture, and mixed media.

Title: Johannes Gutenberg
Description: Johannes Gutenberg, an inventor and goldsmith, pioneered movable type printing in Europe. His invention had a profound impact and allowed for the mass distribution of literature, greatly influencing the art of typography.

Title: Typography Art
Description: Typography Art, a subset of graphic design, focuses on the way text can be transformed to convey a narrative. Typically making use of simple coloring, it aims to create visually pleasurable layouts where symmetry and balance play a key role.

Title: New Topographics
Description: New Topographics refers to a movement in American landscape photography that frames human-altered landscapes in a manner that might be termed 'objective'. Photographs capture outdoor environments under natural light with a melancholic mood and balanced composition achieving a deliberately mundane or prosaic tonality.

Title: Neon Noir
Description: Neon Noir, a cinematic and artistic style, is characterized by high contrast between light and dark, glowing colors, and a deeply mysterious, often urban environment. Characterised by a stark and moody aesthetic that reflects the ambiguity of its characters' moral journeys.

Title: Chinese Modernism
Description: Chinese Modernism represents a fusion of Western and Eastern painting styles, blending traditional ink wash painting with elements of Cubism and Surrealism. It generally portrays a revolutionary mood with vibrant colors and a figurative composition.

Title: Low Fidelity
Description: Low Fidelity (or lo-fi) is an artistic concept primarily found in music and film. It embraces imperfections in the recording process and an aesthetic of simplicity, often imbuing productions with a relaxed or intimate atmosphere.

Title: Corporate
Description: The Corporate art style is characterized by its formal and professional visual aesthetics. It employs abstract, minimalist and realist art styles, caters to a neutral color palette, and usually depicts office environments. The composition is typically symmetrical, reflecting the organization and order associated with corporate life.

Title: Lo-fi
Description: The Lo-fi art style embraces a retro, vintage aesthetic often prevalent in impressionist works. Utilizing a muted color scheme, it evokes a relaxed mood and often gives a feeling of nostalgia. The composition may come across as rugged or casually arranged, in line with the low-fidelity theme.

Title: Analog
Description: Analog art style pays homage to traditional art forms, utilizing classic techniques found in realism, impressionism, and cubism. Analog mediums such as painting involve detailed compositions and a serene mood. The color palette remains natural, stemming from the use of traditional art materials.

Title: Silhouette Animation
Description: The Silhouette Animation art style creates a striking visual impression through its use of contrasted compositions, monochrome palettes, and backlit lighting. Symbolic of the early days of film and theater, this style imparts a mood of mystery. Artists like Lotte Reiniger and Norman McLaren are known for their contribution to this form of animation.

Title: Shadow Animation
Description: Shadow Animation style is closely related to the Silhouette Animation style, playing on the aspects of light and contrast. Exuding a sense of mystery, the style maintains a monochrome palette, involves dim lighting and contrasted compositions. Prominent artists include Lotte Reiniger and Norman McLaren.

Title: Chicago School
Description: The Chicago School is an art style characterized by architectural innovation, particularly in the design of skyscrapers. It often features a grey color palette, with a focus on urban cityscapes. The compositions are notable for their use of steel and large glass windows, stylizing the skyline.

Title: Feline Art
Description: Feline Art is an art style that centers around cats and their depiction in various forms and styles, including realism and abstract. The compositions focus on the anatomy and the movement of cats. The mood, lighting, and color can vary greatly depending on the specific piece and artist.

Title: Dramatic Realism
Description: Dramatic Realism is an intense art style that uses high contrast lighting and vibrant colours to create dramatic poses and scenes. Although the environment can vary, the focus on realism is key. Artists like Caravaggio and Rembrandt are known for their work in this style.

Title: Low-polygon
Description: Low-polygon is an art style that emphasizes digital, stylized shapes and forms. It can feature a variety of lighting and color schemes. Though the environments may vary, the compositions are defined by a geometric, low-polygon aesthetic. Artist Tim Reynolds is recognized for his work in this style.

Title: Polygonal Art
Description: Polygonal Art is an art style that focuses on digital, geometric forms. Though the lighting, color, and situations may vary, the compositions emphasize a robust polygonal aesthetic. Artists like James Nolan Gandy have grown popularity in this innovative form.

Title: Architectural Vision
Description: Architectural Vision involves the art of envisioning, conceptualizing and defining architectural structures. The art form tends to be geometrically complex and is often set in an urban environment. The medium typically used is drawing and related artists include Diego M. Rodriguez and Carlos Lujan.

Title: Eco-architecture
Description: The Eco-architecture art style is a form of architectural design that prioritizes the creation of eco-friendly structures that sync harmoniously with nature. It usually involves a peaceful mood, with a focus on green color schemes, and is associated with artists like Diego M. Rodriguez and Carlos Lujan.

Title: Dynamic Composition With Exaggerated Action Poses
Description: Dynamic Composition With Exaggerated Action Poses is an art style in which artists utilize dramatic lighting and active, vibrant poses, often seen in medium like anime, manga, and comics. It embodies a dynamic composition with artists like Diego M. Rodriguez and Carlos Lujan using this style in their artworks.

Title: Kagami Yoshimizu
Description: Kagami Yoshimizu is a well-known manga artist, most closely associated with the art styles of manga and anime. His work predominantly uses digital art as a medium, and he is often compared to other artists like Ken Akamatsu or Hayao Miyazaki.

Title: Modernist Architecture
Description: Modernist Architecture primarily includes styles such as International Style, Brutalism, and Bauhaus. The medium is architecture, set mainly in urban environments. Artists like Le Corbusier and Frank Lloyd Wright championed this movement, focusing heavily on functional composition.

Title: Thomas Wilfred
Description: Thomas Wilfred was an artist celebrated for his unique styles, including Lumia, Kinetic Art, and Light art. His medium of choice was light sculpture, using a manipulated light source to create vibrant colors. Similar artists include James Turrell and Dan Flavin.

Title: Monkey Punch
Description: Monkey Punch is praised for his distinct manga and anime art styles, primarily using ink as the medium. His drawing style and storytelling techniques align him with other influential manga artists like Go Nagai and Osamu Tezuka.

Title: Adventure Art
Description: Adventure Art is an exhilarating style that often incorporates elements of Fantasy Art, Realism, and Surrealism. The medium usually employed is illustration, with a general mood of excitement. Artists associated with this style include Frank Frazetta and J.C. Leyendecker.

Title: Eva Hesse
Description: Eva Hesse was a notable artist associated with post-minimalism and abstract expressionism. Her work often comprised of sculptures involving repeated forms, organic shapes with a typically monochromatic color scheme. Artists like Robert Morris, Sol LeWitt, and Richard Serra were also integral parts of the same art movement.

Title: Post-minimalism
Description: Post-minimalism is an art style that broadended the minimalist trend, including conceptual art and performance art forms, allowing for more complex structures even if they were to some extent geometrically simple. It often is characterized by sculptures with an abstract mood and a monochromatic color scheme. Notable artists include Eva Hesse, Bruce Nauman, and Richard Serra.

Title: Cubofuturism
Description: Cubofuturism is an art style that emerged as a blend of Futurism and Cubism. It is associated with paintings composed of geometric shapes and forms, often with contrasting lighting and a polychromatic color scheme. Notable artists in this category are Kazimir Malevich, Natalia Goncharova, and Lyubov Popova.

Title: Tessellation
Description: Tessellation is a characteristic visual style employed in creating complex geometric patterns that fit together without gaps or overlaps in a drawing. The color scheme is varied. Associated artists include M.C. Escher, Bridget Riley, and Vasarely.

Title: Indian Modern Art
Description: Indian Modern Art combines traditional Indian art with European avant-garde movements. The dominant medium is painting which employed vibrant colors with mixed composition. Key movements include the Bengal School, Progressive Artists' Group, and Contextual Modernism. Notable artists are Maqbool Fida Husain, Amrita Sher-Gil, and Rabindranath Tagore.

Title: Material Art
Description: Material Art is a style that leans towards the creative use of physical materials in art, often non-traditional. It includes assemblage of various elements which may be found or acquired, emphasizing the artist's viewpoint about utilising unconventional resources in art.

Title: Magical Girl
Description: The Magical Girl style is a sub-genre of the Japanese mediums of manga and anime. It features girls with magical abilities destined to save the world. It is characterized by vibrant colors, dynamic visuals, and an uplifting mood.

Title: Editorial Design
Description: Editorial Design refers to an art style that focuses on the layout and visual aesthetics of publications, including magazines, newspapers and books. It combines typography, graphics, and other visual elements to provide the reader with a seamless experience.

Title: Card Art
Description: Card Art refers to designs used on collectible cards, postcards, and greeting cards. It employs a centered composition with pictorial illustrations or graphic designs often set against a fantasy background. It is meant to visually communicate the card's purpose or theme.

Title: African Traditional
Description: African Traditional Art includes statues, masks, textiles, and ceramics which reflect the diverse cultures and traditions of Africa. It uses symbols for communication with earth tones dominating the color scheme. Sculpture, especially wood carving, is one of the most prominent mediums.

Title: Buddhist
Description: Buddhist art primarily consists of depictions of Buddha and the stories from his lives. Art styles vary by region, Gandhara, Amaravati, and Tibetan being pivotal. The medium often used is sculpture with a serene mood and symmetrical compositions. The color scheme is often monochrome.

Title: Tibetan
Description: Tibetan art is a fusion of Indian, Nepalese, Chinese styles harmonizing on religious themes. Notable art styles are Thangka painting and Buddhist art. It is vibrant with a divine mood and intricate composition, typically created using painting as a medium.

Title: Alighiero E Boetti
Description: Alighiero E Boetti was an Italian conceptual artist known for works incorporating embroidery with philosophical themes. Defining styles include Arte Povera and Conceptual Art, both using geometric compositions.

Title: Joan Blaeu
Description: Joan Blaeu was a Dutch cartographer known for creating comprehensive atlases. His art style is notably detailed Cartography, with a predominance of monochrome colors. His medium was typically printmaking.

Title: Fantasy Cartography
Description: Fantasy Cartography is the art of creating maps for imaginary worlds often associated with fantasy literature. Notable styles include Imaginary Landscapes and High Fantasy. The medium generally used is painting, with an imaginary composition.

Title: Topographic Maps
Description: Topographic Maps art displays detailed, graphic representation of elements in the landscape like hills, valleys, plains and other geographical features, creating a three-dimensional effect on a flat surface. The neutral color palette often features browns, greens, and blues. This art style is associated with artists such as Hikmet Barutcugil.

Title: Hikmet Barutcugil
Description: Known for his contributions to Turkish marbling art, also known as Ebru, Hikmet Barutcugil's art style reflects intricacies, depth, and the tranquil, abstract swirls of color created with water-based paints. He is a contemporary of artists like Joseph Addison.

Title: Joseph Addison
Description: Joseph Addison, known more widely as a writer than an artist, belonged to the 18th-century art period. His contemporaries in art included artists like Charles Woolnough.

Title: Charles Woolnough
Description: Charles Woolnough, known for his work in the 19th century, had an indistinct art style coinciding with the Romanticism era. He shared his time with writers and artists like Joseph Addison.

Title: Carrageenan Marbling
Description: Carrageenan Marbling art style is a method of aqueous surface design where carrageenan and water-based paints are used to create flowy, multi-colored patterns on various surfaces. The expressive moods presented in this style are associated with artists like Hikmet Barutcugil.

Title: Ollie Johnston
Description: Ollie Johnston is regarded for his work in Disney Character Animation and was known for his vibrant and joyful style. He created balanced compositions and used bright lighting to enhance the overall effect. He worked closely with artists like Walt Disney and Frank Thomas.

Title: Frank Thomas
Description: Frank Thomas was an animator known for the Disney Character Animation style. He utilized vibrant colors and bright lighting to create joyful cartoons. His work often involved balanced composition, and he collaborated with artists like Walt Disney and Ollie Johnston.

Title: Nude Photography
Description: Nude Photography is a visual art form that often uses photography as its medium. The style, prevalent in contemporary works, places models in a studio environment. Lighting is often natural, color scheme is usually monochromatic and the mood can be intense. Works are often asymmetrical. Artists like Helmut Newton and Robert Mapplethorpe are known for such art.

Title: Jim Lee
Description: Jim Lee is renowned for his style in Superhero Comics. His art often features diverse colors, dramatic lighting, and immersive environments that bring superhero stories to life. His action-packed compositions imbue scenes with a heroic mood. Artists like Stan Lee and Jack Kirby have influenced his work.

Title: Book Cover Art
Description: Book Cover Art is a style focusing on Graphic Design, often reflecting the narrative in symbolic compositions. The environment is often an imaginary world, with vibrant colors and varying lighting conditions. Artists like Chip Kidd and Peter Mendelsund have made significant contributions to this field.

Title: Readymade
Description: Readymade art involves the use of commonplace objects — a technique that challenges conventional standards of art. A sculpture medium is often used, and compositions involve everyday objects. Artists like Marcel Duchamp, Pablo Picasso, and Andy Warhol have famously utilized this style.

Title: Decorative
Description: Decorative art emphasizes beauty and aesthetics over functionality, with a strong focus on intricate patterns in its composition. It is commonly seen in the painting medium. Renowned artists of this style include Gustav Klimt, William Morris, and Erté.

Title: Big Eyes
Description: Big Eyes art is characterized by a distinct style where subjects, especially people, are depicted with unusually large, expressive eyes. Often seen in painting, this style has a melancholy mood with compositions featuring exaggerated figures. Artists Margaret Keane and Tim Burton are known for this style.

Title: Australian Art
Description: Australian art encompasses styles and movements that depict the country's unique landscapes, its rich Aboriginal heritage, and contemporary subjects. The environment often involves the Australian outback or cityscapes, with compositions focusing on nature and local culture. Notable Australian artists include Tom Roberts, Albert Namatjira, and Sidney Nolan.

Title: Abstraction
Description: Abstraction refers to art that does not attempt to represent an accurate depiction of visual reality. It is typically seen in the medium of painting, with a goal to evoke emotions. Its compositions are non-representational, utilizing abstract forms and shapes. Artists like Wassily Kandinsky, Pablo Picasso, and Kazimir Malevich are known for their contributions to abstraction.

Title: Body Awareness
Description: Body Awareness in art refers to the artistic style where the physical human body is the central focus. The Art has an expressive mood, with organic composition and a colourful palette. Famous artists like Michelangelo, Lucian Freud, and Egon Schiele have utilized this style with natural lighting to magnify physical features and highlight natural forms.

Title: Self-portrait
Description: Self-Portrait art is a self-reflective style where artists depict themselves as the subject. The works typically feature a centered composition set in a studio with manipulated studio lighting. The color schemes vary broadly. It has been prominent in various art movements, such as portraiture and impressionism, with renowned artists like Frida Kahlo, Rembrandt, and Vincent van Gogh presenting vivid self-portraits.

Title: Neo-classicism
Description: Neo-classicism art style pays homage to the classical antiquity, with its noble mood, earthy colors, symmetrical compositions, and realistic lighting. It's often manifested through paintings of historical and heroic figures composed in grand, symmetrical arrangements. Prominent neo-classical artists include Jacques-Louis David, and Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres.

Title: Cinematic Style
Description: Cinematic Style in art emulates the visual aesthetics of cinema, often involving digital mediums. It provides a narrative composition, set in varying environments, using dramatic lighting and high-contrast colors to create suspenseful moods. Artists like Gregory Crewdson, Cindy Sherman, and Philip-Lorca diCorcia are among those who have fruitfully employed the cinematic style.

Title: Unknown Artists
Description: Art from unknown artists often falls under the Outsider Art or Naive Art styles. It is characterized by its personal nature, untrained composition, and typically features bold colors. The medium is varied, largely based on what was available to the artist. Artist such as Henry Darger, Bill Traylor, and Maude Lewis were relatively unknown during their lifetime but gained posthumous recognition.

Title: Cowboy Art
Description: Cowboy art style is a genre closely related to Western Art and American Frontier Art, typically rendered in painting mediums. The art often depicts rural landscapes, natural sunlight lighting, and presents an adventurous mood. The composition is dynamic, portraying cowboys' adventurous lifestyle. Artists such as Charles Marion Russell and Frederic Remington are known for their work in this art style.

Title: Abstract Sculpture
Description: Characterized by non-representational forms, Abstract sculpture art style encompasses art movements like Cubism and Minimalism. The medium is predominantly sculpture, with a varied color scheme and a subjective mood evoked based on viewer perception. Prominent artists in this genre include Henry Moore, Alberto Giacometti, and Barbara Hepworth.

Title: Minimalist Sculpture
Description: Minimalist sculpture art style is a subset of Abstract Art, mainly showcased in the sculpture medium. The art features simplified, monochromatic compositions that evoke a serene mood. Artists like Donald Judd, Agnes Martin, and Dan Flavin are well-known for their minimalist sculptures.

Title: Wood Sculpture
Description: Wood sculpture art style is a practice mainly related to carving and assemblage art styles. The art primarily uses wood carving as its medium and showcases compositions in three-dimensional forms. The mood around these sculptures is generally rustic. Wharton Esherick, Louise Nevelson, and David Nash are notable artists in this art genre.

Title: Macro Photography
Description: Macro photography art style involves capturing extreme close-ups, typically of very small subjects. This style often relates to nature and still life photography. The works can utilize both natural and artificial lighting and focus on bringing out detailed moods. Notable macro photographers include Robert Mapplethorpe, Edward Weston, and Imogen Cunningham.

Title: Celebrity Photography
Description: Celebrity Photography focuses on capturing images of celebrities. The art style involves different photography techniques like Portrait, Fashion and Candid. The medium is Photography with usage of Studio Lighting. The color scheme is usually in full color displaying a prestigious mood with a centered composition.

Title: Close-up Photography
Description: Close-up Photography is an intense art style that focuses on small details to make them the main subject of the picture. It includes Macro, Micro, and Portrait photography styles. The composition tends to fill the frame, creating high detail and intricate visuals.

Title: Surreal Photography
Description: Surreal Photography uses unusual images and scenarios to create a dreamlike and sometimes disturbing aesthetic. The art style includes Conceptual, Abstract, and Fine Art photography. The composition is often unconventional, creating a sense of the uncanny and extraordinary.

Title: Neo-Victorian
Description: Neo-Victorian is an aesthetic movement emulating the Victorian era's romanticism. Included are styles like Gothic Revival, Steampunk, and Historical Revival. The medium is predominantly painting depicting urban setups with a detailed composition. Colors tend to compliment the mood of romance, often using sepia tones.

Title: Digital Print
Description: Digital Print is a modern art form, depicting images produced from digital sources, using styles like Digital Art, Graphic Design, and Computer Art. The medium is Digital Media, and compositions are often geometric, creating a contemporary, modern mood.

Title: Textile Design
Description: Textile Design Art Style focuses on the design of fabrics. It involves the use of techniques like weaving, printmaking, and silk-screen printing. The composition is usually patterned. Notable artists in this field include Anni Albers and Lucienne Day.

Title: BioWare
Description: BioWare is renowned for its distinctive art style in the gaming industry. Using digital medium, they create immersive virtual reality environments with a touch of fantasy. Key elements involve concept art, character design, and 3D modeling. Notable artists include Drew Karpyshyn and Matt Rhodes.

Title: Sculpture Art
Description: Sculpture Art Style focuses on three-dimensional artworks typically executed in mediums like stone, metal, or wood. It can be under various styles such as realism, kinetic sculpture, or installation art. It often employs natural lighting. Renowned sculptors include Michelangelo and Louise Bourgeois.

Title: Collage Art
Description: Collage Art Style is a technique of composing an artwork by pasting diverse materials such as photos, paper, or fabric onto a surface. It can be associated with art styles like Dadaism and Surrealism. The color approach is often multicolor, and the composition is usually asymmetric. Significant artists in this domain include Kurt Schwitters and Romare Bearden.

Title: Architectural Art
Description: Architectural Art Style pertains to the aesthetic aspect of buildings and structures. It typically involves the use of concrete or steel, structural lighting, and geometric composition. Various styles include Gothic, Renaissance, and Modern architecture. Noteworthy artists include Le Corbusier and Zaha Hadid.

Title: Illustration Art
Description: Illustration art style is a flexible and diverse style which aims at telling a story or portraying a concept in a visually interesting way. It's often seen in books, magazines, advertisements and various forms of media. The subject matter, color scheme, and lighting conditions all vary greatly, as do the materials used. Notable artists of this style include Norman Rockwell and Quentin Blake.

Title: Nabis Art
Description: Nabis art style is a French Post-Impressionist avant-garde movement that sought to express the spiritual or symbolic essence of subjects, often focusing on intimate domestic themes. It is characterized by its simplification of form, innovative use of color, and emphasis on personal symbolism. Notable artists include Pierre Bonnard and Édouard Vuillard.

Title: Urban Landscape Painting
Description: Urban landscape painting is an art style that focuses on representing city scenes. It is associated with both realism and Impressionism movements, depicting every day life with a variety of color schemes and lighting conditions depending on the scene and time of day. Renowned artists include Edward Hopper and Camille Pissarro.

Title: Automatism
Description: Automatism is a method of creating art in which the artist suppresses conscious control over the process, allowing the unconscious mind to have great sway. Originated by the Surrealists, it's linked with Abstract Expressionism and Dada. The style tends to be abstract, with varied color schemes and lighting. Famous Automatism artists include Joan Miró and Jackson Pollock.

Title: American Renaissance
Description: The American Renaissance was a period of American architecture and the arts from 1876 to 1917, characterized by renewed national self-confidence and a feeling that the nation was bringing civilization and elegance to the American cities. The style borrowed heavily from European motifs, specifically neoclassical and Romanesque, and focused on balance and symmetry. Notable figures include Daniel Chester French and Richard Morris Hunt.

Title: Mesoamerican Architecture
Description: Mesoamerican Architecture art style is predominantly seen in ancient structures designed by Mesoamerican civilizations such as the Maya, Aztec, and Zapotec. The structures usually exhibit grand scale and symmetry, often built with stone, and are typically set in sacred spaces. Their color scheme often aligns with earthy tones, reflecting a majestic mood.

Title: Platformer
Description: The Platformer game art style encompasses a wide variety of visual styles, including pixel art, cartoon, abstract, and caricature. Typically characterized by dynamic and colorful visuals, these games set in a virtual environment often induce an adventurous mood. The composition tends to range from 2D to 3D, with notable developers being Nintendo, Sega, and Ubisoft.

Title: Archigram
Description: The Archigram architectural style, pioneered by artists such as Peter Cook, Dennis Crompton, and Ron Herron, features futuristic, modular, high-tech designs. Generally depicted through monochrome sketches, the style is set within an urban environment. It has a distinctly innovative mood, allowing for non-traditional compositions.

Title: Lebbeus Woods
Description: Lebbeus Woods, an American architect, is known for his experimental and futuristic art style. He typically uses design drawings in monochrome colors to depict an urban environment. The mood of his works is often provocative, with compositions that are usually asymmetrical.

Title: Kobayashi Kiyochika
Description: Kobayashi Kiyochika, a Japanese painter, paints in a style that blends both Ukiyo-e and Nihonga. His works, typically in the medium of woodblock prints, depict both rural and urban environments. The color palette is often vibrant, and the mood ranges from nostalgic to melancholic. His compositions commonly highlight naturalistic themes.

Title: Stealth Action
Description: Stealth Action art style is associated with video game design and conceptual art. It is often seen in urban settings with high contrast lighting and a dark color scheme to create suspense. The composition revolves strongly around dynamic action scenes. An artist relevant in this field is Hideo Kojima.

Title: Heavy Metal
Description: Heavy Metal art style is largely adopted in illustrations, album covers, and poster arts associated with the music genre. It often illustrates abstract environments with dramatic lighting, vibrant colors and intense mood. Artists like Derek Riggs and Ken Kelly are known for this style.

Title: Luis Méndez Rodríguez
Description: Luis Méndez Rodríguez is a Spanish Surrealist painter known for his dreamlike scenarios portrayed through soft lighting, a muted color palette, and a mystical mood. His compositions often incorporate surrealistic elements.

Title: Luis Paret Y Alcázar
Description: Luis Paret Y Alcázar's art is characteristic of the Spanish Rococo style, often displaying elite interiors in his paintings. His style is known for its naturalistic lighting, bright colors, and elegant mood. The composition of his works is often ornate.

Title: Yozo Hamaguchi
Description: Yozo Hamaguchi is a renowned artist of modern printmaking, specifically mezzotint. His work, often comprised of still life, employs the chiaroscuro technique on a monochrome palette to create tranquil moods and elegant simplicity.

Title: Blockbuster
Description: Blockbuster art style is marked by high production quality and commercial appeal. This style often uses radiant colors and dynamic composition to portray action-packed scenes. This category prominently shines in the realm of cinematic art, typically set in urban environments or science fiction landscapes. Directors like Steven Spielberg, George Lucas, and James Cameron are associated with this style.

Title: Explosions
Description: Explosions art style is a physical representation of energy and change. It utilizes vibrant colors and chaotic compositions to create thrilling visual spectacles. This style is influenced by Abstract Expressionism and Pop Art, with prominent artists like Roy Lichtenstein and Jackson Pollock exploring this concept in their works.

Title: Underground Comics
Description: Underground Comics art style is marked by controversial subject matter and a rebellious stance against mainstream comics. It uses sequential compositions and urban themes in an illustrative medium. Renowned artists like Robert Crumb, Gilbert Shelton, and Spain Rodriguez are associated with the Underground Comics art style.

Title: Time-lapse Photography
Description: Time-lapse Photography art style involves capturing sequential images to depict the passing of time. Natural lighting is a crucial aspect, often highlighting changing environments. It's generally associated with Photorealism and Land Art. Artists known for this include Rob Whitworth, Michael Shainblum, and Ron Fricke.

Title: Digital Surrealism
Description: Digital Surrealism art style merges traditional surrealist motifs with modern digital art techniques. It's realized through digital painting, focusing on unreal moods and imaginative compositions set in fictitious environments. Renowned surrealists like Andrew Jones, Alyssa Monks, and even Salvador Dali, who inspired this style, are often associated with Digital Surrealism.

Title: Film Directing
Description: Film Directing art style is characterized by the personal influence and artistic control a director has on a movie. The style varies greatly depending on the director's distinct vision and method of storytelling.

Title: High Renaissance
Description: High Renaissance art style, prevalent from about 1490 to 1527, is known for its balance and harmony. The style is characterized by a grandeur of vision and use of innovative techniques to produce a naturalistic effect in works.

Title: Arte Povera
Description: Arte Povera art style emerged in the late 1960s as an Italian radical art movement against the conventions of government and industry. Artists in the movement used untraditional materials such as organic and waste materials, and incorporated elements of nature.

Title: Realistic Art
Description: Realistic Art art style focuses on the lifelike depiction of the real world or reality. Artists use detailed techniques to depict subjects as they appear in real life, including still life, landscapes, and portraits.

Title: Adventure Comics
Description: Adventure Comics art style is a vibrant and dynamic form often featuring heroic figures in an oft-distant or fictional environment. The art consistently captures a sense of excitement, movement, and drama, heavily relying on high contrast lighting and perspective.

Title: Decollage
Description: Decollage, part of the Nouveau Realisme movement, is an art style where the artist creates an artwork by tearing or cutting away pieces of an original image, often posters or other multimedia. This results in a fragmented, 'reverse-collage' visual effect.

Title: Traditional Chinese Fashion
Description: Traditional Chinese Fashion is an art style that highlights China's rich sartorial history. From Hanfu, Qipao to Tangzhuang, each design imbues deep cultural symbolism with unique color palettes and composition.

Title: R&B
Description: R&B, short for Rhythm and Blues, is an art style and music genre that combines jazz, gospel, and blues influences. Characterized by its emotive and passionate moods, it plays an instrumental role in the evolution of rock and roll and contemporary music.

Title: Soul
Description: Soul is an art style and music genre that emerged from the African American community in the United States in the late 1950s and early 1960s. Combining elements of African American gospel music, R&B and jazz, soul music is known for its emotional and heartfelt qualities.

Title: British Fashion
Description: British Fashion is an art style that epitomizes the eccentric and avant-garde spirit of British culture. From Mod, Punk to the refined Savile Row style, it consistently pushes boundaries, creating iconic and influential fashion movements throughout history.

Title: DIY
Description: DIY Art Style is a concept that embraces creativity, individuality and personal expression. Often seen in the realm of Collage, Installation Art, Assemblage and Mixed Media. Artists often utilize a range of materials, and the environment is usually household or residential with an asymmetrical composition.

Title: Jean Giraud (Moebius)
Description: Jean Giraud, also known as Moebius, is known for his surreal and vivid comic art style. His work is characterized by dynamic composition, dramatic lighting, and vivid colors, set in the realms of fantasy and science fiction. His art style has influenced the realms of fantasy art, conceptual art, and surrealism.

Title: Point-and-click
Description: The Point-and-click art style is often seen in the gaming world, particularly in genres such as Pixel Art, Illustrative Art and Comic Art. This digital medium offers varied lighting and colors, creating engaging mood and interactive composition within game environments.

Title: Vibrant Colors
Description: The Vibrant Colors art style is characterized by the use of bright, intense colors, often associated with Pop Art, Fauvism, Abstract Expressionism, Expressionism, and Color Field. It generally creates an energetic mood, in varied compositions and environments.

Title: Tile or Glass Pieces
Description: The Tile or Glass Pieces art style is predominantly seen in Mosaics, Stained Glass, Inlay, Ceramic Art, and Glass Art. The art is usually geometric and decorative in nature, with varied natural lighting and color, often used to enhance architectural structures.

Title: Varied Colors
Description: The varied colors art style heavily features a vibrant and diverse spectrum of colors. Artists like Van Gogh and Picasso utilized this style to evoke moods and depict different perceptions of reality. The art can be created in various art styles including Impressionism and Abstractionism.

Title: Small Pieces Arranged to Form a Larger Image or Pattern
Description: The Mosaic art style involves arranging small pieces of materials to form a larger image or pattern. This technique, used by artists like Gino Severini, often results in abstract or figurative mosaics. The materials can vary, with tile being common and typically displayed in both indoor and outdoor environments.

Title: Bill Gold
Description: Bill Gold was a renowned graphic designer known for his cinematic poster art style. Often dramatic in mood, his composition typically featured photo montage elements which he used to convey the essence of the film. His influence is visible in works by artists like Bob Peak and Drew Struzan.

Title: Annie Atkins
Description: Annie Atkins is a graphic designer noted for her detailed and nostalgic art. Working mainly in the digital medium, her style incorporates typography and layout principles. Other artists who share similar styles include Paula Scher and Milton Glaser.

Title: Olly Moss
Description: Olly Moss is a graphic designer well known for his captivating use of silhouette and negative space. His whimsical poster art and graphic design work often leaves a lasting impression. His style shares similarities with artists such as Saul Bass and Eiko Ishioka.

Title: Illustrative
Description: Illustrative art style is a visually appealing method aimed to convey information, story or concepts. It typically uses drawings as a medium and can be applied to a variety of art styles such as graphic, comic, and animation. The composition is usually focused on the clarity of the subject. The mood, lighting, and color are diverse and dependent on the narrative or concept being delivered.

Title: Typographic
Description: Typographic art style is an expressive form that relies heavily on the use of typeface and fonts, and their arrangement. It's a key component within graphic art styles such as minimalist, post-modern, and pop art. The pieces in this art style are often bold and strong in color, with a composition focused on typography.

Title: Felipe Vigarny
Description: Felipe Vigarny was a renowned sculptor known for his realism and Renaissance-influenced art style. Working in primarily monochromatic, natural tones, his sculptures exude a serene mood. Vigarny emphasized balance and symmetry in his compositions. He is commonly associated with artists such as Gil De Hontañón and Pedro De Gumiel.

Title: Pedro De Gumiel
Description: Pedro De Gumiel, a known architect, contributed to the Gothic and Renaissance architectural styles. His work, marked by an air of grandeur, often features natural light, the use of aged stone color, and a composition laying emphasis on symmetry and proportions. Gumiel shares a stylistic similarity with artists like Felipe Vigarny and Gil De Hontañón.
