Title: Gil De Hontañón
Description: Gil De Hontañón, a celebrated architect, was known for his contributions to the Gothic and Renaissance architectural movements. His style is characterized by natural light, aged stone color, and symmetry which creates a sense of majesty and harmony. His work garnered comparison to artists like Felipe Vigarny and Pedro De Gumiel.

Title: Diego De Siloe
Description: Diego De Siloe was a Spanish Renaissance sculptor and architect. His style was a blend of Gothic structure with Renaissance details and Baroque elements, often used to evoke religious moods and themes.

Title: Andrés De Vandelvira
Description: Andrés De Vandelvira was an influential Renaissance architect. His work is characterized by ornamented and articulate designs, with the dominant use of the Mannerist style.

Title: Moorish
Description: Moorish art refers to the Islamic art of the Moors, distinguished by its intricate geometric patterns, polychromatic color schemes and its medium is majorly architectural. It drew heavily from the Arabesque style.

Title: Tudor
Description: The Tudor style is distinctive English Renaissance art and architecture prominent during the Tudor period. The artwork displays darker, earth-toned colors typical of the Medieval palette, with a focus on natural lighting and rural environments.

Title: Ustad Ahmad Lahauri
Description: Ustad Ahmad Lahauri was a Persian architect who is often attributed as the principal designer of the Taj Mahal, a masterpiece of symmetrical Mughal architecture. His work is characterized by grand scale, white color, and Islamic aesthetics.

Title: Mirak Mirza Ghiyas
Description: Mirak Mirza Ghiyas was a famous Persian architect best known for defining the distinct Mughal architecture style. His works incorporated both Persian and Indian architectural elements, resulting in the development of unique designs.

Title: Ustad Hamid
Description: Ustad Hamid, a Mughal court artist, is best known for his contributions to Mughal miniature art. His work is characterized by its detail and use of bright, vivacious colors, demonstrating the opulence and grandeur of the Mughal period.

Title: Muhammad Hanif
Description: Muhammad Hanif is a contemporary artist well-known for his sculptural works. His pieces often lean towards the abstract, leaving the interpretation to the viewer.

Title: Asad Khan
Description: Asad Khan is a prominent modern art painter best known for his expressive and figurative works. His paintings often depict the human condition while maintaining a visually intriguing balance of shape and color.

Title: Indo-Islamic
Description: Indo-Islamic is an interesting fusion of Islamic and Indian art styles, flourishing in regions with an Islamic influence. It primarily appears in architecture and paintings, featuring bright, bold colors, symbolic lighting, and serene implications. The style is characterized by its geometric patterns which convey a sense of serenity.

Title: Persian
Description: Persian art style is a part of the larger Islamic art culture, but with a distinct style of its own. Notable for its detailed miniature paintings, vibrant use of color, and the intricacy of geometric patterns. Renowned artists include Reza Abbasi and Hossein Behzad.

Title: Timurid
Description: The signature Timurid art style is noticeable in its manuscript illuminations, characterized by a rich color palette and detailed patterns. It's an important part of Islamic and Persian art with a key focus on miniature painting. Significant artists include Behzad, Mirak, and Sultan Mohammed.

Title: Rajput
Description: The Rajput art style, significant in the Indian art tradition, is celebrated for its vivid use of color and figurative composition. The style often depicts courtly scenes in miniature painting form, drawing influence from Mughal art. Notable artists include Nihal Chand, Bhawanidas, and Sahibdin.

Title: Bishnupur
Description: The Bishnupur art style is a unique Indian art form characterised by the use of terracotta materials, specifically visible in architecture and sculptures. The style is primarily crafted by local artisans.

Title: Dhaka Muslin
Description: The Dhaka Muslin art style is a part of the broader textile art scene. Known for its eponymous fabric, this style is primarily associated with the traditional weaving techniques of Bengali weavers.

Title: Pashmina Shawls
Description: Pashmina Shawls art style is primarily associated with handmade textile art, demonstrating a high degree of craftsmanship. Colors in these works are assorted, often based on natural dyes. Renowned artists in this field include Firdous Jan, Almas Boby, and Razia Begum.

Title: Zardozi Embroidery
Description: Zardozi Embroidery art style is closely associated with intricate textile and embroidery works, characterized by extremely detailed compositions. The art is typically showcased by artists like Seema Kapoor, Rekha Salim, and Nisha Patel.

Title: Zari
Description: The Zari art style is indicative of the lavish textile artwork which places emphasis on using metallic threads to create a detailed composition. Artists like Fatima Akhtar, Aziza Khan, and Shama Parveen contribute to this style.

Title: Mughal
Description: Mughal art style is linked to the royal courts of the Mughal empire, characterized by comprehensive compositions that include miniature painting, architectural design, and illuminated manuscripts. The art usually has soft lighting representation with vibrant colors, expressing a royal feeling. Renowned artists associated with this style include Abu'l Hasan, Govardhan, and Bishandas.

Title: Royal
Description: Royal art style primarily encapsulates majestic portraits of royals, sculptures, and landscapes often set in palatial environments. The compositions are refined and elegant, resonating with the artists Anthony van Dyck, Peter Paul Rubens, and Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres.

Title: Bertillon
Description: Bertillon art style is characterized by the precise, systematic style of photography developed by Alphonse Bertillon. He used this method for criminal identification, emphasizing sequential front and profile mugshots. It falls under portraiture and realism, focusing on truthful representations.

Title: Mugshots.com
Description: Mugshots.com art style leans on documentary photography and reality art. These stored frontal and profile mugshots are captured for identification processes, composed in single-frame formats. The imagery provides a raw and truthful capture of reality.

Title: Profile, Frontal
Description: Profile, Frontal art style is a portraiture method frequently found in Photorealism. Traditionally represented in painting, it consists of the person's face in both frontal and profile views. The composition is pictorial, often adhering to classical standards set by Old Master artists such as Da Vinci or Van Eyck.

Title: Frank Oz
Description: Frank Oz's art style is characterized by his direction in film making and his puppetry talent. He worked in collaboration with many realms of art and is closely linked to artists like Jim Henson, known for their work in creative direction and performance art.

Title: Dave Goelz
Description: Dave Goelz is an artist in the domain of puppetry. His artistic contribution lies within the design, manipulation, and creation of puppet characters. His work is specifically recognized within the field of puppetry.

Title: Jerry Nelson
Description: Jerry Nelson was a prominent figure in the puppetry world, featuring his distinctive voice acting skills, puppet manipulation, and character creation abilities in his artistry. His work greatly influenced the field of puppetry.

Title: Richard Hunt
Description: Richard Hunt was notably recognized for his puppet performance, character development, and voice acting abilities. His contribution to the artistic medium of puppetry is highly appreciated within the puppeteering community.

Title: David Alfaro Siqueiros
Description: David Alfaro Siqueiros was an influential painter known for his vibrant, large-scale works in the Muralism art style. His work largely consisted of social realism and political art, making a significant impact on modern Mexican art.

Title: José Clemente Orozco
Description: José Clemente Orozco was a prominent painter in the Muralism movement. His artistry mainly explores symbolism and social realism, dominating large-scale compositions with an earthy color palette. Orozco's work held a major influence on twentieth-century Mexican art.

Title: Yuko Taguchi
Description: Yuko Taguchi is an esteemed producer, whose artistry is manifested in the medium of film production. Her style involves selecting and coordinating scenes to create impactful narratives. Her style sees influence from noteworthy artists like Kazuki Akane, Shinichiro Watanabe, and Mamoru Hosoda.

Title: Sequential Photography
Description: Sequential Photography is an art style where a sequence of images is captured to represent motion. This style is noted for its use of photographic medium, often employing natural light with an emphasis on portraying action and motion. Artists like Eadweard Muybridge and Harold Edgerton are significant contributors in this field.

Title: Animated Feature
Description: Animated Feature refers to a type of motion picture that is predominantly animated. The styles can vary from anime, CGI, to stop motion and the medium primarily used is animation. The environment typically includes imaginary worlds, moods can vary. Artists like Walt Disney, Hayao Miyazaki, and John Lasseter are renowned in this genre.

Title: Victorian Watercolor
Description: Victorian Watercolor refers to the art style that emerged during the Victorian era. It generally uses watercolor as the primary medium, and its environment often includes rural landscapes. The color scheme often employs vibrant colors, the mood is generally idealized and the compositions are often narrative. Artists such as John Ruskin and Dante Gabriel Rossetti are associated with this style.

Title: Watercolor Painting
Description: Watercolor Painting is a style that uses water-based paints on a paper canvas. It is associated with a variety of styles, such as Impressionism and Abstract. Watercolor paintings typically involve transparent colors, often set in plein air environments, and evoke various moods. The compositions are layered showcasing an overlap of colors. Artists like J.M.W. Turner and Paul Klee have extensively used this medium.

Title: Gaspard-Félix Tournachon (Nadar)
Description: Gaspard-Félix Tournachon, famously known as Nadar, was a prolific French photographer and has greatly contributed to the art styles of portraiture and aerial photography. His work mainly involved studio lighting and prominent use of the photographic medium. The compositions were largely portraits, often capturing the essence of the subject.

Title: Autobiographical Photography
Description: Autobiographical Photography refers to an art style that employs photography as a medium to chronicle the personal and intimate aspects of the artist's life. It's deeply personal in mood, often having a narrative composition.

Title: Realistic Manga
Description: Realistic Manga is an art style that strives to portray characters and stories in a realistic manner within the Manga medium. The mood is often serious, and everything is laid out in a storyboard composition.

Title: Shoujo Manga
Description: Shoujo Manga is a genre of manga intended for young girls that emphasizes romantic, relational, and emotional content. It usually uses a Panel Composition and revolves around a romantic mood.

Title: Realistic Painting
Description: Realistic Painting is an art style that seeks to represent subject matter truthfully without artificiality, avoiding artistic conventions or stylization. The composition is often realistic, mirroring the natural world as closely as possible.

Title: Yuki Midorikawa
Description: Yuki Midorikawa is renowned for her distinctive Shoujo Manga art style. She utilizes the Manga medium and is prominently associated with this style. Notable for her works, she puts emphasis on elegance, emotions, and sophistication.

Title: Classicism
Description: Classicism refers to the art style grounded in the principles of ancient Greek and Roman art. It prioritizes formality, balance, and restraint, often set against historic backgrounds. Colors are kept to a minimum and the composition is usually symmetrical. Pioneers include Jacques-Louis David and Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres.

Title: Traditionalism
Description: Traditionalism, as the name suggests, sticks to the traditional styles of art that include Impressionism, Realism, and Expressionism. This art is nostalgic in nature, often depicting cultural settings. The color schemes are vivid, the compositions orderly, and the lighting natural.

Title: Prehistoric
Description: The Prehistoric art style is confined to the stone age, primarily consisting of cave paintings and sculptures. It's characterized by crude, unstructured compositions and earthy color palettes. The environment is typically cave walls and due to lack of available information, the relevant artists are still unknown.

Title: Tribal
Description: Tribal art style is characteristic of the indigenous folklore and cultural heritage. It is rich with symbolic patterns and vibrant colors set against natural surroundings. The medium includes sculptures, body art, and textiles. Renowned artists of this art style include Ephe Olliver and John Mawurndjul.

Title: Spiritualism
Description: Spiritualism in art infuses supernatural, mysticism, and philosophy. This art style reaches beyond the physical world, represented by translucent colors, dreamy lighting, and ethereal compositions. Wassily Kandinsky and Hilma af Klint are among the prominent artists of spiritualist art.

Title: X-ray Photography
Description: X-ray Photography is a unique form of art where objects are photographed using x-ray technology. This creates an ethereal, almost alien-like perspective of commonplace subjects. The photography style offers a deep, intriguing insight into the inner structures of subjects that are usually hidden from the naked eye.

Title: Flower Painting
Description: Flower painting is a timeless genre of art often depicting serene and vibrant scenes. It allows artists to explore color, light, and composition, using the delicate and transient beauty of flora as a foundation. Various styles from Realism to Pop Art have been applied to express the unique beauty of flowers.

Title: Visual Pun
Description: Visual Pun is a type of art that uses images to create a pun or play on words. It's typically humorous, merging unrelated elements in a surprising and clever way. This style pushes the boundaries of imagination and challenges perceptions, encouraging viewers to reconsider the nature of everyday objects and symbols.

Title: High-Tech
Description: High-Tech art is a creative expression that heavily leverages modern technologies. From digital art to installation pieces, this style reflects the rapid advancements and global influence of technology. Artists in this genre often use neon colors, futuristic themes, and innovative interactions, transporting viewers into a digital realm.

Title: Sustainable Design
Description: Sustainable Design is an art style that champions eco-friendliness and sustainability. Artists in this genre creatively use recycled or natural materials, emphasizing the importance of conservation. Colours are often natural and earthy, mirroring the environmental themes. The artworks not only look beautiful but also serve as a profound commentary on environmental issues.

Title: Everyday Wear
Description: Everyday Wear is art style that focuses on clothing and apparel in a regular, everyday context. It often features minimalistic and uniformistic designs, reminiscent of the street art style. It is often depicted through life-like colors and in distinct physical forms like sculpture, offering realistic representation.

Title: Optical Illusion
Description: The optical illusion art style is a visual artistic twist that creates perception-based illusions tricking the viewer's mind into believing something that doesn't exist. It surfaces in abstract, op-art, and illusionism styles. The work usually consists of paintings set in surreal spaces with distorted perspectives.

Title: Trompe-l'oeil
Description: Trompe-l'oeil is a French term referring to the art of creating highly realistic imagery in paintings to give the optical illusion that depicted objects exist in three dimensions. The art style often involves a still life setting, aiming to trick the eye ('trompe l'oeil' means 'deceive the eye' in French).

Title: Illusionism
Description: Illusionism in art refers to the use of artistic techniques to create optical illusions, and ultimately, to make two-dimensional artworks seem three-dimensional. It's highly associated with painting and recurrently found in architectural spaces with artistic styles like Baroque and Mannerism.

Title: Japanese Manga
Description: Japanese Manga is an art style derived from the comic culture of Japan. It is depicted through various artistic styles - Shōnen, Shōjo and Seinen. The art medium is drawing, set in fictional realities, and the color scheme ranges from monochrome to colorful, based upon the style and genre.

Title: International Typographic Style
Description: The International Typographic Style (also known as Swiss Style) is a graphic design art style developed in Switzerland during the 1950s. Its main features include the use of a mathematically-derived grid system, clean and readable typography (like the Helvetica font), and an asymmetrical layout. The color scheme is often limited to monochrome.

Title: Middle Eastern Fashion
Description: Middle Eastern Fashion is characterized by the use of vibrant colors, intricate embroidery, and luxurious fabrics. It’s a cocktail of tradition and modernity, where artists work within cultural norms to create stunning and exotic designs. Notable designers in this art style include Elie Saab, Zuhair Murad, and Rami Al Ali.

Title: Savile Row Tailoring
Description: Savile Row Tailoring involves the art of customizing clothing, specifically suits, to fit the individual perfectly. The style is typically English, featuring neutral palettes, precise cuts, and a focus on minimalistic elegance. Esteemed artists in this style include Henry Poole, Huntsman, and Gieves & Hawkes.

Title: Miniature Painting
Description: Miniature Painting is an art form that presents intricate, detailed works often illustrating narrative scenes. Renowned across various cultures, these pieces feature vibrant colors and lighting that complements the precision of the details. Artists well-known in this style include Mani, Behzad, and Abu'l Hasan.

Title: Quilting
Description: Quilting is an art style that involves sewing together pieces of fabric to create a larger design. The often geometric composition may vary in complexity from simple patterns to intricate patchworks. The art is colorful and highly tactile. Artists notable in this style include Faith Ringgold, Nancy Crow, and Jean Ray Laury.

Title: Contemporary Landscape Painting
Description: Contemporary Landscape Painting is an art style that captures scenery such as mountains, valleys, trees, rivers, and forests with a current perspective. Professionals often use various techniques and styles including impressionistic, realistic, and abstract interpretations. Artists choose natural outdoor environments as their subjects, using multicolored pigments and natural light conditions to convey calm and composed emotions.

Title: Hatching
Description: Hatching is a drawing technique used to create tonal or shading effects by drawing closely spaced parallel lines. Often employed in monochromatic visual art representations, it's largely used in sketching, drawing, and realist styles. The composition primarily involves an arrangement of overlapping lines that vary in density and directionality.

Title: Crosshatching
Description: Crosshatching is a technique used in pencil drawing, ink sketching, and other similar art forms. It implies marking the paper with intersecting sets of lines to convey varying degrees of volume and depth. Largely featured in realism and illustration, it uses mostly monochromatic color schemes.

Title: Indian
Description: Indian art style is widely known for its richness, diversity and originality. It ranges from the ancient paintings of Ajanta to the miniature and Madhubani artworks of medieval era. Various forms of Indian art depict historical and spiritual scenes, often using vibrant colors. The mood expressed is highly spiritual and cultural.

Title: Lyrical Abstraction
Description: Lyrical Abstraction is an art movement that emerged in the 1960s, extending the post-war Abstract Expressionist movement. It emphasizes free, personal expression of emotion through non-representational abstract forms. The compositions involve layers of paint, creating a dense, lush visual experience. Artists use a wide spectrum of colors to evoke an emotional response.

Title: Natural History
Description: Natural History Art style amplifies details of nature and wildlife through detailed illustrations. These works often serve scientific and educational needs, portraying an inquisitive mood. Vibrant colors are prevalent, and the composition aims for accuracy and detail.

Title: Industrial Design
Description: Industrial Design art style focuses on usability and efficiency while retaining aesthetic appeal. Styles such as minimalism, futurism, and retro are common. The medium is often 3D modeling, with functional mood and geometric layout.

Title: Upcycling
Description: Upcycling Art Style creatively reuses discarded materials, making them into sculpture and decor. The mood and color scheme often depend on the source materials, resulting in an inventive and diverse collection of works.

Title: Instant Photography
Description: Instant Photography art style offers the ability to capture moments spontaneously, often resulting in candid compositions. This art style envokes a sense of authenticity and realness, making it popular for street and portrait photography.

Title: Popular Culture
Description: Popular Culture art style channels the current socio-cultural phenomena into creative expression. Often provocative and vibrant, this art style interacts with the audience using figures familiar to them, seen through mediums like pop art and contemporary art.

Title: Paper Engineering
Description: Paper Engineering art style involves the creation of artistic objects using paper as the primary medium. It can take on multiple forms, such as Origami, Paper Mache, or Kirigami, often showcasing geometric or abstract compositions. Notable artists include Matthew Shlian and Beatrice Coron.

Title: Low Key
Description: Low Key art style emphasizes dim or low lighting conditions, creating dramatic or mysterious moods. This technique is common in Chiaroscuro and Tenebrism art styles. Notable artists include Caravaggio and Rembrandt.

Title: High Key
Description: High Key art style features vibrant or high light settings, often in Impressionism and Post-Impressionism. The resulting works usually portray lively or joyful moods. Prominent artists include Claude Monet and Pierre-Auguste Renoir.

Title: Neo-impressionism
Description: Neo-impressionism is an art style marked by detailed, precise compositions and the use of vibrant colors. It includes sub-styles like Pointillism and Divisionism found in paintings. Notable artists include Georges Seurat, Paul Signac, and Camille Pissarro.

Title: Soft Lighting
Description: The Soft Lighting art style uses soft or diffuse lighting to create a serene or dreamy mood. This technique is often used in Impressionism, Romanticism, and Symbolism. Notable artists include Claude Monet and JMW Turner.

Title: Sunlight
Description: Sunlight art style is majorly seen in impressionist and realist paintings, capturing the play of natural light and shadows in an outdoor environment. Artists like Claude Monet and Pierre-Auguste Renoir have brilliantly depicted the warmth and euphoria of sunlight in their paintings with a realistic composition.

Title: Rembrandt Lighting
Description: Rembrandt Lighting art style is a technique often seen in Portrait Photography and Scene Lighting. It traditionally occurs in an indoor setting and utilizes artificial light to create a distinct chiaroscuro for dramatic effect. Renowned artists like Rembrandt Van Rijn and Johannes Vermeer are known for their exemplary use of this technique.

Title: Top Lighting
Description: The Top Lighting art style is notable in theatrical and cinematic works. This technique, which can be used in both indoor and outdoor environments, uses artificial light from an overhead source to create dramatic shadows. Prominent filmmakers like Orson Welles and Martin Scorsese have effectively used this style.

Title: Post-Modernism
Description: Post-Modernism art style is an evolution from Modernism, often seen in conjunction with Pop Art. Artists like Damien Hirst and David Salle have used mixed media to create fragmented compositions, challenging pre-existing thoughts about art and its purpose.

Title: Cave Art
Description: Cave Art is a style of Prehistoric Art often seen in the form of drawings inside caves. Made by Prehistoric Peoples, these earthen-colored, figurative compositions capture wildlife, rituals, and day-to-day activities.

Title: Prehistoric Art
Description: Prehistoric art provides an insight into early human life, reflecting its beliefs, daily habits, and environments. Most of this art style comprises rudimentary drawings of animals and humans, usually using natural pigments.

Title: Generative Art
Description: Generative art is characterized by the use of algorithms and computing technology to create art. The defining factor is that it's partly or completely generated by autonomous systems, often leading to unpredictable results and complex compositions.

Title: Algorithmic Art
Description: Algorithmic art is a subset of generative art where art pieces are primarily or entirely created using algorithmic processes. It covers a wide range of practices where mathematical algorithms play a central role in the generation of the artwork.

Title: Side View of the Subject
Description: The side view art style often emphasizes the subject's profile or view from the side. Common in portraiture as well as still life and wildlife art, it can bring a new perspective and focus on different characteristics of the subject.

Title: Agitprop
Description: Agitprop is a strongly political and propaganda-driven art style, characterized by its use of bold, simple, and high contrast compositions. It is often found in public spaces and aimed at conveying provocative messages or rallying for political causes.

Title: Nekromantix
Description: The Nekromantix's art style is characterized by their dark, Gothic, rockabilly, and horror punk vibes. The medium is usually reflected in their music album art and promotional material. The color scheme mostly features black and white, contributing to a gloomy and dark mood.

Title: The Meteors
Description: The Meteors' art style showcases a strong influence of the psychobilly and rockabilly genres. The vivid color palette of the band's album cover art reflects their vibrant and energetic moods.

Title: Tim Schafer
Description: Tim Schafer's art style in video game design leans towards the cartoonish and surreal, often set in imaginative fantasy environments. The composition is usually narrative-driven with a humorous mood.

Title: Scott Campbell
Description: Scott Campbell's art style consists of a mix of cartoonish and abstract styles. He primarily works in the medium of comics, generating whimsical moods through his sequential art.

Title: Raymond Chandler
Description: Raymond Chandler's art style relates to the hardboiled and detective noir genres of literature, which tend to depict crime and moral ambiguity in a gritty, realistic style.

Title: Hardboiled
Description: The Hardboiled art style is marked by its gritty mood, depicting crime and moral ambiguity with realism. Dashiell Hammett and Raymond Chandler are key authors associated with this genre.

Title: Dashiell Hammett
Description: Dashiell Hammett's art style is rooted in the hardboiled and detective noir genres, centering on crime and moral uncertainty with a bold, realistic approach.

Title: Woodburning
Description: The Woodburning art style often features sepia hues, with warm, earthy tones. It can use geometric compositions, blending art nouveau and naturalism styles in pieces created on a wooden medium.

Title: Fire-inspired
Description: Fire-inspired art style taps into the intensity, power, and red color that embodies fire, symbolic and expressive pieces that stir strong emotional responses thus aligning with styles like Expressionism and Symbolism.

Title: Ukrainian Folk Art
Description: Ukrainian Folk Art is a traditional art style heavily influenced by the country’s rich history and culture. Artists often use vibrant colors to depict joyful, rural settings. Noted artists include Maria Pryimachenko and Kateryna Vasylivna Bilokur. Art often includes pictorial compositions.

Title: Egg Decorating Art
Description: Egg Decorating Art, often associated with Easter and Spring celebrations, involves elaborate designs on eggshells. The art form takes many styles from various cultures, usually characterized by multi-colored geometric designs. It's a form of decorative art associated with festive moods.

Title: Abdullah Qajar
Description: Abdullah Qajar was an influential artist in the Qajar dynasty, known for his intricate oil portraits of royal court figures. Characterized by rich colors, soft lighting, and a regal mood, Qajar’s work is an integral part of Iranian and Persian Art.

Title: Kamal-ol-Molk
Description: Kamal-ol-Molk was a prominent artist in Persia, known for his mastery in Realism. His oil paintings primarily depict urban landscapes under natural light, often carrying a reflective mood. His work is a significant part of Persian art.

Title: Persian Art
Description: Persian Art, encompassing a rich variety of art forms from Iran, often depicts historical and spiritual themes. The art style is characterized by vibrant colors and figurative compositions, and renowned Persian artists include Hossein Behzad and Reza Abbasi.

Title: Traditional Chinese Painting
Description: Traditional Chinese Painting is an ancient fine art style, significant in Chinese culture capturing scenes of nature and life activities. The art emphasizes brushwork, ink, and the theme's spirit over strict realism. Landscape, Bird-and-Flower, and Figurative paintings are common variations.

Title: Chinese Traditional Fashion
Description: Chinese Traditional Fashion represents the rich and vibrant history of Chinese artistry. It includes styles such as Hanfu, Qipao, and Tangzhuang, with intricate designs and bold, vibrant colors. Notable designers include Guo Pei, Ma Ke, and Hu Sheguang.

Title: Cinematic Lighting
Description: The Cinematic Lighting art style focuses on creating mood, directing attention, and revealing character using high contrast and dramatic lighting effects. The technique often employs three-point lighting. Notable cinematographers practicing this style include Roger Deakins and Vittorio Storaro.

Title: Still Life Painting
Description: Still Life Painting is an art style that focuses on inanimate objects. Various sub-styles exist, such as realism and impressionism. The arrangement often exhibits symmetry and vibrantly colored objects. Notable artists include Paul Cézanne, Pablo Picasso, and Vincent van Gogh.

Title: New Media Art
Description: New Media Art, including Digital and Interactive Art and Virtual Reality, represents the intersection of art and technology, providing new ways for artists to express their innovation and engage audiences. Noteworthy artists include Nam June Paik, Marina Abramović, and Olafur Eliasson.

Title: RahXephon (Anime)
Description: RahXephon is an anime with a distinct art style employing Otaku and Manga art, created prominently by artists like Yutaka Izubuchi and Hiroshi Ousaka. The art is predominantly set in metropolitan environments, with a bright color scheme and layered composition, presenting a mystical mood.

Title: Gonzo Journalism
Description: Associated with Hunter S. Thompson and Ralph Steadman, the Gonzo Journalism art style is closely linked with Abstract Expressionism and Surrealism. Its characteristic feature is a nonlinear composition.

Title: Post-punk
Description: Post-punk art stands out with its bold color schemes, chaotic composition, and a rebellious mood. This style is observed on music album covers created by artists like Peter Saville and Jamie Reid. It often draws from Surrealism, Pop Art, and Abstract styles.

Title: Oceanic Art
Description: Oceanic art is a form of Tribal, Primitive, and Ethnographic styles, representative of cultures like the Malagan, Sepik, and Maori. This outdoor art primarily uses sculpture as a medium, with naturalistic colors, natural lighting, displaying a spiritual mood and detailed composition.

Title: Stop Motion Animation
Description: Stop Motion Animation, a significant part of film art, blends the art styles of Sculpture and Photography. Artists like Ray Harryhausen and Tim Burton use controlled lighting in a studio environment with a sequential composition, resulting in a varied color scheme and a whimsical mood.

Title: Fantasy Photography
Description: Fantasy Photography is an art style that involves the creation of stunning, surreal images. Often characterised by contrasting lights, vibrant colours and ethereal mood, it emphasizes the use of fantasy environments and storytelling composition. Influential artists include David LaChapelle and Annie Leibovitz.

Title: Neo-Mediterranean
Description: Neo-Mediterranean is an art style that blends elements of Classicism and Realism, often seen in painting. It utilizes earthy colors, natural lighting, and balanced compositions to portray tranquil moods within Mediterranean landscapes. Artists like Santiago Rusiñol and Joaquím Mir have contributed to this style.

Title: Underground Film
Description: Underground Film is an art style that veers towards the avant-garde and experimental. Films in this genre often feature non-linear storytelling, implemented in an urban setting with a low-key, often monochrome visual aesthetic. The mood tends to be rebellious, with prominent artists including Andy Warhol and Kenneth Anger.

Title: Site-specific Sculpture
Description: Site-specific Sculpture art style involves creating sculptures that are designed to harmonise with their surroundings. This style favours outdoor environments, natural lighting and color, and an immersive composition. Known for their environmental and land art, artists like Michael Heizer and Richard Serra have contributed significantly to this style.

Title: Optical Illusion Art
Description: Optical Illusion Art is a style that plays with perception to create intriguing visuals. It is commonly associated with Op Art and Abstract styles, and often involves contrasting lighting and monochromatic color schemes. Notable artists include M.C. Escher and Bridget Riley.

Title: Controversial Photography
Description: Controversial Photography deals with provocative and often divisive subjects, pushing boundaries of the societal norms. The style includes a variety of photographic genres, often highlighting political, sexual or moral issues. Notable artists include Robert Mapplethorpe and Sally Mann.

Title: Pulp Fiction Cover Art
Description: Pulp Fiction Cover Art applies to the visual style of printed covers for the cult classic Pulp Fiction. Featuring a retro and vibrant art style, such cover art typically exhibits bold colors and dynamic compositions. Noteworthy artists include John Dilnot and Frank Kozik.

Title: Baroque Revival
Description: Baroque Revival art style is a reflection of the ornate and overly decorated aesthetics of the Baroque period. It is most commonly seen in architecture, featuring rich colors, dramatic lighting, and complex compositions. Influential figures include Andre Le Notre and Francois Mansart.

Title: Glam Rock
Description: Glam Rock is a music style characterized by outrageous stage costumes, makeup, and dramatic spectacle. The visual art style incorporated in its representation often involves vibrant colors, experimental compositions, and extravagant mood. Iconic artists include David Bowie and Elton John.

Title: Cinematography
Description: Cinematography refers to the art of making motion pictures, with styles across a broad spectrum ranging from Film Noir to Italian Neorealism. Its visual styles vary in environment, lighting, color, and composition, depending on the story being told. Some of the notable cinematographers include Gregg Toland and Roger Deakins.

Title: Animalier
Description: Animalier refers to the art form originating in the 19th century, which focuses on the realistic portrayal of animals, based on the artists' detailed observations of their behavior and anatomy. The style captures accurate and vivid representations of animals in their natural environment. Notable Animalier sculptors include Antoine-Louis Barye, Pierre-Jules Mêne, and Christopher Fratin.

Title: Richard Linklater
Description: Richard Linklater is a renowned Director known for his distinctive Realist and Independent cinema style. His style is marked by an urban environment, natural lighting, contemplative moods, and long take compositions. Key contributors to his style are actors Julie Delpy, Ethan Hawke, and Patricia Arquette.

Title: Richard Williams
Description: Richard Williams is a distinguished Animator celebrated for his Traditional animation style. His work involves a range of moods and colors, with settings in fantasy environments and features diffused, soft lighting. Ken Harris, Art Babbitt, and Milt Kahl are other artists known in this area.

Title: Peach-Pit
Description: Peach-Pit is a Manga creator duo known for their distinctive Manga and Shōjo art style in the realm of graphic novels. Often employing dramatic moods, their work is primarily black-and-white and uses a panel-based composition. Artists Banri Sendo and Shibuko Ebara contribute significantly to this style.

Title: Youth Culture
Description: The 'Youth Culture' art style encompasses various art forms, including Pop Art and Graffiti, that reflect the societal values and sentiments of younger generations. Typically energetic and vibrant, these artworks often portray urban life in an eccentric composition. Artists like Keith Haring, Jean-Michel Basquiat, and Richard Hamilton are notably associated with this style.

Title: Immersion
Description: Immersion art, encompassing styles like Installation, Performance, and Digital Art, creates a multi-sensory, engaging environment that fully absorbs the audience into the artwork. Artists like Abramovic, Eliasson, and Turrell have pushed the boundaries of this medium.

Title: Audiovisual
Description: Audiovisual art, combining visual and sonic elements, results in forms like Video Art, Experimental Cinema, and Sound Art. It provides dynamic, temporal experiences. Renowned artists include Nam June Paik, Bill Viola, and Laurie Anderson.

Title: Nautical
Description: Nautical art involves artistic representation of the sea, ships, and the marine environment. Styles include Marine Painting, Naval Art, and Seascapes. It captures the adventurous mood with a dominant horizon and natural lighting. Aivazovsky, Turner, and Homer landmark this style.

Title: Neoplatonism
Description: Neoplatonism art, reflecting a philosophy of universal love and beauty, influenced art styles like Renaissance and Symbolist Art. It often conveyed transcendental moods through symmetrical compositions. Michelangelo, Botticelli, and Blake pivoted on Neoplatonic principles.

Title: Mythology
Description: In the realm of art, mythology contributes to styles such as Surrealism, Symbolist Art, and Romanticism. Its fantastical nature is relayed through paintings promoting narrative compositions. Artists like Moreau, Dali, and Williams used mythological themes prominently in their works.

Title: Structural Expressionism
Description: Structural Expressionism is a Modernist architectural style that emphasizes expressive, sculptural forms, bold geometric patterns, and innovative use of materials. Architecture in this style often gives a dramatic and dynamic mood while embracing the multi-color palette.

Title: Cinematic Realism
Description: Cinematic Realism is an artistic concept in film that heavily employs techniques endeavored to reproduce reality and to maintain narrative continuity. The environment, color schemes, and lighting conditions vary greatly, reflecting the real world.

Title: Dark Contemporary
Description: Dark Contemporary is a modern art style characterized by elements of Surrealism, Impressionism, and often Gothic aesthetics. Using dark tones and low light conditions, the artworks often depict melancholic and introspective themes.

Title: Diagrammatic
Description: The Diagrammatic art style is largely characterized by design-oriented drawings that emphasize on forms, symbols, and structures. It often lacks narrative, and mood is generally analytical or detached.

Title: Zoological Illustration
Description: Zoological Illustration art style is marked by meticulous and accurate depiction of animals in their natural environments. It is heavily characterized by highly detailed and realistic drawings, using natural colors. This art requires strong observational and analytical skills.

Title: Micro Photography
Description: Micro Photography art style, often called macro photography, is a genre of photography that involves capturing small subjects up close. With ample use of natural light, the style unveils detailed, textured compositions with the true color of subjects. Artists like John Hallmén, Paul Harcourt Davies, and Thomas Shahan are known for their work in this style.

Title: Detailed Art
Description: Detailed Art art style is characterized by meticulous attention to detail and intricate compositions. This hyper-realistic style is shown in various mediums, with painting being predominant. Renowned artists such as Leonardo da Vinci, Albrecht Dürer, and Johannes Vermeer have made iconic works in this style.

Title: Realistic Compositions
Description: Realistic Compositions art style incorporates a true-to-life representation of objects, with an emphasis on correct proportions. This style of art accurately and unexaggeratedly depicts life, often executed with meticulous detail. Artists such as Jean-Baptiste Greuze, Thomas Eakins, and Andrew Wyeth excel in creating realistic compositions.

Title: Textured Art
Description: The Textured Art art style stands out with its emphasis on tactile and visual textures. Often commonly seen in painting, this rough, and often layered, compositions convey depth, emotion, and can evoke a physical response. Artists like Pablo Picasso, Vincent Van Gogh, and Jackson Pollock are known for their remarkable textured art.

Title: Graphic Art
Description: Graphic Art is a digital art style characterized by its organized composition and often bold, purpose-driven visuals. Graphic Art can range from abstract to minimalistic, with graphical elements dominating the piece. Artists like Shepard Fairey, Banksy, and Andy Warhol are few among many influential figures of this style.

Title: Engraved Art
Description: An engraved art style leans heavily on detailed patterns and lines meticulously etched into materials like metal, wood, or bone. Famous engraved artworks are known for their astonishing detail, depth, and technical prowess.

Title: Ivory or Bone Carving
Description: Whether it's ivory or bone, Carving Art is a time-old discipline, creating detailed sculptures, reliefs, and figurines. Possible environments include historical or tribal settings, while artists create intricate 3D compositions.

Title: Mature Art
Description: Mature Art explores adult themes through a variety of styles, from Figurative to Expressionism. The mood can range from provocative to reflective, exploring with varied colors and realistic human forms within their compositions.

Title: Anime Art
Description: Anime Art is a popular style seen in Japanese animation, comprising styles like Manga, Chibi, and Shojo. It's often drawn or created digitally, set in fantasy worlds with high contrast lighting and vibrant colors. It's best known for its stylized characters.

Title: Lifelike With an Anime Touch
Description: Lifelike with an Anime touch is an artistic style that combines the anime aesthetic with a more realistic approach. It's often seen in portraiture and photorealistic art, with a mood that's lifelike, detailed compositions, and color emphasis on stylized eyes.

Title: Scandinavian Science Fiction Art
Description: Scandinavian Science Fiction art style often employs cutting edge technology, such as digital painting, to create futuristic landscapes and elements, often in a somewhat retro or vintage style. Lighting is mostly artificial, creating a subdued color scheme that aids the mysteriously contemplative mood. The composition tends to be symmetrical, adhering to the Scandinavian art principle of clean lines and minimalist design.

Title: Alexander Deineka
Description: Alexander Deineka was a Soviet painter associated with the Social Realist art style. His work often portrayed scenes of the industrial proletariat, cast in natural light and painted with a muted color palette. His paintings usually evoke a heroic mood, with figures positioned in balanced compositions.

Title: Vera Mukhina
Description: Vera Mukhina was a noted Soviet sculptor associated with the Socialist Realist style. Her monumental works, often displayed in public spaces, are created with a monochromatic color palette and bathed in natural light. Her sculptures usually convey an optimistic mood and are endowed with a dynamic composition.

Title: Sergei Gerasimov
Description: Sergei Gerasimov was a Soviet painter closely connected to the Social Realist movement. His works frequently depict rural landscapes under natural light, rendered in a detailed composition and a vibrant color palette. The mood of his paintings is often optimistic.

Title: Speculative Fiction
Description: Speculative Fiction art style corresponds to narrative genres speculating about worlds that are unlike the real world in various important ways. It includes fantasy and science fiction art, with artworks often being illustrations featuring futuristic or alternate realities. The mood is typically mystical, with complex compositions and a wide range of colors. Lighting conditions vary depending on the depicted scene.

Title: Ecological Design
Description: Ecological Design merges the principles of ecology with the art of design, focusing on a sustainable approach. Frequently seen in architecture and landscape architecture, it uses natural colors and is most commonly set in a natural environment.

Title: Militaristic Design
Description: Militaristic Design art style reflects military themes and warfare images. Often monochromatic and gritty, this design style is typically set on the battlefield and is frequently seen in historic war paintings.

Title: Traditional African Fashion
Description: Traditional African fashion employs bold, vibrant colors and geometric patterns, typically created as textiles. It is known for its afrocentric art style and ethnic fashion art influences, illuminated mostly by natural light.

Title: Nude
Description: Nude art style is a representation of the human form in its purest form, without clothing. Commonly seen in sculpture, this style is prevalent in both modern and renaissance art. The art typically depicts realistic moods with a primary focus on human anatomy.

Title: Indie
Description: The Indie art style is known for its alternative and lowbrow influences, often characterized by pale, muted colors. Images can be a bit dreamy and abstract, with most of the artwork done in digital format in an urban setting.

Title: Spiritual
Description: Spiritual art style is associated with abstract, symbolism, and surrealism genres. The medium used is mainly painting, set in an indoor environment with natural lighting. The color is vibrant, creating a serene mood. It often features non-objective compositions and is associated with artists such as Mark Rothko and Wassily Kandinsky.

Title: Geometric Patterns
Description: The Geometric Patterns art style is related to minimalism, art deco, and abstract. This style is often realized in the medium of digital art. The color scheme is usually monochrome, and its compositions often show symmetry. Artists such as Bridget Riley and Victor Vasarely are associated with this art style.

Title: Boris Iofan
Description: Boris Iofan, known for his Soviet modernism and Stalinist architecture, employed the medium of architecture in his work. His style relates closely to fellow architect Alexey Dushkin.

Title: Alexey Dushkin
Description: Alexey Dushkin's architectural works feature the styles of Soviet modernism and Stalinist architecture. His style is similar to that of the architect Boris Iofan.

Title: Soviet Modernism
Description: Soviet Modernism, including constructivism and Stalinist architecture, is an architectural style often associated with Boris Iofan and Alexey Dushkin. This style is defined by its utilitarian and austere characteristics.

Title: Authoritative
Description: The Authoritative art style often conveys a sense of power and dominance. It might make use of cubism or surrealism, with abstract geometric compositions in a monochrome color scheme. The environment is often set in urban spaces, with strong contrasting lighting to emphasize the authority. Famous artists like Pablo Picasso and Salvador Dali have works resonating with such authoritarian presence.

Title: Psychological Realism
Description: Psychological Realism is an art style focusing on representing the inner emotional states of the subjects rather than their outward appearance. It incorporates elements of Realism in terms of artistic style and often uses Symbolism to convey complex psychological themes. Artists like Ilya Repin and Ivan Kramskoi are renowned for their use of this style.

Title: Limited Color Palette
Description: Limited Color Palette is an art style characterized by the use of a restricted number of colors. The style emphasizes composition, shapes, and lines, and can be found in various art schools such as Minimalism, Color Field, and Surrealism. Notable artists include Piet Mondrian, Yves Klein, and Mark Rothko.

Title: Mesopotamian
Description: Mesopotamian art is a historical style representative of ancient civilizations like Babylonian, Assyrian, and Sumerian. It mainly consists of sculptures characterized by a hierarchical composition and an archaic mood. The artwork often depicts historical and societal scenes.

Title: Ink Painting
Description: Ink Painting is an art style prevalent in East Asian cultures, specifically in styles like Sumi-e, Shuimohua, and Calligraphy. The art, usually done in monochromatic black, involves a serene mood and an asymmetrical composition. Renowned artists include Wu Guanzhong, Qi Baishi, and Zhang Daqian.

Title: Japanese Traditional Art Style
Description: The Japanese Traditional Art Style encompasses various art schools such as Ukiyo-e, Kano School, and Nihonga. The style is distinguished by its use of painting as a medium, vibrant color palettes, serene moods, and flat, two-dimensional compositions. Notable artists include Hokusai, Hiroshige, and Katsushika Oi.

Title: Paper Marbling
Description: Paper Marbling is an art style known for creating random, ethereal patterns on paper. It is seen in forms like Ebru and Suminagashi. The essence of the art lies in its bright, multi-colored schemes, creating an aura of fluid, abstract beauty. Pioneering artists in this style are few due to the nature of the art form.

Title: Caledonia Curry (Swoon)
Description: Caledonia Curry, widely known as Swoon, presents an art style rooted in Urban Art and Street Art. Often produced with Mixed Media materials, her creations are synonymous with Urban environments, featuring dynamic Multicolor schemes. The mood of her works is Empowering, often utilizing the challenging technique of Collage composition.

Title: Electronic
Description: Electronic defines an art style that primarily belongs to Digital Art and New Media Art categories. Created using Digital mediums, they often exhibit Multicolor themes with an Abstract arrangement. Artists like Nam June Paik and Bill Viola have made significant contributions to this art style.

Title: Retrowave
Description: Retrowave is an art style falling under the umbrella of Pop Art and Abstract Art. It utilizes Digital media, is characteristic of Artificial settings, and typically features Fluorescent lighting and Neon color schemes. The style emits a Nostalgic mood, underscored by Geometric compositions. Well-known artists of this style include Beeple and James White.

Title: Neon
Description: Neon is an art style known for its vibrant use of Fluorescent Neon colors. Falling under the Pop Art and Digital Art styles, Neon art applies the Medium of Light and Space and is often set in Artificial environments. The art style typically presents Geometric compositions and has prominent artists such as Dan Flavin and James Turrell.

Title: Neo-Gekiga
Description: Neo-Gekiga is a stylistic evolution in Manga Art, also associated with Contemporary Art. Drawings serve as the primary medium of Neo-Gekiga artists, portraying Urban environments in a Monochrome color scheme. Featuring Gritty lighting and Dramatic moods, the art style is narrative in its arrangement. Artists like Tatsumi Yoshihiro and Tsuge Tadao significantly contributed to this art style.

Title: Japanese New Wave
Description: Japanese New Wave is a cinematic art style that emerged in the 1960s. It's characterized by its modernism, realism, and innovative composition. This art style typically explores themes of political resistance and social commentary, often set in an urban Japanese environment.

Title: Extreme Cinema
Description: Extreme Cinema is an art style grounded in films that push boundaries, often encompassing sub-genres like horror, gore, and exploitation. This style is characterized by shocking, graphic content, and a highly contrasting color scheme.

Title: Superflat
Description: Superflat is a postmodern art movement inspired by Japanese pop culture elements like anime and manga. It's characterized by its flat, bright colors, digital medium, and a predominantly surreal mood.

Title: Contemporary Pop Art
Description: Contemporary Pop Art is a modern interpretation of the Pop Art movement. It blends traditional Pop Art aesthetics with a postmodern twist, often incorporating ironic and playful themes while being painted in vibrant colors.

Title: Decadent Art
Description: Decadent Art is an art style rooted in the late 19th-century Decadent movement. It's often characterized by the entwinement of beauty and decay, with complex compositions, rich colors, and a predominantly melancholic mood.

Title: Sports
Description: Sports art captures the dynamic and energetic scenarios associated with physical activities. Art styles often used for this concept range from Impressionism to Realism, expressing the fluidity and motion of sports. The color schemes are typically vibrant to reflect the energetic environment, and compositions are dynamic to depict the continuous movement.

Title: Yakuza Film
Description: Yakuza Film's art style is often defined by Noir and Neo-noir, portraying the dark and gritty underworld of crime. The environment is usually urban, with low-key lighting creating a shadowy, mysterious aesthetic. The mood is tense, often using a monochromatic scheme for a stark composition that emphasizes raw emotions.

Title: Black Comedy
Description: Black Comedy art style often employs elements of Absurdism and Irony. Films are set in both indoor and outdoor settings with contrasting lighting and sparse color usage. The mood is generally sardonic, using incongruous compositions to portray humor resulting from grim or challenging circumstances.

Title: Chinese
Description: Chinese art style is profoundly influenced by traditional values and philosophies. Art styles such as 'Ink and wash painting', 'Calligraphy' and 'Shan shui' often dominate, using subtle colors to create harmonious and balanced compositions. The artwork embodies the belief of unity between humans and nature, symbolizing the Chinese culture richly.

Title: Brazilian
Description: Brazilian art style vibrantly reflects its colorful, diverse culture. Drawing inspiration from Modernism, Constructivism, and Tropicalismo, artists often work in a variety of mediums, including sculpture. The art is set in natural environments using bright colors, typically portraying a joyful mood. The compositions are diverse, illustrating the multifaceted nature of Brazilian life.

Title: Traditional
Description: Traditional art, often referenced as Classical or Realism, primarily focuses on the realistic and detailed portrayal of subjects. Various mediums and color schemes may be used, with the composition generally being figurative.

Title: African
Description: African art, recognized by its Tribal or Abstract styling, leverages a variety of mediums in creating pieces. Its vibrant mood is often set in natural environments, with common geometric compositions that speak to the cultural significance of symmetry.

Title: Cultural
Description: Cultural art styles such as Impressionism, Surrealism, and Cubism reflect different cultures and eras. Renowned artists like Claude Monet, Salvador Dalí, and Pablo Picasso have used various mediums to create pieces that exhibit the values, beliefs, and ideals of particular cultures.

Title: Mathematician
Description: In Mathematics-inspired art, a strong emphasis on geometric structures and patterns is evident. The art style usually comprises well-systematized, patterned compositions that illustrate mathematical concepts. The medium often used is drawing, creating a well-structured, precise representation of the themes.

Title: Fractal Art
Description: Fractal Art is a form of algorithmic art, created by calculating fractal objects and represented as digital art. It’s recognized for its colorful palette, elaborate, psychedelic patterns, and elegant geometric structures. The style often connects with the realm of Mathematics and can be described as complex yet harmonious, often embodying elegance. This style of art is associated with artists like Takeshi Obata.

Title: Comic
Description: Comic Art uses sequential visual art to convey stories. Typically rendered via drawing, this art style can vary in color and lighting, capturing a wide range of moods, though often associated with humor. Framing and illustration techniques directly influence the storytelling aspect. Takeshi Obata is among the famous artists in Comic Art.

Title: Coffee
Description: Coffee art style revolves around using coffee as a medium for creating artistic representations. This can range from latte art, coffee ground art, to using brewed coffee as a type of paint. The style exhibits shades of brown, predominantly. Some renowned artists in this sphere include Jon Norquist, Dirceu Veiga, and Karen Eland.

Title: Whimsical Art
Description: Whimsical art is a playful and cheeky art style that often portrays scenes of whimsy, fantasy, and exuberance. This art style can be seen in various mediums, but are commonly found in paintings. The environment is often fantastical, bringing life to the extraordinary and the unreal. It embraces an array of bright colors and cheerful moods, creating a rich, vibrant visual style. The compositions can be irregular, adding to the playfulness and eccentricity. Known artists in this domain include Diego M. Rodriguez, Carlos Lujan, and Mugrshots.com.

Title: Profile
Description: Profile art style displays the side view of the subject, usually in drawing medium. Egyptian Art, Profile Portraiture, and Silhouette Art express this method of representation. Artists like Edgar Degas and John Flaxman have used this style in their works.

Title: Frontal
Description: The 'frontal' style is a frequent concept mostly observed in Manga and Anime artworks. This style is heavily adopted to craft comics in a two-dimensional composition. Artists such as Yuki Urushibara, Hiroshi Nagahama, Toshio Masuda, and Ikuo Kuwana have predominantly used this methodology in their creations.

Title: Psychadelic
Description: Psychedelic art style evokes forms and colors suggestive of the altered states of consciousness induced by psychedelic substances. It's distinguishable by complex patterns, vivid colors, convoluted compositions, and surreal mood. It has heavily influenced the works of artists like Peter Max, Pablo Amaringo, and more.

Title: Ukrainian Folk
Description: Ukrainian Folk art style is a traditional Ukrainian art form, characterized by its vibrant colors, figurative compositions, and joyful mood. Notable Ukrainian folk artists include Maria Pryimachenko and Kateryna Bilokur.

Title: Egg Decorating
Description: Egg Decorating is a unique art form involving the decoration of eggs, often with intricate designs. The art medium engaged is 3D and the environment is usually indoor. Fabergé, Picasso, and Christel Assante are among the well-known artists associated with this style.

Title: Production Studio
Description: A Production Studio art style depicts the creation of art in a studio environment. It can include a variety of styles, from digital to multimedia. Renowned artists associated with this concept include Walt Disney, Hayao Miyazaki, and others.

Title: Neo-traditional
Description: Neo-traditional art form is a modern take on traditional styles, especially in tattoos. It incorporates the bold lines and classic symbols of traditional tattoos but with a modern twist. Along with the use of vibrant colors, it often takes inspiration from various art styles like American traditional, Japanese, New School, Floral, and Folk.

Title: Art Collective
Description: With a focus on collaborative efforts, Art Collectives feature interdisciplinary artists who produce work in varied styles engaging a range of mediums. Often Contemporary and occasionally interventionist, the art features shared authorship. Not restricted to a physical studio, the environments range from galleries to public spaces.

Title: Engineering
Description: A distinctive style that melds artistic creativity and scientific principles, Engineering Art represents a fusion of Architectural, Geometric, and Digital styles. The style mainly manifests in structural sculptures, often using metallic color schemes to demonstrate industrial themes.

Title: Biomechanical
Description: In the Biomechanical art style, organic forms are combined with machinery, often depicted in dark, muted tones. Influenced by Surrealist and Gothic elements, the style explores themes of otherworldliness via a unique fusion of the biological and the mechanical. The result is stunningly alien and eerily beautiful.

Title: Nanga
Description: Nanga, also known as Bunjinga, refers to a traditional Japanese art style of 'literati painting'. Originating from Chinese literati painters, Nanga artists typically painted landscapes, flora and fauna with subdued colors elevating themes of simplicity, solitude, and mindful interaction with nature. Well-known Nanga artists include Ike no Taiga and Yosa Buson.

Title: Edo Period
Description: The Edo period, a pivotal era in Japanese history, ushered in a rich tapestry of artistic styles that characterized life in urban areas. Ukiyo-e, Bijin-ga, and Shunga are examples of prominent art styles from this period. Art was typically executed in a medium of woodblock prints, reflected a structured composition, and depicted vibrant and dynamic moods. Hokusai and Utamaro are among the notable artists of this era.

Title: Linoleum Block
Description: Linoleum block refers to an art style rooted in printmaking techniques known as Lino cutting, a variant of woodcut in printmaking. The medium involves carving into a linoleum surface which is then inked and used to print onto paper or fabric. It usually employs a monochromatic color scheme and boasts bold compositions. Famous artists such as Pablo Picasso and Henri Matisse worked with this medium.

Title: Knotting
Description: Knotting, a versatile art form utilized in various cultures, primarily involves creating intricate designs through the tying of knots. Macrame and Celtic knotwork are some popular styles within this category. The medium typically involves thread, rope, or string, presenting a relaxed mood and featuring interlaced compositions. Prominent artists in this medium are Bonnie Meltzer and Emily Katz.

Title: Pen
Description: Pen art uses ink as its medium and primarily involves styles like calligraphy and ink drawing. This form of art often has a monochromatic color scheme and is characterized by a focus on detail in its composition. The atmosphere and mood of pen art can heavily depend on the artist's line work and overall style. Albrecht Dürer and Leonardo da Vinci are among the significant figures known to use the pen medium.

Title: Charles Frederick Worth
Description: Charles Frederick Worth, known as the 'father of haute couture,' is renowned for his Victorian and Belle Époque influenced artworks characterized by extravagance and elegance. The medium of his art is primarily fashion. His design concepts laid the foundation for other artists like Gabrielle Chanel, Elsa Schiaparelli, and Christian Dior.

Title: Paul Poiret
Description: Paul Poiret was a prominent fashion designer who introduced the Art Nouveau, Art Deco, and Modernist style to his designs. Working primarily in the medium of fashion, Poiret's influence encompasses artists like Madeleine Vionnet, Jeanne Lanvin, and Coco Chanel.

Title: Katsuhiro Harada
Description: Katsuhiro Harada, a game designer is appreciated for his Anime, Manga, and Digital art styles, often set within fantasized environments. Famously known for his work in the Tekken series, his art forms have inspired other game designers like Hideo Kojima, Shigeru Miyamoto, and Suda51.

Title: Yoshinori Ono
Description: Influential game designer, Yoshinori Ono has developed an unique art style, incorporating elements of Anime, Manga, and Digital Art in fantasy environments. His deep-rooted influence in the gaming industry is seen in the works of designers like Katsuhiro Harada, Hideo Kojima, and Hideki Kamiya.

Title: Kazumasa Kojima
Description: Kazumasa Kojima's bold artistic style blends elements of Anime and Manga in his illustrations. As an animator, his unique approach to his medium has influenced other artists like Shinya Ohira, Yoh Yoshinari, and Inio Asano.

Title: Fighting Game
Description: The Fighting Game art style is often a blend of manga, anime, and cinematic realism. It's typically presented through digital art, with a vibrant color scheme set in dynamic battle arenas. The compositions frequently depict dynamic action scenes. Renowned artists like Yoshinori Ono, Harada Katsuhiro, and Hiroshi Matsuyama have greatly contributed to this art style.

Title: Michael Arias
Description: Michael Arias' art style bridges anime, CGI, and cinematic realism. He creates in the medium of animation which often features detailed color grading set against urban landscapes. His compositions emphasize detailed cinematography.

Title: Kiyoshi Kurosawa
Description: Kiyoshi Kurosawa's art style falls under horror, drama, and thriller genres. His work presented in film often showcases urban dystopian environments with low-key lighting, creating an unsettling mood. His compositions are well-known for their slow-burn narratives.

Title: Susumu Taira
Description: Susumu Taira's art style gravitates towards portrait photography with a touch of realism. His medium is photography, typically using natural lighting. The composition often contains up-close portraitures.

Title: Photographers
Description: Photographers' art style can run the gamut from documentary and fine art to commercial photography. The medium, lighting, and composition can greatly vary depending on the photographer and their subjects. Renowned artists like Annie Leibovitz, Robert Capa, and Henri Cartier-Bresson have significantly influenced this field.

Title: Cinematographers
Description: Cinematographers, or directors of photography, are the artists behind the visual aesthetics of a film. Utilizing cinematography techniques, they capture the mood, theme, and narrative of the film. Styles range from the high contrast, dramatic lighting of Film Noir to the naturalistic approach of Italian Neo-realism. Notable cinematographers include Gregg Toland and Christopher Doyle.

Title: Temari Artisans
Description: Temari, a traditional Japanese folk art, is practiced by Temari artisans. It involves crafting intricate, brightly colored, geometric designs on handball-sized spheres using thread. The art form is considered a symbol of friendship, loyalty and deep wish. Notable exponent of this art is Fujino Hide.

Title: Japanese Embroidery
Description: Japanese Embroidery is a centuries-old art form practiced by highly skilled artisans. It demands precision and mastery, often incorporating symbolic motifs drawn from nature, Buddhism and Shinto religion. This art form showcases highly detailed needlework artistry, and radiates calmness and tranquility. Naito Toyoko and Kurenai-kai are among the renowned artists.

Title: Botticelli
Description: Sandro Botticelli, an Italian painter of the Early Renaissance, is noted for his mythological and religious works distinguished by his graceful linearity and flowing compositions. His works are considered embodiment of the intellectual and artistic ferment of Florence. Leonardo da Vinci is another genius of the era.

Title: R.K. Post
Description: R.K. Post, a renowned fantasy illustrator, has a distinctly gritty and edgy style combined with high level of detail. His works revolve around fantasy worlds, ranging from luminescent and whimsical to dark and eerie. Clyde Caldwell and Larry Elmore are other known fantasy illustrators.

Title: Greek Sculptors
Description: Greek Sculptors' work, often in marble, focused on the human form and Gods, utilizing a naturalistic style. Famous Greek sculptors include Praxiteles, Phidias, and Myron.

Title: Chinese Sculptors
Description: Chinese sculptors are known for symbolic works, often in terra cotta. The most famous example of their work is the Terra Cotta Warriors, made by unidentified artists in the Qin dynasty.

Title: Mayan Sculptors
Description: Mayan sculptors carved intricate works in stone, often including hieroglyphics and representational art. Notable methods include Stelae, Lintels, and Altars.

Title: Ancient Art
Description: Ancient art covers all creations dating from prehistory to the early Middle Ages. Various mediums were used such as stone, clay and papyrus, often in a symbolic style.

Title: Impressionistic
Description: Impressionism is an art style focused on capturing the fleeting effects of light on scenery. It's characterized by loose brushwork and vivid colors. Notable artists include Claude Monet, Edgar Degas, and Pierre-Auguste Renoir.

Title: Poetic
Description: Poetic art style often captures emotions, feelings, and visual expressions in an interpretation that may seem abstract but largely emotive. It's closely linked to styles such as Surrealism, Romanticism, Abstract Expressionism, and Impressionism, which look to bend or liberate the visual interpretation from traditional norms.

Title: Absurd
Description: The absurd art style is often equated with movements like Dadaism and Surrealism, challenging the boundaries of rationality and norm. Artists sculpt such pieces in provocative or nonsensical manners that unsettle viewers or provoke thought, displaying a chaotic composition.

Title: Controversial
Description: Controversial art style often challenges social norms, political views, or established perceptions. Modernism, Conceptual Art, and Dadaism have been associated with this style for their thought-provoking installations and presentations using a blend of mediums.

Title: Dark Comedy
Description: Dark comedy art style uses satirical compositions to voice dark or ironic humor visually. Artists utilize art styles such as Pop Art, Lowbrow, and Conceptual Art, often incorporating a monochromatic color scheme to create stark, sardonic artwork.

Title: Romance
Description: Romance art style often deals with passion, love, beauty, and desire, explored through styles like Rococo, Baroque, and Pre-Raphaelite. These pieces display intimate compositions, dense with symbols of love and sensuality.

Title: Kinetic Sculpture
Description: Kinetic Sculpture is an art style based on sculpture, that lends itself to outdoor settings. It is related to styles including Abstract, Modern, Contemporary, Constructivism and Futurism. The style, innovative in mood, is defined by the principle of movement in the composition of the work. Renowned artists involved in this style include Alexander Calder and Jean Tinguely.

Title: Biomimicry
Description: Biomimicry is an art style inspired by nature, incorporating natural elements and designs into artworks. These works, ware often made using various mediums and are associated with Sustainable, Eco-Art, Land, Environmental and Bio Art styles. Artists who have utilized Biomimicry include Janine Benyus and Ross Lovegrove.

Title: Thermal Imaging
Description: Thermal Imaging is an artistry technique where images are created based on detected radiations, usually mapping temperature variances. Often found in modern and contemporary art styles, these works can be created virtually anywhere. This style makes use of infrared lighting, a heat map color scheme to deliver a scientific mood through infrared imagery composition. Prominent artists like Richard Mosse and Donna Ong have used this technique.

Title: Painter of Light
Description: 'Painter of Light' is a term used to describe artists whose work is characterized by luminous effects and serene moods. This style of painting has roots in several related art movements, including Impressionism, Luminism, Romanticism, Baroque, and Realism. The artworks typically depict landscapes, seascapes, and cityscapes. Renowned 'Painters of Light' include Thomas Kinkade and J.M.W. Turner.

Title: Keith Loutit
Description: Keith Loutit is a photographer known for his time-lapse photography and cinemagraph techniques, often depicting cityscapes. His style can be associated with Contemporary, Landscape Photography, Documentary Photography, Time-Lapse Photography, and Cinemagraph Art Styles. His works often feature natural lighting and a peculiar distorted perspective that adds a melancholic mood. Other artists in this domain include Samuel Orr and Terje Sorgjerd.

Title: Oliver Curtis
Description: Oliver Curtis is known for his distinct photography art style. His works often encompass various locations, capturing their essence through his lens. Utilizing natural light to portray his subjects, Curtis typically employs eye-level shots, offering a grounded and intimate perspective to viewers.

Title: Ben Thomas
Description: Ben Thomas is a renowned photographer, noted for his urban photography. He generally showcases vibrant color schemes in his work. His compositions emphasize wide-angle shots of urban spaces, incorporating varying lighting situations to enhance the visual interest and vitality of his images.

Title: Animal Photography
Description: Animal Photography is a field of art that focuses on photographing animals in their natural environment. Often utilizing natural light and deriving from art styles like wildlife and pet photography, it consists of compositions that use eye-level shots to bring the viewer closer to the perspective of the subject.

Title: Vintage Photography
Description: Vintage Photography is an art style featuring visual aesthetics from the past. Captured through photography medium, it commonly entails the use of a soft light, classic compositions, and a predominantly sepia tone or monochrome color scheme, all resonating with the retro feel.

Title: Action Cinema
Description: Action Cinema is an art style in film that features intense sequences of movement and agility. The style varies from stylized to realistic action, usually characterized by fast-paced shots. Action Cinema often showcases varying environments and employs dramatic lighting to enhance the intensity of the scenes.

Title: Critical Regionalism
Description: Critical Regionalism is an architectural style that advocates for the balance between global and local influence in architecture. It emphasizes a thoughtful and contextual approach to building design, often involving locally sourced materials and traditional construction methods.

Title: Architectural Design
Description: Architectural Design refers to the concept and plan behind the construction and design of buildings and structures. It involves solving complex issues like contextual site, function, and form, while also taking aesthetic considerations into account.

Title: Chinese Architecture
Description: Chinese Architecture is an architectural style that can be traced back to more than two thousand years. It involves a variety of architectural structures such as towers, palaces, and gardens, all carrying deep historical, cultural, and philosophical meanings.

Title: Imperial Architecture
Description: Imperial Architecture is a style seen in historical Chinese architectures, specifically those that were built for the emperors. It often features central symmetry, emphasizing the cosmic balance in the universe, with extensive use of the color red, indicating good fortune and happiness.

Title: Feng Shui Architecture
Description: Feng Shui Architecture is an ancient Chinese system of designing buildings in accordance with the laws of cosmos and environment. It aims to achieve harmony with natural forces, and influence prosperity, health, and happiness.

Title: Japanese Architecture
Description: Japanese Architecture is recognized by its harmony with nature. The structures often feature natural materials, predominantly wood, and maintain a balance between interior and exterior spaces through the use of sliding doors, gardens, and courtyards.

Title: Shinto Architecture
Description: Shinto Architecture is the building style of Shinto shrines in Japan, characterized by simplicity and the use of natural materials. It often features a straight roofline, wooden structure, and vermilion color. The style values symmetry and the principle of balancing elements.

Title: Buddhist Architecture
Description: Buddhist Architecture originated in India and took on different forms as it spread across Asia. The styles vary but often feature towers or domes, and incorporate traditional religious symbols. Common elements include the use of geometric shapes, and a color palette that includes a lot of gold.

Title: Korean Architecture
Description: Korean Architecture, known for its 'hanok' houses and grand palaces, features curved roofs, raised floors and layouts planned in accordance to the land and the seasons.
